The standard circulating coinage of the United Kingdom , British Crown Dependencies and British Overseas Territories is denominated in pounds sterling. Since 2008, the one-pound coin has been the lowest value coin in the pound sterling, having replaced the one penny piece, which until 1984 was the lowest value coin in the currency system. In 1997 the United Kingdom, with the consent of the other 11 British Crown dependencies and British overseas territories, introduced a new design of circulating pound coin. These coins are the responsibility of Her Majesty's Treasury .

Year 1532 (MDXXXII) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 22 – São Vicente is established as the first permanent Portuguese settlement in Brazil. March 18 – The English Parliament bans payment by the English Church to Rome. April – Battle of Quipaipan in Peru: Atahualpa wins the civil war in the Inca Empire, defeating his brother Huáscar. May 13 – Francisco Pizarro lands on the northern coast of Peru. May 16 – Sir Thomas More resigns as Lord Chancellor of England.

Heinrich Christian Wilhelm Busch (15 April 1832 – 9 January 1908) was a German humorist, poet, illustrator, and painter. He published wildly innovative illustrated tales that remain influential to this day.Busch drew on the tropes of folk humour as well as a profound knowledge of German literature and art to satirize contemporary life, any kind of piety, Catholicism, Philistinism, religious morality, bigotry, and moral uplift.His mastery of drawing and verse became deeply influential for future generations of comic artists and vernacular poets. Among many notable influences, The Katzenjammer Kids was inspired by Busch's Max and Moritz.

Nature versus nurture is a long-standing debate in biology about the balance between two competing factors which determine fate : our genes (nature) versus the external environment (nurture). As a rule of thumb, the answer to the debate is that nature and nurture together shape our biological and psychological traits, but neither alone is enough to explain the whole story, or to account for the variety of traits we see among humans. However, a recent paper published this week in Science reports on an experiment that appears to challenge this rule.

Year 1456 (MCDLVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 18 – Second Battle of Oronichea (1456): Ottoman Forces of 15,000 are sent to capture Albania, but are met and swiftly defeated by Skanderbeg's smaller forces. June 9  – Halley's Comet makes an appearance, as noted by the humanist scholar Platina. July 7 – A retrial of Joan of Arc acquits her of heresy, 25 years after her execution. July 22 – Battle of Nándorfehérvár (Belgrade): The Hungarians under John Hunyadi rout the Turkish army of Sultan Mehmed II.

Photomontage is the process and the result of making a composite photograph by cutting , gluing , rearranging and overlapping two or more existing photographs to form a combined picture or picture. It is a very complex process that requires skills, dedication, knowledge, and talent. In this work the technique of montage photography was used to give the viewer of the image the opportunity to see the same subject from two different viewpoints and also from different angles. This series is called “Ruin & Recycling” where it show the aftermath of war in many countries. Photograph of an abandoned building.

Optical rotation, also known as polarization rotation or circular birefringence, is the rotation of the orientation of the plane of polarization about the optical axis of linearly polarized light as it travels through certain materials. Circular birefringence and circular dichroism are the manifestations of optical activity. Optical activity occurs only in chiral materials, those lacking microscopic mirror symmetry. Unlike other sources of birefringence which alter a beam's state of polarization, optical activity can be observed in fluids. This can include gases or solutions of chiral molecules such as sugars, molecules with helical secondary structure such as some proteins, and also chiral liquid crystals.

Year 1020 ( MXX ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This article describes the events of the year 1020 throughout the world. It was the first year of the 2nd millennium, the 20th year of the 10th century, and the 1st year of the 10th decade. Year 2005 is a common year starting on Saturday, the 2005th year of the Common Era. Year 1020 (MXX) was a leap year starting on Friday of the Julian calendar.

Year 1446 ( MCDXLVI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Treaty of Brétigny is signed in Troyes in France, ending the 100 Years War. The English King, Henry VI of England, is captured in the Battle of Northampton, but is soon restored to his throne. The Duke of Bedford is appointed regent in France. February 23 - The Council of Constance, the 16th Ecumenical Council of the Catholic Church, convened by Papal Bull of Martin V, begins in Konstanz in the German state of Baden-Württemberg.

Year 1486 ( MCDLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full Julian calendar ). January 21 – Pope Sixtus IV is elected. The Portuguese fleet of Vasco da Gama returns to Lisbon after a voyage of discovery to India. Kemal Reis arrives back in Algiers, after exploring and charting the Mediterranean coast of Africa, from Tunisia to present-day Libya, a voyage that takes 7 years, and in which Reis's fleet includes the carrack Santa Clara de Assisi, one of only two surviving examples of this kind of ship from this era.

Year 1361 ( MCCCLXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. April–May – Invasion of Korea: Goryeo general Yi Seong-gye leads a rebellion and founds the Joseon Dynasty, which rules Korea (with interruptions) for more than five centuries. August 25 – The Battle of Winwaed between the forces of England and a Welsh army under Llywelyn ap Gruffudd and Owain Glyn Dŵr takes place near Wakefield in Yorkshire in the English county of Yorkshire. It is the first pitched battle between the English longbowman and the Welsh bowman of this period.

Mary Virginia Martin (December 1, 1913 – November 3, 1990) was an American actress and singer. A muse of Rodgers and Hammerstein, she originated many leading roles on stage over her career, including Nellie Forbush in South Pacific (1949), the title character in Peter Pan (1954), and Maria von Trapp in The Sound of Music (1959). She was named a Kennedy Center Honoree in 1989. She was the mother of actor Larry Hagman.Early life Martin was born in Weatherford, Texas. Her autobiography described her childhood as secure and happy.

A lever ( or ) is a simple machine consisting of a beam or rigid rod pivoted at a fixed hinge, or fulcrum. It converts the applied force into a greater torque by changing the direction of this force by a certain mechanical advantage (a "multiplier"). There are two basic types of levers: the first, the fixed-length lever, and the second the moved-pivot lever, also known as the movable-arm or compound lever. In each case, the fulcrum, the object that remains stationary, lies between the effort applied to one end and the torque exerted by the other end.

Year 1363 ( MCCCLXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year the ruling Ottoman Sultan Bayezid I annexed the last of the Christian Byzantine territories of Thessaly and Macedonia thus completing what is seen by many historians as the Ottoman conquest of Anatolia. The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state's military forces. The governor has a duty to enforce state laws, the power to either approve or veto bills passed by the Montana State Legislature, to convene the legislature at any time, and to grant pardons and reprieves.The current Montana Constitution, ratified in 1972, calls for a 4-year term for the governor, commencing on the first Monday in January following an election. The governor is term-limited to 8 years in any 16-year period. The constitution provides for the election of a lieutenant governor for the same term as the governor.

Georg Hackl (often named: Hackl Schorsch, ; born 9 September 1966) is a German former luger who was three time Olympic and World Champion. He is known affectionately as Hackl-Schorsch or as the Speeding Weißwurst a reference to what he looks like in his white bodysuit coming down the luge at fast speeds.BiographyHackl was born in Berchtesgaden, Bavaria. He took up luge as part of his physical education lessons whilst at school, learning to slide at the Königssee track.Hackl was known for his rivalry with Markus Prock, with Prock being dominant in World Cup competition whilst Hackl consistently achieved success at the Winter Olympics.

Pearl Harbour is a small harbour at the head of the Waiau River , in the town of Manapouri on New Zealand’s South Island . It is located near the mouth of the Dart River . It is named after James Pearl , who had a farm in the area in the 1880s. The area was first visited by Europeans in 1862 by Captain William Warr, who was surveying the area for the New Zealand government, which was interested in its potential for whaling . In 1863, the whaling ship Pioneer and its crew of 10 men and 1 woman, the first European residents, settled at the harbor.

A business plan is a formal written document containing the goals of a business , the methods for attaining those goals, and the requirements of the business as well. Business plans are used by business people to convince other people to purchase a product or service from the company. They are also used to secure a loan or a bank for a loan to expand or purchase equipment. There are four basic sections of a business plan
1. Executive summary: The executive summary of the business plan is a one-page or two-page overview of the whole plan.

Year 1329 (MCCCXXIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  February 1 – King John of Bohemia (of the Teutonic Order) captures Medvėgalis, an important fortress of the pagan Grand Duchy of Lithuania, and baptizes 6,000 of its defenders. February 18 – Amda Seyon I, Emperor of Ethiopia, begins his campaigns in the southern Muslim provinces (possibly in 1332). March 27 – Pope John XXII condemns some teachings of Meister Eckhart as heretical. April – Antipope Nicholas V is excommunicated by Pope John XXII.

Year 1235 (MCCXXXV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  Connacht in Ireland is finally conquered by the Hiberno-Norman Richard Mór de Burgh; Felim Ua Conchobair is expelled. The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics ( LASP ) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder, specializing in space-based research. The LASP research programs focus on space physics, astrophysics, and atmospheric sciences with major emphasis in solar-terrestrial physics, solar physics, heliophysics, astrophysics and magnetospheric research. LASP has been the premier laboratory for space physics and space instrumentation development in the United States since it was founded in 1963. LASP operates two facilities that are world-class in their respective fields of expertise and are used to perform a broad spectrum of science and technology.

Year 1342 ( MCCCXLII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1429 – Henry V of England and Charles VI of France meet near Calais to discuss the English siege of the French city, but Henry withdraws his forces without an agreement . 1997 – A car bomb attack on a restaurant in Istanbul, Turkey kills 22 people, including the Turkish Minister of State Yıldıray Oğur . 1964 – 118 people are killed during the 1964 Alaska earthquake, the most destructive earthquake in U.S. history .

A mace is a blunt weapon , a type of club or virge that uses a heavy head on the end of a handle to hit the target. It is usually made of wood, but metal maces (like this one) are also common in modern times and have seen use as military weapons, particularly in naval warfare. Maces were popular among medieval armies because they were easily carried and could be employed as a melee weapon or thrown as a missile weapon. They could even be combined with a pike. They were often made with a metal cap or spike for use as a close combat weapon.

Year 1031 (MXXXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July 20 – King Robert II (the Pious) dies at Melun, after a 35-year reign. He is succeeded by his 23-year-old son, Henry I, who becomes the sole ruler of France. Henry's mother, Queen dowager Constance of Arles, prefers her third son, Robert, as heir to the throne and, with the help of Count Odo II, begins a war against Henry.

In mathematics, two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common. Equivalently, two disjoint sets are sets whose intersection is the empty set. For example, {1, 2, 3} and {4, 5, 6} are disjoint sets, while {1, 2, 3} and {3, 4, 5} are not disjoint. A collection of more than two sets is called disjoint if any two distinct sets of the collection are disjoint.GeneralizationsThis definition of disjoint sets can be extended to a family of sets : the family is pairwise disjoint, or mutually disjoint if  whenever .

Stigmata ( , plural of , 'mark , spot , brand ' ) , in Christianity , are the appearance of the wounds of Christ on a person's body. The term originally referred to "baptismal stigmata , " wounds in the body of a believer that symbolically portray Christ's sufferings. The term stigmata came into use about 1700. Later , the term was applied to the actual appearance of wounds (holy wounds ) on persons afflicted with stigmata. Stigmata were first reported in the early thirteenth century in Italy . They became popular in the 14th and 15th centuries , and many thousands of people claimed the wounds.

Events  January–June  January 5 – Franco-Dutch War – Battle of Turckheim: The French defeat Austria and Brandenburg. January 29 – John Sassamon, an English-educated Native American Christian, dies at Assawampsett Pond, an event which will trigger a year-long war between the English American colonists of New England, and the Algonquian Native American tribes. March 30 – The guild organisation Maîtresses couturières is founded in Paris. April – English merchant Anthony de la Roché, blown off course after rounding Cape Horn eastabout, makes the first discovery of land south of the Antarctic Convergence, landing on South Georgia and (probably) Gough Island.

Year 1419 ( MCDXIX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Lancastrians are defeated by the Yorks. August 1 – Henry Bolingbroke replaces John, Duke of Lancaster as King of England. November 21 – John IV, Duke of Brabant and John V, Duke of Brittany are killed at the Battle of Landévennec.

Year 1162 (MCLXII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 6 – German forces, led by Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), capture Milan; much of the city is destroyed three weeks later, on the emperor's orders. The fortifications are demolished, and the churches are destroyed. The population is dispersed, and the commune abolished. The fate of Milan leads to the submission of Brescia, Piacenza, and many other northern Italian cities.

Escherichia coli , also known as E. coli , is a Gram-negative, facultative anaerobic, rod-shaped, coliform bacterium of the genus Escherichia that is commonly found in the lower intestine of warm-blooded organisms. Most E. coli strains are harmless, but some serotypes (EPEC, ETEC etc.) can cause serious food poisoning in their hosts, and are occasionally responsible for food contamination incidents that prompt product recalls. The harmless strains are part of the normal microbiota of the gut, and can benefit their hosts by producing vitamin K2, and preventing colonisation of the intestine with pathogenic bacteria, having a mutualistic relationship.

Roger Williams ( 21 December 1603between 27 January and 15 March 1683 ) was a Puritan minister , theologian , founder of the first Baptist church in North America , and a political theorist . Williams became a Puritan pastor in 1631 and was ejected from Massachusetts Bay Colony because of his theological views. He left for what was then Providence Plantation in 1636 and was elected the first Governor in 1638. A staunch defender of civil and religious liberty, Williams became the first to propose the separation of civil and ecclesiastical powers in government, a fundamental concept of modern Western democracy.

Year 1206 (MCCVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  January 31 – Battle of Rusion: The Bulgarian forces (some 7,000 men) under Tsar Kaloyan defeat the remnants of the Latin army near the fortress of Rusion in Thrace. Around 120 knights supported by soldiers and cavalry are killed in battle or captured. In February, the Bulgarians attack and loot the fortified town of Rodosto (see Battle of Rodosto), defended by a Venetian garrison. Later, Kaloyan captures many more towns and fortresses.

The human leg , in the general word sense , is the entire lower limb of the human body , including the foot , ankle , thigh, and lower parts of the torso , such as the hip area and pelvis. It joins to the knee at the level of the knee , and the knee joins to the thigh at the level of the knee. The lower leg is a combination of the thigh, lower leg, and foot. It is a continuation of the upper leg bones, femur and tibia, with a flattened, expanded bone , the tarsal bones, and foot bones.

A compass is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation . It commonly consists of a north-pointing needle that indicates the direction of north and a ring that indicates the degrees from north (the azimuth ) through a 360 degree scale. The use of these devices to navigate was first recorded in 2nd century AD. The compass is used as an important navigational tool by many people including land, air and naval navigators. The most common use is to determine the heading of a vehicle, vessel, aerial vehicle, or a person.

Bobsleigh or bobsled is a team winter sport that involves making timed runs down narrow, twisting, banked, iced tracks in a gravity-powered sleigh. International bobsleigh competitions are governed by the International Bobsleigh and Skeleton Federation, also known as FIBT from the French . National competitions are often governed by bodies such as the United States Bobsled and Skeleton Federation, Bobsleigh Canada Skeleton, and the German Bobsleigh, Luge, and Skeleton Federation.The first bobsleds were built in the late 19th century in St. Moritz, Switzerland, by wealthy tourists from Victorian Britain who were staying at the Palace Hotel owned by Caspar Badrutt.

He was interrogated for two years and eventually condemned to death by burning in Paris on 18 March 1314, on the rumored order of the Pope. This was the end of the […]
Events January 15 – The Templars of France are arrested and imprisoned, leading to their suppression by the king, Pope Clement V, Jacques de Molay and the other Grand Masters being burned at the stake on 18 March 1314.

Year 1301 (MCCCI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 14 – The death of Andrew III of Hungary ends the Árpád Dynasty in Hungary, resulting in a power struggle between Wenceslaus III of Bohemia, Otto III, Duke of Bavaria, and Charles Robert of Naples. Year 1042 (MXLII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April 19 – Emperor Michael V Kalaphates banishes his adoptive mother and co-ruler Zoë, for plotting to poison him, to the island of Principo. Michael V flees to the monastery of Stoudios, but is arrested, blinded and castrated.

Year 1340 ( MCCCXL ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Year 1340 ( MCCCXL ) was a leap year starting on Saturday of the Julian calendar. On January 25, Pope Benedict XII succeeds John XXII as the 206th pope. In 1340, Pope Benedict XII succeeds Pope John XXII as head of the Catholic Church. This is a summary of some of the historical events which occurred during the year 1340. In 1340-41, a famine occurred throughout much of Europe.

A horoscope (or other commonly used names for the horoscope in English include natal chart, astrological chart, astro-chart, celestial map, sky-map, star-chart, cosmogram, vitasphere, radical chart, radix, chart wheel or simply chart) is an astrological chart or diagram representing the positions of the Sun, Moon, planets, astrological aspects and sensitive angles at the time of an event, such as the moment of a person's birth. The word horoscope is derived from the Greek words ōra and scopos meaning "time" and "observer" (horoskopos, pl.

Eric Arthur Heiden (born June 14, 1958) is an American physician and a former long track speed skater, road cyclist and track cyclist. He won an unprecedented five individual gold medals, and set four Olympic records and one world record at the 1980 Winter Olympic Games. Heiden was the most successful athlete at those Olympic Games, single-handedly winning more gold medals than all nations except for the Soviet Union (10) and East Germany (9). He is the most successful Winter Olympian from a single edition of any Winter Olympics. He delivered the Athlete's Oath at those same 1980 Games.

Year 1575 (MDLXXV)  was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 21 – Queen Elizabeth I of England grants a monopoly on producing printed sheet music, to Thomas Tallis and William Byrd. February 8 – William I of Orange founds Leiden University. February 13 – Henry III of France is crowned at Reims. February 14 – Henry III of France marries Louise de Lorraine-Vaudémont. Year 996 (CMXCVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Japan  February - Chotoku Incident: Fujiwara no Korechika and Takaie shoot an arrow at Retired Emperor Kazan 2 March: Emperor Ichijo orders the imperial police to raid Korechika’s residence - Empress Teishi (sister of Korechika) cuts her hair because of the humiliation - Takaie is arrested, Korechika is absent  5 March: Korechika returns with his head shaven and attired as a monk Europe  Spring – King Otto III starts his first expedition to Italy from Regensburg, and proceeds over the Brenner Pass.

Year 1444 ( MCDXLIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. July 15 – Wars of the Roses – Battle of Hedgeley Moor: The forces of King Henry VI of England defeat the Yorkist army under the command of the Duke of Norfolk. Fall of the Sasanid Empire: King Ismail I of Persia conquers Tabriz, Iran and becomes ruler of the city. The University of Freiburg is founded by Albert the Bear in Freiburg, Germany. Howard Kingsbury Smith (May 12, 1914 – February 15, 2002) was an American journalist, radio reporter, television anchorman, political commentator, and film actor. He was one of the original members of the team of war correspondents known as the Murrow Boys.Early life and educationEarly career and CBS yearsWorld War IIUpon graduating, Smith worked for the New Orleans Item, with United Press in London, and with The New York Times. In January 1940, Smith was sent to Berlin, where he joined the Columbia Broadcasting System under Edward R. Murrow.

Year 1022 (MXXII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Battle of Svindax: The Byzantine army under Emperor Basil II defeats the Georgians at Svindax (modern Turkey). King George I is forced to negotiate a peace treaty, ending the Byzantine–Georgian wars. Summer – Nikephoros Phokas (Barytrachelos) conspires with the Byzantine general Nikephoros Xiphias against Basil II. The rebellion collapses and Xiphias assassinates Phokas. Europe  Spring – Emperor Henry II divides his army into three columns and descends through Rome onto Capua.

Natural science is one of the branches of science concerned with the description , understanding and prediction of natural phenomena based on empirical evidence observed and experimentally tested, as opposed to, intuition or spiritual beliefs. The term is often understood to refer to just the physical aspects of the natural world which is studied by physics, chemistry, and earth sciences, but the natural sciences also consist of life, earth, chemical, and physical sciences. The main idea of natural science is that there is a single reality, which can be known only by way of observation and experimental procedures.

Year 1325 ( MCCCXXV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. May 18 - The Statute of Mortmain is passed, limiting the charitable gifts which can be made without tax to 10 marks per year. July 11 - Louis I of Naples is defeated and captured by Robert of Sorbonne while trying to invade the Kingdom of Naples. December 10 - Battle of Pevensey: Scottish forces of King Robert I defeat those of Richard of Cornwall and his allies. This page uses content from the English Wikipedia.

Events  January–June  February 1 – Queen Elizabeth I of England signs the death warrant of her cousin Mary, Queen of Scots, after Mary has been implicated in a plot to murder Elizabeth. Seven days later, on the orders of Elizabeth's privy council, Mary is beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle. February 12–24 – Period of exceptionally severe cold in western Europe. April 29 – Singeing the King of Spain's Beard: On an expedition against Spain, English privateer Sir Francis Drake leads a raid in the Bay of Cádiz, sinking at least 23 ships of the Spanish fleet.

Phillis Wheatley Peters, also spelled Phyllis and Wheatly (c. 1753 – December 5, 1784) was an American author who was the first African-American author of a published book of poetry. Born in West Africa, she was sold into slavery at the age of seven or eight and transported to North America, where she was bought by the Wheatley family of Boston. After she learned to read and write, they encouraged her poetry when they saw her talent.On a 1773 trip to London with her master's son, seeking publication of her work, Wheatley met prominent people who became patrons.

Operetta is a form of theatre and a genre of light opera . It includes spoken dialogue , songs , dances and acting , but no interludes. Although operas have existed in various forms in Western musical traditions since Ancient Greece, there is no single source that provides a definition of the operetta genre, and this has led to considerable controversy over what works belong to it. This is particularly problematic, because operettas have been extremely popular for a very long period of time, but have gradually become less common in the twentieth century.

The Quirinal Hill ( ; ; ) is one of the Seven Hills of Rome , at the north-east of the city's historical center. With the Capitoline Hill, it is the hillock that is closest to the Roman forum. It has a rectangular shape, and a maximum width of about 150 meters. It rises to a maximum height of 130 m over the Roman Forum and 83 m above sea level. Its area is of about 60,000 square meters, or 10 hectares; with its highest peak it reaches an altitude of 148 metres (485 ft) above mean sea level.

Year 1169 ( MCLXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. May 16 – Siege of Kraków : The Polish Duke Bolesław the Pious is defeated and captured by Duke Casimir the Restorer of Poland. May 22 – Battle of Legnano : The Lombard League of Italian cities defeats an army of the Holy Roman Empire, led by King Frederick I Barbarossa . June 1 – After a siege of about 3 months, the army of the German Kingdom of the Romans led by Emperor Frederick I Barbarossa is defeated outside Milan, Italy.

Year 1412 (MCDXII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) on the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 16 – The Medici Family are  made official bankers of the Papacy. January 25 – Ernest, Duke of Austria, marries Cymburgis of Masovia. July 24 – Behnam Hadloyo becomes Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Mardin. Events January–June March – The Synod of Jerusalem brings together bishops and representatives from the whole of Eastern Orthodox Christendom. This is a sign of unity and concord among the churches. 1162 – Battle of Alnwick. The Scots, led by King David I defeat an English invasion force led by William the Lion, Earl of Albany. 1346 – Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor, renounces the Privilegium maio, the Golden Bull of 1356, which gave special rights to the Czech nobles and clergy. 1461 – Joan of Arc leads the siege of Jargeau, a town held by the English.

Year 1373 (MCCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 24 – The Treaty of Santarém is signed between Ferdinand I of Portugal and Henry II of Castile, ending the second war between the two countries. April 28 – Hundred Years' War: The French re-capture most of Brittany from the English, but are unable to take Brest. May 13 – English anchoress Dame Julian of Norwich receives the sixteen Revelations of Divine Love. June 16 – The Anglo-Portuguese Treaty is signed in London, and is the oldest active treaty in the world.

The European bison (Bison bonasus) or the European wood bison, also known as the wisent ( or ), or the zubr , or colloquially the European buffalo, is a European species of bison. It is one of two extant species of bison, alongside the American bison. The European bison is the heaviest wild land animal in Europe and individuals in the past may have been even larger than their modern-day descendants. During late antiquity and the Middle Ages, bison became extinct in much of Europe and Asia, surviving into the 20th century only in northern-central Europe and the northern Caucasus Mountains.

Georg Hackl ( often named : Hackl Schorsch , ; born 9 September 1966 ) is a German former luger who won 15 medals at the Winter Olympics , with 10 of those medals coming in two consecutive Winter Games ( Albertville and Lillehammer). The 2002 Winter Olympics, officially known as the XX Olympic Winter Games, was a Winter Olympics multi- sport event that was held from 8–24 February in the South Korean province of Jeongseon and the surrounding areas of Gangwon- do. It was the first Olympics to be held in South Korea and the first Olympics held in East Asia.

Proline (symbol Pro or P) is an organic acid classed as a proteinogenic amino acid (used in the biosynthesis of proteins), although it does not contain the amino group  but is rather a secondary amine. The secondary amine nitrogen is in the protonated NH2+ form under biological conditions, while the carboxyl group is in the deprotonated −COO− form. The "side chain" from the α carbon connects to the nitrogen forming a pyrrolidine loop, classifying it as a aliphatic amino acid. It is non-essential in humans, meaning the body can synthesize it from the non-essential amino acid L-glutamate.

Year 1295 ( MCCXCV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Year 1295 ( MCCXCV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ), in the 13th year of the reign of Edward I, also known as Edward of Caernarvon, and the 12th year of his reign as King of England, which began on October 20, 1272 (or possibly January 20, 1274, depending on the scholars), when he became King of England.

Year 1271 (MCCLXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July 2 – Kings Otakar II of Bohemia and Stephen V of Hungary sign the first Peace of Pressburg, settling territorial claims, following the failed invasion of Hungary by Otakar II. September 1 – Pope Gregory X succeeds Pope Clement IV as the 184th pope, as the compromise candidate between French and Italian cardinals, ending a three-year conclave, the longest ever. The County of Toulouse is returned to the crown of France.

Year 1569 ( MDLXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian calendar and a common year starting on Tuesday of the 10-day slower Julian calendar. February 11 – The 18th day of the Fat Hindu month Maagha, 508th Saka Era, Bikrami year of Vikram Samvat – Agra, capital of the Mughal Empire, is founded by Akbar the Great. February 13 – The Treaty of Blois is signed by France and Spain. April 20 – William of Orange, later known as William the Silent, is secretly married to Countess Maria of Nassau.

Year 1162 ( MCLXII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Muhammad al-Nafzawi (محمد بن علي النفزاوي) was an Arab physician who lived during the reign of the Abbasid caliphs. He was from Nafzawa, in Iraq, and was descended from a family of jurists. He studied at the university of Baghdad, and then at the University of Cairo. 15th of Zi'ab in the year 845 AH: The Ottoman sultan, Suleiman I the Magnificent conquers Damascus, Syria, following a siege of 15 days.

The African clawed frog ( Xenopus laevis , also known as the xenopus , African clawed toad , African claw-toed toad , West African clawed frog ) is a species of true frog , native to sub-Saharan Africa. It is the only living member of the clawed toad genus Xenopus, and the family Xenopodidae, which once contained over 400 species. The species was previously thought to be more widespread and diverse, with over 500 named subspecies . However, later studies suggest that the vast majority of these "species" were actually hybrids with a single species of West African clawed frog, Xenopus tropicalis.

Year 1043 ( MXLIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 28 – In the Battle of Dandanaqan, Yusuf ibn Abd al-Rahman al-Fihri, the Almohad caliph, is defeated by the Zirids of Ifriqiya ( modern-day Libya ), and is killed in action, ending his bid to conquer the Maghrib. February 23 – Pope Clement II is elected Pope, succeeding Pope Leo IX. Spring – An earthquake occurs near Jerusalem, destroying a number of Christian and Jewish holy sites.

Year 1201 ( MCCI ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. ... Events November 18 - The University of Paris is officially recognized. ... The Gregorian calendar (also called the western calendar and the christian calendar) is the calendar that was established by papal decree of Pope Gregory XIII in 1582. ... The Julian calendar was introduced by Julius Caesar in 45 BC and came into force in 42 BC (709 ab urbe condita). ... Events February 25 - Richard of Cornwall marries Joan, daughter of Charles, King of Navarre.

Year 1250 ( MCCL ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. June 12 – King Louis IX of France dies after a reign of 20 years, and is succeeded by his son Philip III . December 22 – The Republic of Pisa is destroyed by the Republic of Genoa . 1404-08-31 31 Aug A great earthquake hits Constantinople , collapsing many buildings, resulting in an estimated 8,000 deaths. 1405-01-04 4 Jan 20,000 people die in the earthquake, fire and tsunamis of Lisbon , Portugal .

Aloysius Lilius ( c. 1510 – 1576 ) , also variously referred to as Luigi Lilio , Luigi Giglio , and Loys Lilius , was an Italian physician and astronomer , who is best remembered for his invention of the astronomical calendar that became popular around the world. The year in the Gregorian calendar known as the ‘Aloysian ‘ year after him. Although Lilius made several contributions to astronomy and mathematics , his major achievement was the invention of the ‘Liliana’ astronomical calendar , which he presented to the city of Venice and then to Pope Julius in the early 1570s.

Adrian of Nicomedia (also known as Hadrian) or Saint Adrian (, died 4 March 306) was a Herculian Guard of the Roman Emperor Galerius Maximian. After becoming a convert to Christianity with his wife Natalia (Ναταλία), Adrian was martyred at Nicomedia in Asia-Minor             (Turkey). Hadrian was the chief military saint of Northern Europe for many ages, second only to Saint George, and is much revered in Flanders, Germany and the north of France.MartyrdomAdrian and Natalia lived in Nicomedia during the time of Emperor Maximian in the early fourth century.

Year 1455 ( MCDLV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Mongol Empire – Siege of Xiangyang: The capital of the Southern Tang is besieged and falls after the siege lasts 34 years. Wednesday, April 25 – Battle of Abydos: The Byzantine emperor Constantine XI is killed during the final siege of Constantinople (see Fall of Constantinople). March 20 – The Byzantine emperor Constantine XI Palaiologos, is killed in the final Ottoman assault on the capital of the Byzantine Empire. His successor is his nephew Demetrios Palaiologos.

Year 1516 (MDXVI) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Juan Díaz de Solís discovers the Río de la Plata (in future Argentina). January 23 – With the death of Ferdinand II of Aragon, his grandson, Charles of Ghent, becomes King of Spain; his mother Queen Joanna of Castile also succeeds as Queen of Aragon and co-monarch with Carlos, but remains confined at Tordesillas. March 1 – Desiderius Erasmus publishes a new Greek edition of the New Testament, Novum Instrumentum omne, in Basel.

Events  March 18 – Jacques de Molay, the 23rd and last Grand Master of the Knights Templar, is burned at the stake in Paris, France. April 4 – Exeter College, Oxford is founded in England by Walter de Stapledon, Bishop of Exeter. June 24 – Battle of Bannockburn: Scottish forces led by Robert the Bruce defeat Edward II of England, regaining Scotland's independence. August 31 – King Haakon V of Norway moves his capital from Bergen to Oslo, where he builds Akershus Fortress, from which Norway is ruled for the next 500 years.

The French and Indian War ( 1754–1763 ) was a theater of the Seven Years ' War , which pitted the colonies of British America against France and its allies, Britain' s former colonies of New France. A primary cause was the disagreement between the French and British over who would control this region of North America. The main conflict took place along this region of the Eastern United States from Maine to the Mississippi River. The conflict began with British colonization of the Ohio River Valley and the French counter- expansion from Canada. The French and Indian War was fought between Great Britain and France.

The tale of the founding of Rome is recounted in traditional stories handed down by the ancient Romans themselves as the earliest history of their city in terms of legend and myth. The most familiar of these myths, and perhaps the most famous of all Roman myths, is the story of Romulus and Remus, twins who were suckled by a she-wolf as infants. Another account, set earlier in time, claims that the Roman people are descended from Trojan War hero Aeneas, who escaped to Italy after the war, and whose son, Iulus, was the ancestor of the family of Julius Caesar.

Margaret (, ; March or April 1283 – September 1290), known as the Maid of Norway, was the queen-designate of Scotland from 1286 until her death. As she was never inaugurated, her status as monarch is uncertain and has been debated by historians.Margaret was the daughter of King Eric II of Norway and Margaret of Scotland. By the end of the reign of her maternal grandfather, King Alexander III of Scotland, she was his only surviving descendant and recognized heir presumptive. Alexander III died in 1286, his posthumous child was stillborn, and Margaret inherited the crown.

Year 1484 ( MCDLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. August 25 – Christopher Columbus sets sail from Cadiz, Spain with 17 ships and over 1000 men to find a new route to India and the Orient. July 16 – John Cabot sails from Bristol, England with his crew of 38 to explore the North Atlantic Ocean and to find the Northwest Passage for the English crown. July 10 – The Treaty of Barcelona is signed, ending the War of Sicilian Vespers in the Kingdom of Sicily, and creating the first Sicilian Parliament.

Year 1182 (MCLXXXII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April – Massacre of the Latins: The Roman Catholic (called "Latin") inhabitants of Constantinople massacre the Venetian, Genoan, and other Latin officials and traders who rule as agents of Empress Maria of Antioch. She is the mother and regent of 12-year-old Emperor Alexios II. In August, Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Maria's late husband, Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos), raises an army and enters the city, representing himself as the 'protector' of Alexios.

Events January–June January 3 – The Long Parliament adopts the Directory for Public Worship in England , Wales , Ireland and Scotland. January 27 – The Parliament of England adopts the Act of Habeas Corpus , limiting the power of the English kings. French Huguenots fleeing persecution under Louis XIV establish a new refuge in the Hudson River Valley of the Province of New York. February 28 – The Parliament of England declares the Royal Navy a law enforcement agency. April 12 – William Penn , a member of the British Parliament, is granted the land of Pennsylvania in North America as his personal proprietary colony.

Year 1207 (MCCVII) was a common year starting on Monday (full calendar) under the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Siege of Attalia: Seljuk forces led by Sultan Kaykhusraw I besiege the city port of Attalia (modern-day Antalya) with siege machines. After a siege of more than 2 months, the city is captured, Kaykhusraw allows his forces 3-day looting and slaughtering. The capture of the port gives the Seljuk Turks a major path into the Mediterranean. September 4 – Battle of Messinopolis: Latin forces under Boniface of Montferrat are ambushed and defeated at Messinopolis.

Year 1273 ( MCCLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. December – Battle of Sagrajas: King Alfons XI of Castile defeats the Moorish Emir of Granada, losing his life in the process. It is the final major battle between the Muslims and the Christians in Spain, effectively ending 800 years of Muslim occupation of the Iberian peninsula. Raymond VII, Count of Turenne marries Joan of England. Abbas I of Sharifate of Mecca becomes the Emir of Mecca.

Botulism is a rare and potentially fatal illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum. The disease begins with weakness, blurred vision, feeling tired, and trouble speaking. This may then be followed by weakness of the arms, chest muscles, and legs. Vomiting, swelling of the abdomen, and diarrhea may also occur. The disease does not usually affect consciousness or cause a fever.Botulism can be spread in several ways. The bacterial spores which cause it are common in both soil and water. They produce the botulinum toxin when exposed to low oxygen levels and certain temperatures.

Events January–June January–March – Archangelsk is founded as New Kholmogory in northern Russia , by Ivan the Terrible . January 31 – King Henry I of Spain ( Spain ) issues an edict ordering a general jihad against the Huguenots (Protestants). May 22 – The marriage of Henry II of France with Catherine de’ Medici creates the power of the French Catholic league in Europe. May 23 – The Treaty of Bergerac unites the forces of King Charles IX of France and Henry III of France against the forces of the Huguenots led by Duke Henry of Guise and Admiral Gaspard de Coligny.

Robert Sanderson Mulliken  (June 7, 1896 – October 31, 1986) was an American physicist and chemist, primarily responsible for the early development of molecular orbital theory, i.e. the elaboration of the molecular orbital method of computing the structure of molecules. Mulliken received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1966 and the Priestley Medal in 1983.Early yearsRobert Mulliken was born in Newburyport, Massachusetts. His father, Samuel Parsons Mulliken, was a professor of organic chemistry at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. As a child, Robert Mulliken learned the name and botanical classification of plants and, in general, had an excellent, but selective, memory.

Year 1390 (MCCCXC) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – The Treaty of Lyck confirms an alliance between Vytautas and the Teutonic Knights, in the Lithuanian Civil War against Vytautas's cousin, Jogaila. April 14 – John VII Palaiologos overthrows his grandfather, John V Palaiologos, as Byzantine Emperor. April 19 – Robert III succeeds his father, Robert II, as King of Scotland. May 26 – Lithuanian Civil War: The Treaty of Königsberg is signed in Königsberg, between Samogitian nobles and representatives of the Teutonic Knights.

Year 1165 (MCLXV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) makes an alliance with Venice against Emperor Frederick I (Barbarossa), who takes an oath at the Diet of Würzburg to support Antipope Paschal III against Pope Alexander III. Andronikos Komnenos, a cousin of Manuel I, escapes from prison at Constantinople. After passing through many dangers, he reaches Kiev and seeks refuge at the court of Prince Yaroslav Osmomysl.

In the Swedish calendar it began as a leap year starting on Monday and remained so until Thursday , February 1936. In the United States it was the last leap year to start on a Monday; the following leap years started on Tuesday, in the United Kingdom it was the only leap year to start on a Tuesday. Years numbered starting on Monday ( 25 December) in the United States and Canada were:
1892 ( 1892 MDCCCXCII)
1936 ( 1936 MMMXCVI), also leap year, and so 365 days long.

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese (born 17 April 1954) is an Italian former racing driver, who raced in Formula One from  to . For 19 years, he held the record for the most Grand Prix starts.He became the first Formula One driver to achieve 200 Grand Prix starts when he appeared at the 1990 British Grand Prix, and the first to achieve 250 starts at the 1993 German Grand Prix. Patrese entered 257 Formula One World Championship Grands Prix and started 256 races. As of the end of the  season he is the ninth-most experienced F1 driver in history.

Phillis Wheatley Peters , also spelled Phyllis and Wheatly ( c. 1753 – December 5 , 1784 ) was an African - American who is widely regarded as the first African - American female writer to be published . She is also known for having become the first African American woman to be freed from slavery in America . Peters was born around 1753 in West Africa to a Gambian man from the Fula ethnic community . She was sold into slavery in Boston in 1761, when she was only eight years old, by her father, and taken to Massachusetts .

Acetic acid bacteria (AAB) are a group of Gram-negative bacteria which oxidize sugars or ethanol and produce acetic acid during fermentation. The acetic acid bacteria consist of 10 genera in the family Acetobacteraceae. Several species of acetic acid bacteria are used in industry for production of certain foods and chemicals.DescriptionAll acetic acid bacteria are rod-shaped and obligate aerobes. Acetic acid bacteria are airborne and are ubiquitous in nature. They are actively present in environments where ethanol is being formed as a product of the fermentation of sugars. They can be isolated from the nectar of flowers and from damaged fruit.

Vapor pressure ( or vapour pressure in English-speaking counties other than the US ; see spelling differences ) or equilibrium vapour pressure is the pressure exerted by a vapour in its liquid-vapour equilibrium state at a given temperature. It is an intensive property and is measured as pressure or force per unit area, or pascals per unit area. It also represents the partial pressure of the vapours in the air above a liquid, a measurement for which the unit is millimetres of mercury. When a substance boils, its atoms or molecules leave the liquid phase and become vapour.

Year 1042 ( MXLII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In 1042, John I succeeds his brother, King Henry I of France. The Normans invade Southern Italy, capturing Cosenza and destroying the Muslims in Calabria. The Battle of Sardica takes place. The Bulgars destroy the Byzantine army and conquer the Byzantine Empire's remaining territory in Northern Greece. The Byzantine Emperor, Michael IV, is captured in Constantinople by the Seljuqs in 1041. Kenneth III of Scotland conquers Cumbria. April 22 - The Hodgson massacre takes place.

Events <onlyinclude>January–June  January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed, establishing an alliance between Charles X Gustav of Sweden and Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg. January 24 – The first Jewish doctor in the Thirteen Colonies of America, Jacob Lumbrozo, arrives in Maryland. April 1 – Lwów Oath: John II Casimir Vasa, King of Poland, crowns the Black Madonna of Częstochowa as Queen and Protector of Poland in the cathedral of Lwów, after the miraculous saving of the Jasna Góra Monastery during the Deluge, an event which changed the course of the Second Northern War.

The Cathedral of St. John the Divine ( sometimes referred to as St. John 's and also nicknamed St. John the Mute or The Big Bronx ) is the largest Neogothic cathedral in the United States.It is the Cathedral of the Episcopal Church in the State of New York.The Cathedral was designed to be three times larger than any other church in the world. It is located in New York City, New York. It is on West 110th Street at Amsterdam Avenue , on the south side of Central Park. The Cathedral is not in the middle of Manhattan. It is one block north of Central Park.

Year 1276 (MCCLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.It is the only Year of Four Popes.Events By areaAfrica Mamluk sultan Baibars conquers Al-Maris, previously part of Makuria, and annexes it into Egypt.Americas A severe 23-year drought begins to affect the Grand Canyon area, eventually forcing the agriculture-dependent Anasazi culture to migrate out of the region.Asia February – The court of the Southern Song Dynasty of China and hundreds of thousands of its citizens flee from Hangzhou to Fujian, and then Guangdong, in an effort to escape an invasion by Kublai Khan's Yuan Dynasty.

Year 1186 ( MCLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Abbasid–Tibetan wars: In a Tibetan victory, an Abbasid fleet is defeated and its commander taken prisoner in a naval battle on the Caspian Sea, between Toghrul III and the Mongols and their allies. May 11 – Battle of Basian: Seljuk Turks rout a crusader army led by Hugh III of Jaffa; the Seljuk commander, Kılıç Arslan I (who is later to become the Sultan of Rum), is mortally wounded.

Year 1350 (MCCCL) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 9 – Giovanni II Valente becomes Doge of Genoa. May 23 – A number of supporters of William V, Count of Holland, in his power struggle with his mother Margaret I, Countess of Holland, found the Cod League. August 29 – Battle of Les Espagnols sur Mer off Winchelsea: An English fleet personally commanded by King Edward III defeats a Castilian fleet. September 5 – Conservative noblemen in the County of Holland found the Hook League.

Albert III  (9 November 141411 March 1486) was Elector of Brandenburg from 1471 until his death, the third from the House of Hohenzollern. A member of the Order of the Swan, he received the cognomen Achilles  because of his knightly qualities and virtues. He also ruled in the Franconian principalities of Ansbach from 1440 and Kulmbach from 1464 (as Albrecht I).BiographyEarly lifeAlbert was born at the Brandenburg residence of Tangermünde as the third son of the Nuremberg burgrave Frederick I and his wife, the Wittelsbach princess Elisabeth of Bavaria-Landshut.

Nature versus nurture is a long-standing debate in biology about the balance between two competing factors which determine fate: environment (nurture) and genetics (nature). The alliterative expression "nature and nurture" in English has been in use since at least the Elizabethan period and goes back to medieval French.The complementary combination of the two concepts is an ancient concept . Nature is what people think of as pre-wiring and is influenced by genetic inheritance and other biological factors. Nurture is generally taken as the influence of external factors after conception e.g.

Year 1217 (MCCXVII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Fifth Crusade  Summer – Various groups of French knights reach the Italian ports. King Andrew II of Hungary arrives with his army in Split, in Dalmatia. He is joined by German forces, led by Duke Leopold VI (the Glorious). At the end of July, Pope Honorius III orders the crusaders assembled in Italy and Sicily to proceed to Cyprus, but there is no transport provided by the Italian city-states, Venice, Genoa and Pisa.

Greyhound racing is an organized, competitive sport in which greyhounds are raced around a track. There are two forms of greyhound racing, track racing (normally around an oval track) and coursing, the latter is now banned in most countries. Track racing uses an artificial lure (usually a form of windsock) that travels ahead of the greyhounds on a rail until the greyhounds cross the finish line. As with horse racing, greyhound races often allow the public to bet on the outcome.In many countries greyhound racing is purely amateur and solely for enjoyment.

Electroporation , or electropermeabilization , is a microbiology technique in which an electrical field is applied to cells in order to increase the permeability of cell membranes. Electropermeabilization is mainly performed using two different approaches: direct electroporation, which is a one-time pulse application of an electric field to the membrane of a cell to induce the passage of a DNA plasmid ; or a repeated pulse delivery of an electric field for a period of minutes or days. In the former approach, the pore formation is a rapid process that is generally less than 500 µs. This approach may also induce irreversible cell lysis.

Adrian of Nicomedia ( also known as Hadrian ) or Saint Adrian ( , died 4 March 306 ) was a Christian priest in the Roman Empire who is venerated as a saint in the Eastern Orthodox Church, Oriental Orthodox churches, and Roman Catholicism. He was one of the Seventy Disciples sent by Christ with a mandate to teach and spread the gospel message. After his arrival, Adrian immediately began preaching in the area around the Black Sea. He is considered the first bishop of Nicomedia. His life was recorded by Eusebius in his Church History.

Year 993 ( CMXCIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Caliph of the Fatimid dynasty of Egypt and the Jazira is al-Muizz li-Din Allah. The Battle of the Neretva takes place in Herzegovina, between the Byzantine Empire and the First Bulgarian Empire. Liege (in Latin: Legia), the largest city in the Belgian province of Antwerp, is granted its charter from Count Godfrey I of Namur by the German king, Otto II, at the city's market square, in the present-day square Grote Markt 23.

OS-9 is a family of real-time, process-based, multitasking, multi-user operating systems, developed in the 1980s, originally by Microware Systems Corporation for the Motorola 6809 microprocessor. It was purchased by Radisys Corp in 2001, and was purchased again in 2013 by its current owner Microware LP.The OS-9 family was popular for general-purpose computing and remains in use in commercial embedded systems and amongst hobbyists. Today, OS-9 is a product name used by both a Motorola 68000-series machine language OS and a portable (PowerPC, x86, ARM, MIPS, SH4, etc.)

Year 1292 (MCCXCII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  April 5 – The Papal election, 1292–94 begins. November – Michael II becomes Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch. November 17 (Julian calendar) – John Balliol is selected by King Edward I of England as King of Scotland, from among 13 competitors for the Crown of Scotland; Edward then treats John as a puppet ruler and Scotland as a vassal state, eventually provoking the Wars of Scottish Independence, commencing in 1296.

Year 1270 ( MCCLXX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. May 25 – Charles the Bald defeats and captures Wenceslaus I, duke of Bohemia, in the Battle of Cedynia; the war between the two kings continues. May 30 – Charles the Bald defeats the Hungarian forces of King Stephen I of Hungary and Duke Berthold of Bavaria at the Battle of Roussino. December 7 – Emperor Kōmei is born in the Heian period, the 96th ruler of Japan. August 10 – Emperor Tenmu of Japan dies after 26 years of rule in Japan.

Georgy Konstantinovich Zhukov ( ; ; 1 December 1896 – 18 June 1974 ) was a Soviet general and Marshal of the Soviet Union. He held the post of Chief of Staff of the Red Army, the Deputy Commander of the Warsaw Pact, and the Minister of Defence of the Soviet Union from May 1965 to July 1974. Zhukov took part in all major military campaigns of the Red Army during the 1930s and 1940s, including the Battle of Moscow , the Battle of Stalingrad , the Leningrad Defensive Operation and the Battle of Kursk .

Year 1515 (MDXV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 25 – Francis I of France is crowned (r. until 1547). May 13 – Mary Tudor, Queen of France, and Charles Brandon, 1st Duke of Suffolk, are officially married at Greenwich (near London). June 13 – Battle of Turnadag: The army of Ottoman sultan Selim I defeats the beylik of Dulkadir under Bozkurt of Dulkadir. July–December  July 2 – Manchester Grammar School is endowed by Hugh Oldham, the first free grammar school in England.

Year 1464 (MCDLXIV) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It is one of eight years (CE) to contain each Roman numeral once (1000(M)+(-100(C)+500(D))+50(L)+10(X)+(-1(I)+5(V)) = 1464).Events  January–December  April 25 – Battle of Hedgeley Moor in England: Yorkist forces under John Neville defeat the Lancastrians under Sir Ralph Percy, who is killed.

Year 1342 (MCCCXLII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  January 21–June 27 – An-Nasir Ahmad, Sultan of Egypt, rules prior to being deposed by his half-brother As-Salih Ismail. May 7 – Pope Clement VI succeeds Pope Benedict XII, as the 198th Pope. July 16 – Louis I becomes king of Hungary. July 18 – Battle of Zava: Mu'izz al-Din Husayn defeats the Sarbadars. July 22 – St. Mary Magdalene's flood is the worst such event on record for central Europe.

Year 1208 (MCCVIII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By place  Asia  April 15 – A fire breaks out in the Song Chinese capital city of Hangzhou, raging for four days and nights, destroying 58,097 houses over an area of more than , killing 59 people, and an unrecorded number of other people, who are trampled while attempting to flee. The government provides temporary lodging for 5,345 people, in nearby Buddhist and Taoist monasteries. The collective victims of the disaster are given 160,000 strings of cash, along with 400 tons of rice.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE, FRAeS, (20 May 189511 June 1937) was a British aircraft designer who worked for the Southampton aviation company Supermarine from 1917 to 1936. He is best remembered for designing racing seaplanes such as the  Supermarine S.6B, and the Supermarine Spitfire.Born in Butt Lane, Staffordshire, Mitchell attended Hanley High School and afterwards worked as an apprentice at a locomotive engineering works, whilst also studying engineering and mathematics at night. In 1917 he joined Supermarine, where he was appointed Chief Engineer in 1920 and Technical Director in 1927.

Charles XV also Carl (Carl Ludvig Eugen); Swedish: Karl XV and Norwegian: Karl IV (3 May 1826 – 18 September 1872) was King of Sweden (Charles XV) and Norway, there often referred to accurately as Charles IV, from 1859 until his death in 1872. Though known as King Charles XV in Sweden (and also on contemporary Norwegian coins), he was actually the ninth Swedish king by that name, as his predecessor Charles IX (reigned 1604–1611) had adopted a numeral according to a fictitious history of Sweden.

Year 1490 ( MCDXC ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1448 - The first book to contain the work of William Shakespeare, the Sonnets , is published in London. 1490 - King John III of Portugal orders the expulsion of Jews from the country. 1494 - Vasco de Gama returns to Portugal from the first direct voyage to India by a European. 1497 - Vasco de Gama begins his second expedition to India with a fleet of four ships and some 250 men, in search of a direct route to the "Spice Islands."

Year 990 ( CMXC ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Holy Roman Emperor is Otto II. Arab forces led by Sharaf al-Dawla, governor of Aleppo take Antioch from Bardas Skleros. Emperor Basil II's attempt to relieve the city fails and Bardas is taken prisoner. He is later exiled to Lesbos, where he is executed. Emperor Suzaku abdicates after a 5 year reign. He is succeeded by his brother, Reizei. Bernard I succeeds his brother Adalbert I as Duke of Saxony.

Events  January–March  January 8 – Carolean Death March begins: A catastrophic retreat by a largely-Finnish Swedish-Carolean army under the command of Carl Gustaf Armfeldt across the Tydal mountains in a blizzard kills around 3,700 men and cripples a further 600 for life. January 23 – The Principality of Liechtenstein is created, within the Holy Roman Empire. February 3 (January 23 Old Style) – The Riksdag of the Estates recognizes Ulrika Eleonora's claim to the Swedish throne, after she has agreed to sign a new Swedish constitution. Thus, she is recognized as queen regnant of Sweden.

Lillian Evelyn Gilbreth ( Moller ; May 24 , 1878 – January 2 , 1972 ) was an American psychologist and the first woman inducted into the National Academy of Sciences . Born in Providence, Rhode Island in 1878 , she attended Brown University where she received a Bachelor of Science and Master of Science degree in psychological education. She taught at the school, and later at Providence Junior College, until her graduate studies were interrupted by her marriage to an industrial engineer, Frank Bunker Gilbreth, on February 8, 1904. She later received a Doctor of Philosophy degree from Brown University , which awarded her an honorary doctorate in 1937.

Tone is the use of pitch in language to distinguish lexical or grammatical meaning – that is, to distinguish or to inflect words. All verbal languages use pitch to express emotional and other paralinguistic information and to convey emphasis, contrast and other such features in what is called intonation, but not all languages use tones to distinguish words or their inflections, analogously to consonants and vowels. Languages that have this feature are called tonal languages; the distinctive tone patterns of such a language are sometimes called tonemes, by analogy with phoneme.

Black's Law Dictionary is the most widely used law dictionary in the United States. Henry Campbell Black (1860–1927) was the author of the first two editions of the dictionary.HistoryThe first edition was published in 1891 by West Publishing, with the full title A Dictionary of Law: containing definitions of the terms and phrases of American and English jurisprudence, ancient and modern, including the principal terms of international constitutional and commercial law, with a collection of legal maxims and numerous select titles from the civil law and other foreign systems. A second edition was published in 1910 as A Law Dictionary.

The Witan , literally `` wise men '' , was the king 's council in Anglo-Saxon England from before the time of Caedwalla ( 850 ) until its abolishment by Athelstan ( 930 ) . Witan is a term in Old English or Anglo-Saxon used for a council or assembly of the king and his leading nobles or thegns . Its meaning is `` the wise '', and can be traced to Old English wit ( knowledge, wisdom, counsel, or skill ). The Witan was an assembly of the king's thegns or noble men to advise him and to approve or ratify decisions which affected the whole kingdom.

Events January–June January 10 – The Royal African Company is granted a Royal Charter by Charles II of England . ... January 14 – The Royal African Company, a chartered company of the Kingdom of Great Britain and the earliest known commercial corporation to have trading interests in both Africa and America, receives its Royal Charter . ... January 22 – In Boston , Massachusetts , Samuel Sewall is hanged in effigy for his signature on the Massachusetts Body of Liberties, which bans Quakers from the colony; he is the only man to have his punishment carried out in this manner.

Year 1231 (MCCXXXI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Emperor Frederick II promulgates the Constitutions of Melfi (Liber Augustalis), a collection of laws for Sicily, as well as the edict of Salerno, regulating the exercise of medicine and separating the professions of physician and apothecary, and requiring medical schools to practice dissection. Castillan forces under King Ferdinand III (the Saint) re-conquer the city of Quesada. Battle of Jerez: Ferdinand III defeats Emir Ibn Hud of the Taifa of Murcia.

Year 1181 ( MCLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. May – The Khazar Empire is destroyed by an alliance of Rus', Bulgars, Kipchaks, Kimek, Pechenegs and other nomadic peoples. The Khazars flee westward. December – The city of Palmyra, Syria, is sacked by invading Seljuk Turks, resulting in the death of 200,000 people. This is the beginning of a period of instability and decline that will last until the Mongol invasion of the mid-13th century. Mu'ayyad al-Din al-'Amili, Persian poet (d.

Figure skating jumps are an element of three competitive figure skating disciplines—men 's singles , ladies ' singles , and ice dancing —in which male and female athletes perform spins, jumps, footwork, and step maneuvers together with spins and jumps—and dance moves on the ice. They are not used in ice dance. The jumps can be performed on one or both feet. Skaters must jump from both feet to achieve a certain level of the competition. In ice dance, the couple performs synchronized dance moves on the ice. There are three main groups of jumps in figure skating - toe, edge, and step.

Year 1032 (MXXXII) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Romanos III (Argyros) sends a Byzantine expeditionary army under General Michael Protospatharios, which includes Western auxiliaries and elite troops of Asia Minor, to reinforce the Byzantine position in Calabria (Southern Italy). Europe  September 6 – King Rudolph III dies without any heirs. He bequeaths his entire dominions to Emperor Conrad II (the Elder), dispatching to him the Holy Lance and ring of St. Maurice, symbols of Burgundian investiture.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC. The Late Bronze Age collapse in the ancient Near East and eastern Mediterranean is often considered to begin in this century.Events 1200 BC: The first civilization in Central and North America develops in about 1200 BC in the coastal regions of the southern part of the Gulf of Mexico. Known as the Olmec civilization, its early site is at San Lorenzo. 1200 BC: The Phoenicians found the port of Lisbon, Portugal 1197 BC: The beginning of the first period (1197 BC – 982 BC) by Shao Yong's concept of the I Ching and history.

"Coven"  usually refers to a group or gathering of witches. The word "coven" (from Anglo-Norman covent, cuvent, from Old French covent, from Latin conventum = convention) remained largely unused in English until 1921 when Margaret Murray promoted the idea that all witches across Europe met in groups of thirteen which they called "covens".NeopaganismIn Wicca and other similar forms of neopagan witchcraft, such as Stregheria and Feri, a coven is a gathering or community of witches, like an affinity group, engagement group, or small covenant group.

Bdellovibrio is a genus of Gram-negative , obligate aerobic bacterium . One of the more notable characteristics of this genus is its ability to inject a cytotoxin into the cytoplasm of eukaryotic organisms such as humans, in order to replicate their DNA, which is often in the form of naked circles. In fact, the only known way that it can reproduce is by inserting its DNA into the host cell in order to replicate the plasmid (circular, double-stranded DNA). It is believed that it was originally an endospore-forming bacterium, and when it enters an eukaryotic cell it converts back to a spiral bacterium.

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces. The basic goal is to find algebraic invariants that classify topological spaces up to homeomorphism, though usually most classify up to homotopy equivalence.Although algebraic topology primarily uses algebra to study topological problems, using topology to solve algebraic problems is sometimes also possible. Algebraic topology, for example, allows for a convenient proof that any subgroup of a free group is again a free group.Main branches of algebraic topologyBelow are some of the main areas studied in algebraic topology:Homotopy groupsIn mathematics, homotopy groups are used in algebraic topology to classify topological spaces.

In computational complexity theory , PSPACE is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine in logarithmic space, typically defined as the set of all decision problems that have a polynomial-size answer. It is also a subset of the class of languages that are efficiently solvable on a Turing machine in exponential space , also called PTIME . A function f : 0-1-to-N is polynomially tractable if there exists another function g that satisfies. The PSPACE completeness conjecture is the statement that the set of logically complete problems is closed under PSPACE reductions, where a polynomial-time many-one reduction is called a PSPACE-complete problem.

Sigismund of Luxembourg ( 15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437 ) was a monarch who reigned as king of Bohemia, a title he had inherited in 1378, and Germany, a title he asserted by assuming the government in several rival principalities, but which was never legally confirmed, from 1410 until his death. Sigismund was elected as king of the Romans and Holy Roman Emperor in 1410, but he renounced all his German claims when he was elected emperor. During the Hussite Wars the Bohemian Protestant movement seized control of Bohemia for a time. In the late 1420s, Sigismund was able to reconquer it.

Year 1510 ( MDX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. May 10 – Ferdinand II of Aragon ( Aragon ) is crowned King of Castile in the cathedral of Burgos. June 24 – Christopher Columbus leaves Cádiz, Spain in the Santa Maria , the Nina , and the Pinta on his second voyage to the West Indies. October 19 – Spanish Conquistador Pedro Álvares Cabral establishes a Portuguese colony in Brazil; on his ship's inscription, he names the land Vera Cruz, "true cross", which later becomes the Brazilian town of Belém .

Spins are an element in figure skating in which the skater rotates, centered on a single point on the ice, while holding one or more body positions. They are performed by all disciplines of the sport, single skating, pair skating, and ice dance, and are a required element in most figure skating competitions. As The New York Times says, "While jumps look like sport, spins look more like art. While jumps provide the suspense, spins provide the scenery, but there is so much more to the scenery than most viewers have time or means to grasp".

Margaret ( , ; March or April 1283 – September 1290 ) , known as the Maid of Norway , was Queen of Scots as the wife of King Alexander III . She was the granddaughter of Magnus III of Norway , the last king of a united Norway . Margaret was born in Dunfermline , Scotland , to King Alexander II of Scotland, and his wife Yolande of Dreux , the niece of Saint Louis IX of France . She died at age six in 1290 while on her way to Scotland from Orkney , where she was being held as a potential ruler.

The Stoned Guest is a "half-act opera" by Peter Schickele in the satirical persona of P. D. Q. Bach. The title is a play on the "stone guest" character in Don Giovanni by Mozart, as well as the opera The Stone Guest by Alexander Sergeyevich Dargomïzhsky after the play by Pushkin. The work is a parody of classical opera, although some critics consider it to be the equal of many classical works in technical ability. The opera appears on the 1970 album of the same name.The loose story combines elements of Don Giovanni with elements of Carmen by Georges Bizet.
