January 29 – The Treaty of Saint-Jean-de-Luz between France and Spain gives the French possession of the Spanish territories of Guipúzcoa, Labourd, Basse Navarre, the Aran Valley, and the seigneuries of Fuenterrabía, Fuenterredonde, and Pasajes.

Events January–June January 1 Colonel George Monck ( with his regiment ) crosses from Scotland to England at the village of Coldstream, leading the Royalist Army in England, the New Model Army is raised. February 6 Oliver Cromwell ( with his army ) invades Ireland to support the Royalist cause, he lands at Dublin. May 20–23 The Battle of Colchester in which Cromwell takes Colchester Castle. June 13–15 The Battle of Langside in which James Graham ( Marquis of Montrose ) attempts to raise a Royalist army at Glasgow. July 1–3 The Battle of Edgehill in which the New Model Army defeats the Royalist army in its first major battle.

J. Robert Oppenheimer ( ; April 22 , 1904 – February 18 , 1967 ) was an American theoretical physicist best known for his central role in the development of the first atomic bomb , the first man of the Trinity , the test explosion of the world's first nuclear device at the Alamogordo bombing ground in New Mexico . Born in New York City into a wealthy family of German - Jewish descent , Oppenheimer graduated from Harvard University at the top of his class and went on to teach at the California Institute of Technology (Caltech) and the University of Cambridge in England .

Frederick (Middle High German: Friderich, Standard German: Friedrich; 21 September 1371 – 20 September 1440) was the last Burgrave of Nuremberg from 1397 to 1427 (as Frederick VI), Margrave of Brandenburg-Ansbach from 1398, Margrave of Brandenburg-Kulmbach from 1420, and Elector of Brandenburg (as Frederick I) from 1415 until his death. He became the first member of the House of Hohenzollern to rule the Margraviate of Brandenburg.Biography Frederick was born in Nuremberg, the second-born son of Burgrave Frederick V (1333–1398) and the Wettin princess Elisabeth of Meissen.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 16 – Francesco Morosini, the Doge of Venice since 1688, dies after ruling the Republic for more than five years and a few months after an unsuccessful attempt to capture the island of Negropont from the Ottoman Empire during the Morean War. January 18 – Sir James Montgomery of Scotland, who had been arrested on January 11 for conspiracy to restore King James to the throne, escapes with the aid of the two persons guarding him and flees to France, arriving in Paris on February 15. January 21 (January 11 O.S.)

Mariner 3 (together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed and built by the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) for NASA's Mariner-Mars 1964 project that were intended to conduct close-up (flyby) scientific observations of the planet Mars and transmit information on interplanetary space and the space surrounding Mars, televised images of the Martian surface and radio occultation data of spacecraft signals as affected by the Martian atmosphere back to Earth.Although the launch was initially successful, there was a separation issue and Mariner 3 stopped responding when its batteries ran out of power.

Berchtesgaden  is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land, Bavaria, in southeastern Germany, near the border with Austria,  south of Salzburg and  southeast of Munich. It lies in the Berchtesgaden Alps, south of Berchtesgaden; the Berchtesgaden National Park stretches along three parallel valleys.The Kehlstein mountain , with its Kehlsteinhaus (Eagle's Nest) is located in the area.EtymologyBerchtesgaden, Upper Bavaria (Achental), earlier Perchterscadmen, Perhtersgadem, Berchirchsgadem, Berchtoldesgadem; the word underwent a Latin distortion of Old High German parach, Romance bareca 'hay shed'.

In computer programming , a postcondition is a condition or predicate that must always be true just after the execution of a given algorithm, if the algorithm's preconditions are true and the algorithm's input parameters are those intended. postcondition (Computer science)
postcondition: in computer science, that part of a post-test that indicates whether or not the operation has succeeded; in programming languages, a set of conditions specified in terms of the value(s) of a program variable(s) after executing a particular procedure, such as a function, and assuming the preconditions are true.

Year 1212 (MCCXII) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   England  July 10 – The Great Fire: The most severe of several early fires of London burns most of the city to the ground; over 3,000 people die, many of them by drowning in the River Thames. According to a contemporary account: "An awful fire broke out on the Southwark side of London Bridge; while it was raging, a fire broke out at the other end also and so hemmed in the numerous crowds who had assembled to help the distressed.

Year 1378 (MCCCLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor, visits his nephew Charles V of France in Paris, to celebrate publicly the friendship between their two nations. January 13 – Balša II succeeds his brother, Durađ I, as ruler of Lower Zeta (modern-day Montenegro). March – In England, John Wycliffe tries to promote his ideas for Catholic reform by laying his theses before Parliament, and making them public in a tract.

Year 1236 ( MCCXXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1240 CE was the year 1240 of the Common Era (CE) as well as Anno Domini (AD) or the Anno Martius (AM). It is not a leap year. It was also the first year of the 2nd millennium, 3rd century, 24th century, 1240s, 2nd half of the 13th century, and the 13th century. The year 1316 CE was a leap year, but not a leap year starting on Sunday.

Year 1344 ( MCCCXLIV ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. October 25 - King Haakon VI of Norway becomes the first crowned king to address a Parliament in person at the Norwegian Storting . December 14 - Pope Clement VI is elected, as the first of three popes of that name. The Council of Constance is opened, under papal control. The University of Rostock is founded at Rostock, Germany, by Henry IV of Saxony, the Holy Roman Empire, and the city of Rostock.

The term chat room, or chatroom (and sometimes group chat; abbreviated as GC), is primarily used to describe any form of synchronous conferencing, occasionally even asynchronous conferencing. The term can thus mean any technology ranging from real-time online chat and online interaction with strangers (e.g., online forums) to fully immersive graphical social environments.The primary use of a chat room is to share information via text with a group of other users. Generally speaking, the ability to converse with multiple people in the same conversation differentiates chat rooms from instant messaging programs, which are more typically designed for one-to-one communication.

Year 1383 ( MCCCLXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. February 5 – The Ottoman Turks, under Bayezid I, capture Nicopolis in Bulgaria after a 28-month siege. This is a crushing defeat for the last Christian stronghold in Europe. March 17 – In the Ottoman Empire, the city of Gallipoli (Catala) is captured by the Ottoman Empire. July – Bayezid I and John Hunyadi defeat Timur Lenk at the Battle of Nicopolis. September 24 – Bayezid I lays siege to and conquers Constantinople after the failure of an embassy from the Roman Catholic Church.

Adnams is a regional brewery founded in 1872 in Southwold , Suffolk , England , by George and Ernest Adnams . It has won many awards for its cask beer. Adnams produces a range of traditional ales, which have been developed from the original beers. The Adnams brewery produces a variety of traditional and contemporary beers which are regularly awarded medals at the National and International Beer Competitions. Adnams is a regional brewery and is one of the largest independently owned brewers in England, brewing its own water at its site in Southwold . The Adnams beers are sold throughout the region and in London and the South East.

Dyson 's eternal intelligence concept ( the Dyson Scenario ) , proposed by Freeman Dyson in 1979 , proposes a future in which humanity becomes immortal through the colonization of other planets. [70]
In May 2010 , Dyson stated that he favored colonizing the Moon or asteroids as first steps toward colonizing the cosmos. [71] According to Dyson in 1987,
“The long-range goal must be a permanent presence of humanity in space. We need to develop ways of making the human body robust against the rigors of weightlessness and cosmic rays, and to extend life to a period when death from old age is no longer a problem.

Year 1409 ( MCDIX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. July 12 - In an attempt to gain possession of the Kingdom of England, Henry IV of England, supported by a fleet of 50 French ships with 1,000 men, lands on the coast of Kent. Henry VII, Holy Roman Emperor invades Sicily and occupies Palermo after the Aragonese have abandoned it. Richard of Cambridge becomes the 15th Duke of Brittany. The first stone of the new cathedral of Strasbourg was laid, the construction of the building would last 200 years.

Events  January–June  January – Six months into King Philip's War, Metacomet (King Philip), leader of the Algonquian tribe known as the Wampanoag, travels westward to the Mohawk nation, seeking an alliance with the Mohawks against the English colonists of New England; his efforts in creating such an alliance are a failure. January 29 – Feodor III becomes Tsar of Russia. January 31 – University of San Carlos of Guatemala, the oldest institution of higher education in Central America, was founded. February 10 – After the Nipmuc tribe attacks Lancaster, Massachusetts, colonist Mary Rowlandson is taken captive, and lives with the Indians until May.

Year 1185 ( MCLXXXV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar . March 30 – King Sancho II of Pamplona becomes the first monarch of the Kingdom of Navarre to be buried in his capital of Pamplona. Fall of Haran to the Seljuq Empire. July – Battle of Baliun'el in the Kingdom of Georgia, between King Demetre II and the Seljuk Turks. August 24 – Battle of Bashti: The Seljuk Turks, led by Atsız, defeat the Georgian forces of King David IV, forcing him to retreat to the capital.

Events January – March January 7 – In India , Sufi rebel leader Shah Inayat Shaheed from Sindh who had been in exile in India for 17 years was killed. January 21 – An earthquake on the island of Java, Indonesia , kills 5, March 26 – An earthquake in Turkey destroys the ancient city of Manisa killing 25, May 20 – The United States Senate establishes the Medal of Honor by statute. May 23 – The Battle of Barrosa was fought during the Peninsular War between the French and Spanish Armies, on the field of Barrosa, Almeria Province, Spain.

In cosmology , the cosmological constant ( usually denoted by the Greek capital letter lambda : Λ ) , alternatively known as the dark energy , is the currently preferred model to explain the observed acceleration of the universe's rate of expansion. In classical general relativity , the cosmological constant determines the magnitude of the Einstein Field Equations , which define the geometry of space and time. In general relativity and in most modern models of the universe, the cosmological constant has a value of zero in a space and time with a positive cosmological constant, and it is related to the expansion rate of the universe in such a universe.

A noble savage is a literary stock character who embodies the concept of the indigene , outsider , wild human , or feral man , and is often contrasted with the corrupting civilization of urbanized man . The concept was a common theme in 18th-century British and French philosophy and political theory, and was later used by 19th-century anthropologists to describe certain tribal peoples of the Americas. The term was first used by the British philosopher and statesman Sir Francis Bacon in the 17th century, and appeared in the English language in the 17th century English translation of the French philosophes ' Histoire des deux Indes by Pierre Boileau .

Symbiosis ( from Greek , , `` living together '' , from , , `` together '' , and , `` life'' ) is the interaction of two different species living in close association with one another for mutual benefit, usually in a relationship lasting for many years, as between a parasite and a host or between an organism and a phoretic organism, as on the back of an insect. These relationships are often specific to particular species, for example, the interaction between a particular host plant and a specific type of herbivorous animal.

A trisomy is a type of polysomy in which there are three instances of a particular chromosome, instead of the normal two. A trisomy is a type of aneuploidy (an abnormal number of chromosomes).Description and causesMost organisms that reproduce sexually have pairs of chromosomes in each cell, with one chromosome inherited from each parent. In such organisms, a process called meiosis creates cells called gametes (eggs or sperm) that have only one set of chromosomes. The number of chromosomes is different for different species. Humans have 46 chromosomes (i.e. 23 pairs of chromosomes).

In art history, literature and cultural studies, Orientalism is the imitation or depiction of aspects in the Eastern world. These depictions are usually done by writers, designers, and artists from the Western world. In particular, Orientalist painting, depicting more specifically "the Middle East", was one of the many specialisms of 19th-century academic art, and the literature of Western countries took a similar interest in Oriental themes.Since the publication of Edward Said's Orientalism in 1978, much academic discourse has begun to use the term "Orientalism" to refer to a general patronizing Western attitude towards Middle Eastern, Asian, and North African societies.

Winter sports or winter activities are competitive sports or non-competitive recreational activities which are played on snow or ice . Many winter sports are also available in summer when snow and ice is not available . Winter sports are divided into two major groups - Nordic sports and Alpine sports - with each group further divided into multiple sports. Ski jumping , Nordic combined , skiing , cross-country , curling
Alpine skiing , snowboarding , alpine skiing , freestyle skiing , moguls , ski racing , snowboarding , ski mountaineering
The Nordic sports are usually held on trails with jumping venues in a stadium.

Year 1176 ( MCLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. June 17 – Battle of the Saddle: Henry the Young King defeats his ally Geoffrey V of Anjou in an apparent attempt to kill him. August 5 – The Kingdom of Toledo is captured by Berenguer de Puigverd de Baixeras. The city of Wexford in Ireland is burned by the Welsh Prince Rhys ap Murchin, after which he is granted lordship of the town. Battle of Valencia (1177) in Spain: Berenguer of Barcelona conquers the city.

Year 1343 (MCCCXLIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 14 – Arnošt of Pardubice becomes the last bishop of Prague and, subsequently, the first Archbishop of Prague. January 27 – Pope Clement VI issues his bull Unigenitus, defining the doctrine of "The Treasury of Merits" or "The Treasury of the Church" as the basis for the issuance of indulgences by the Catholic Church. April 23 – The St. George's Night Uprising begins in Estonia.

The tale of the founding of Rome is recounted in traditional stories handed down by the ancient Romans themselves as well as in the many accounts of Roman history. Rome was founded in about 753 BC by two brothers, the twin siblings, Romulus and Remus. According to one of the traditional versions of the founding of the Roman city, the twin brothers quarreled and, in the course of their argument, Romulus killed Remus and established the city of Rome on the banks of the Tiber River in Italy. The city of Rome was to be a new capital for a new, unified Italy.

Year 1290 (MCCXC) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Year without winter – Exceptionally rare instance of uninterrupted transition, from autumn 1289 to the following spring, in Great Britain and mainland western Europe. March 1 – The University of Coimbra is founded in Lisbon, Portugal by King Denis of Portugal; it moves to Coimbra in 1308. July 10 – Ladislaus IV of Hungary is assassinated by three Cumans (Árbóc, Törtel and Kemence), at the castle of Körösszeg (modern-day Cheresig) in Romania.

Year 1370 (MCCCLXX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 9 – Timur becomes first Amir of the Timurid Empire, following the Siege of Balkh which establishes his rule over the Chagatai Khanate, completing his conquest of Central Asia and parts of Persia. May 24 – The Treaty of Stralsund ends the war between Denmark and the Hanseatic League. September 19 – Hundred Years' War: Siege of Limoges – The English led by Edward the Black Prince retake the city from the French by storm with wide destruction, effectively ending the Limoges enamel industry.

A conjugate acid , within the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory , is a chemical compound formed when an acid donates a proton (H + ) to a base , resulting in a charged compound that can react with other chemical species. The term is also used, in chemistry , in more general terms for the conjugate of any ion or ionic species (as opposed to neutral species); in the case of acids this means a conjugate base . In biochemistry and related fields, the term conjugate acid may also refer to an anion which carries a proton as a counter ion.

In physics , quintessence is a hypothetical form of dark energy , more precisely a scalar field , postulated as the dominant energy of the present Universe and a candidate for explaining the accelerating expansion of the universe. Quintessence can explain the accelerating rate of expansion without invoking the existence of any exotic particles. In modern astronomy the term "quintessence" is used only in the sense of an accelerating expansion of the universe due to dark energy, but in ancient astronomy the original meaning was much more general. The ancient use of the term implied that the stars and planets, and even the elements, are "quintessence".

Jesus is comming this sundayYear 1423 (MCDXXIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 27 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Hořice: The Taborites decisively beat the Utraquists. May 21–22 – Byzantine–Ottoman Wars: The Ottoman governor of Thessaly, Turakhan Beg, breaks through the Hexamilion wall, and ravages the Peloponnese Peninsula. July 31 – Hundred Years' War – Battle of Cravant: The French army is defeated at Cravant, on the banks of the River Yonne near Auxerre, by the English and their Burgundian allies.

Lazzi ( ; from the Italian lazzo , a joke or witticism ) are stock comedic routines that are associated with the Commedia dell'arte tradition. They are improvised by the actors when the audience offers them an unexpected obstacle or refusal. "Lazzi" refers to comedic routines as much as to their performers. The word lazzo is first mentioned in the mid-17th century in relation to Molière 's work, but the term itself was in use long before him, as it is used by Ludovico Dolce in his Il Teatro delle Commedie (1596) as well as by Ludovico Serao in Il Regno delle donne (1608) .

The hobby of collecting includes seeking , locating , acquiring , organizing , cataloging , displaying , storing , and maintaining sought-after objects. This term, in its general sense, is almost as old as human culture itself. Collectors may collect for investment, status, pleasure or for a combination of the three. The term refers particularly to the collecting of works of art, antiques, stamps, posters, minerals, coins, beer cans, dolls, comic books, miniature toys (such as model trains) or any other things of value.

The Commonwealth Games , often referred to as the Friendly Games , is an international multi-sport event involving athletes from the Commonwealth of Nations . It is known by the acronym CWG , which in recent editions, has been written as CG , in order to highlight the "Games" aspect of the name . It was officially referred to as the XXI Commonwealth Games in 2010, as it is the twenty-first time that the Games have been staged. The event was first held in 1930, and the next three games were held in 1950, 1954, and 1958.

Cooking bananas are banana cultivars in the genus Musa whose fruits are generally used in cooking . They may be called "dessert bananas," "plantains," or, in the Caribbean region, "cooking bananas." The banana fruit is the most consumed tropical fruit and the most commonly used plant-derived staple in the world. However, the use of bananas in cooking varies considerably among different ethnic and cultural communities; for example, in the US, bananas are rarely used in main courses, but are usually consumed as a dessert fruit with ice cream, pudding, cream or custard.

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago. Formerly one of the "Big Five" accounting firms (along with PricewaterhouseCoopers, Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, Ernst & Young, and KPMG), the company had provided auditing, tax and consulting services to large corporations. By 2001, it had become one of the world's largest multinational corporations.In 2002, the firm voluntarily surrendered its licenses to practice as Certified Public Accountants in the United States after it was found guilty of crimes in the firm's auditing of Enron, an energy corporation based in Texas, which had filed for bankruptcy in 2001.

Epicureanism is a system of philosophy founded around 307 BC based upon the teachings of the ancient Greek philosopher Epicurus. Epicureanism was originally a challenge to Platonism. Later its main opponent became Stoicism.Few writings by Epicurus have survived. However, there are independent attestations of his ideas from his later disciples. Some scholars consider the epic poem De rerum natura (Latin for On the Nature of Things) by Lucretius to present in one unified work the core arguments and theories of Epicureanism. Many of the scrolls unearthed at the Villa of the Papyri at Herculaneum are Epicurean texts.

arXiv (pronounced "archive"—the X represents the Greek letter chi [χ]) is an open-access repository of electronic preprints and postprints (known as e-prints) approved for posting after moderation, but not peer review. It consists of scientific papers in the fields of mathematics, physics, astronomy, electrical engineering, computer science, quantitative biology, statistics, mathematical finance and economics, which can be accessed online. In many fields of mathematics and physics, almost all scientific papers are self-archived on the arXiv repository before publication in a peer-reviewed journal.

Arthrobacter (from the Greek, "jointed small stick”) is a genus of bacteria that is commonly found in soil. All species in this genus are Gram-positive obligate aerobes that are rods during exponential growth and cocci in their stationary phase. Arthrobacter have a distinctive method of cell division called "snapping division" or reversion in which the outer bacterial cell wall ruptures at a joint.DescriptionArthrobacter can be grown on mineral salts pyridone broth, where colonies have a greenish metallic center on incubated at . Under the microscope, Arthrobacter appear as rods when rapidly dividing, and cocci when in stationary phase.

Year 1408 ( MCDVIII ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. May 22 - Pope Pius V succeeds Pope Alexander VI
June 1 - King Henry IV of Castile captures the city of Toledo, Spain. July 24 - The Battle of Dornach, in what is now known as the Old Zürich War, was a Swiss victory over the Old Swiss Confederacy in the canton of Zürich. It is the last documented battle in the Swiss Confederation. July 29 - The English fleet led by Henry VII wins the Battle of Stoke.

Year 1293 (MCCXCIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By areaAfrica December – Mamluk sultan of Egypt Khalil is assassinated by his regent Baydara, who briefly claims the sultanate, before being assassinated himself by a rival political faction.Asia May 26 – An earthquake in Kamakura, Japan kills an estimated 23,000. May 31 – The forces of Raden Wijaya win a major victory in the Mongol invasion of Java, which is considered to be the founding date of the city of Surabaya. The Japanese era Shōō ends, and the Einin era begins.

The African clawed frog (Xenopus laevis, also known as the xenopus, African clawed toad, African claw-toed frog or the platanna) is a species of African aquatic frog of the family Pipidae. Its name is derived from the three short claws on each hind foot, which it uses to tear apart its food. The word Xenopus means 'strange foot' and laevis means 'smooth'.The species is found throughout much of Sub-Saharan Africa (Nigeria and Sudan to South Africa), and in isolated, introduced populations in North America, South America, Europe, and Asia.

Spiro Theodore Agnew (November 9, 1918 – September 17, 1996) was the 39th vice president of the United States, serving from 1969 until his resignation in 1973. He is the second vice president to resign the position, the other being John C. Calhoun in 1832. Agnew was born in Baltimore to a Greek immigrant father and an American mother. He attended Johns Hopkins University and graduated from the University of Baltimore School of Law. He worked as an aide to U.S. Representative James Devereux before he was appointed to the Baltimore County Board of Zoning Appeals in 1957.

In geometry , two figures or objects are congruent if they have the same shape and size , or if one is the image of the other by translation, scaling, rotation, and flipping. The word congruent is a Latin word meaning "fit together" - congruere. Congruency has several important mathematical properties. For example , the sum of the squares of the two sides of a triangle is the same for any congruent triangles (see triangle congruence) , so two congruent triangles must have the same area. • If two rectangles have the same dimensions then they are congruent.

Year 1445 (MCDXLV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  October 10 – Battle of Mokra: The Albanian forces under Skanderbeg defeat the Ottoman forces (Pope Eugene IV raises a hymn of praise, that Christendom has been provided with a new defender, after he hears of the battle). Date unknown  The Portuguese set up their first trading post (Feitoria) in Africa, on the island of Arguin. Portuguese explorer Dinis Dias discovers the Cap-Vert, on the western coast of Africa.

Anne Boleyn (;  1501 – 19 May 1536) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536, as the second wife of King Henry VIII. The circumstances of her marriage and of her execution by beheading for treason and other charges made her a key figure in the political and religious upheaval that marked the start of the English Reformation. Anne was the daughter of Thomas Boleyn, 1st Earl of Wiltshire, and his wife, Lady Elizabeth Howard, and was educated in the Netherlands and France, largely as a maid of honour to Queen Claude of France.

Riccardo Gabriele Patrese ( born 17 April 1954 ) is an Italian former racing driver , who raced in Formula One for a total of 22 seasons between 1977 and 1993. He is the third most decorated Formula One driver , after Michael Schumacher and Jackie Stewart , and was the second driver to reach 100 World Championship Grand Prix. In total, Patrese participated in 250 World Championship Grand Prix weekends, including 247 starts – a feat only surpassed by the Brazilian Emerson Fittipaldi . During his career in Formula 1 , Patrese made 271 starts, a total of 7,114 laps raced, and scored 151 points.

Year 1029 ( MXXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The city of Hanoi, the capital of Vietnam, is founded in what is now the country's north. Mu'awiya (Arabic: معاوية‎, Muʿāwiyah, "Praised"; 6 April 640 – 25 October 680 ) was the second Umayyad caliph, and the founder of the Umayyad dynasty of the Caliphate. He ruled as caliph for nearly 29 years from 661 to 680 CE and was based primarily in Damascus.

Year 1350 ( MCCCL ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Council of Constance ends, and the Papal Schism continues. Pope Innocent VI is elected, beginning the Avignon Papacy, ending the Roman Papacy from 1406-1439. The Tartars invade Lithuania, the Grand Duchy of Moscow, and Kiev. Ferdinand I of Portugal is crowned King of Castile as Ferdinand V of Castile. The Battle of Baugé is fought between the French and British. The French defeat the English, who have to be rescued by their allies the Welshmen.

Year 1525 (MDXXV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 21 – The Swiss Anabaptist Movement is born when Conrad Grebel, Felix Manz, George Blaurock, and about a dozen others baptize each other in the home of Manz's mother on Neustadt-Gasse, Zürich, breaking a thousand-year tradition of church-state union. February 24 – Battle of Pavia: German and Spanish forces under Charles de Lannoy and the Marquis of Pescara defeat the French army, and capture Francis I of France, after his horse is wounded by Cesare Hercolani.

February 2 – King Alfonso V of Castille dies after ruling for 41 years.

Year 1446 (MCDXLVI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It is one of eight years (CE) to contain each Roman numeral once (1000(M)+(-100(C)+500(D))+(-10(X)+50(L))+5(V)+1(I) = 1446).Events  January–December  September 27 – Battle of Otonetë: Skanderbeg defeats the Ottomans. Before October – Sultan Mehmed II of the Ottoman Empire is forced to abdicate, in favor of his father Murad II, by the Janissaries.

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word "play" is from Middle English pleye, from Old English plæġ, pleġa, plæġa ("play, exercise; sport, game; drama, applause"). The word "wright" is an archaic English term for a craftsman or builder (as in a wheelwright or cartwright). The words combine to indicate a person who has "wrought" words, themes, and other elements into a dramatic form—a play. (The homophone with "write" is coincidental.

A compass is a device that shows the cardinal directions used for navigation and geographic orientation. It commonly consists of a magnetized needle or other element, such as a compass card or compass rose, which can pivot to align itself with magnetic north. Other methods may be used, including gyroscopes, magnetometers, and GPS receivers.Compasses often show angles in degrees: north corresponds to 0°, and the angles increase clockwise, so east is 90°, south is 180°, and west is 270°. These numbers allow the compass to show azimuths or bearings which are commonly stated in degrees.

Year 1524 ( MDXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. November 22 - Ottoman Empire and the Republic of Venice sign a treaty at Nisa (Baku) by the Ottoman commander Hayreddin Barbarossa against the Safavids. Pope Adrian VI, elected on this day, the last non-Italian pope before the 19th century. The Ottoman Empire invades Wallachia and forces Vlad II Dracul to surrender. June 11 - The Treaty of Nymphaeum is signed between Pope Adrian VI and King Francis I of France.

A corporate haven, corporate tax haven, or multinational tax haven, is used to describe a jurisdiction that multinational corporations find attractive for establishing subsidiaries or incorporation of regional or main company headquarters, mostly due to favourable tax regimes (not just the headline tax rate), and/or favourable secrecy laws (such as the avoidance of regulations or disclosure of tax schemes), and/or favourable regulatory regimes (such as weak data-protection or employment laws).While the "headline" corporate tax rate in jurisdictions most often implicated in base erosion and profit shifting (BEPS) is always above zero (e.g.

Events  January–June  March 13 – Battle of Tondibi: In Mali, forces sent by the Saadi Dynasty ruler of Morocco, Ahmad al-Mansur, and led by Judar Pasha, defeat the fractured Songhai Empire, despite being outnumbered by at least five to one. April 10 – English merchant James Lancaster sets off on a voyage to the East Indies. April 21 – Japanese tea-master Sen no Rikyū commits seppuku, on the order of Toyotomi Hideyoshi. May 15 – In Russia, Tsarevich Dimitri, son of Ivan the Terrible, is found dead in mysterious circumstances, at the palace in Uglich.

Year 1301 ( MCCCI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. April 25 - The Great Peerage Privilege is ratified by Parliament of England. July 16 - Battle of the Sluys - French fleet defeated by the English Fleet, with a result of the end of French maritime power.

Year 1131 (MCXXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  August 21 – King Baldwin II falls seriously ill, after his return from Antioch. He is moved to the patriarch's residence near the Holy Sepulchre, where he bequeaths the kingdom to his daughter Melisende, her husband Fulk and their infant son, Baldwin. He takes monastic vows, and dies soon after. Baldwin is buried in the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, at Jerusalem.

The French and Indian War (1754–1763) was a theater of the Seven Years' War, which pitted the North American colonies of the British Empire against those of the French, each side being supported by various Native American tribes. At the start of the war, the French colonies had a population of roughly 60,000 settlers, compared with 2 million in the British colonies. The outnumbered French particularly depended on the natives.Two years into the French and Indian War, in 1756, Great Britain declared war on France, beginning the worldwide Seven Years' War.

An engagement ring is a ring indicating that the person wearing it is engaged to be married, especially in Western cultures. A ring is presented as an engagement gift by a partner to their prospective spouse when they propose marriage or directly after a marriage proposal is accepted. It represents a formal agreement to future marriage. In Western countries, engagement rings are worn mostly by women, and rings can feature diamonds or other gemstones. The neologism "mangagement ring" is sometimes used for an engagement ring worn by men. In some cultures, men and women wear matching rings, and engagement rings may also be used as wedding rings.

Year 1344 (MCCCXLIV) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 26 – Reconquista: The Siege of Algeciras (1342–44), one of the first European military engagements where gunpowder is used, ends with the Muslim city of Algeciras surrendering and being incorporated into the Kingdom of Castile. April 17 – Constantine II, King of Armenia, is killed in an uprising and succeeded by a distant cousin, Constantine III. April 23 – The St. George's Night Uprising: The Livonian Order hangs Vesse, the rebel Estonian Elder of Saaremaa Island.

Year 1514 ( MDXIV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the year 1514 AD, the Roman Catholic Inquisition was born, to counteract the Protestant Reformation movement. On January 2, Martin Luther is summoned to the Diet of Worms to appear before Emperor Charles V and the Diet of the Holy Roman Empire and defend his views in person. On January 3, Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor is crowned in Bologna with the Iron Crown of Lombardy by Cardinal Albrecht of Austria, thus confirming Charles' position as leader of the Holy Roman Empire.

Year 1198 ( MCXCVIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. January 15 – The first Parliament of Scotland is convened in Edinburgh. The Albigensian Crusade begins – Count Raymond VI of Toulouse captures and massacres some 200 Knights Templar. King John of England begins to reign. The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of the Royal Air Force, that existed from 1918 to 1964. It was under the political authority of the Secretary of State for Air.Organisations before the Air MinistryThe Air CommitteeOn 13 April 1912, less than two weeks after the creation of the Royal Flying Corps (which initially consisted of both a naval and a military wing), an Air Committee was established to act as an intermediary between the Admiralty and the War Office in matters relating to aviation.

Tequila  is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant, primarily in the area surrounding the city of Tequila  northwest of Guadalajara, and in the Jaliscan Highlands (Los Altos de Jalisco) of the central western Mexican state of Jalisco.The red volcanic soils in the region of Tequila are well suited for growing the blue agave, and more than 300 million of the plants are harvested there each year. Agave grows differently depending on the region. Blue agaves grown in the highlands Los Altos region are larger and sweeter in aroma and taste. Agaves harvested in the valley region have a more herbaceous fragrance and flavor.

Year 1384 (MCCCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May – September 3 – Siege of Lisbon by the Castilian army, during the 1383–85 Crisis in Portugal. August 16 – The Hongwu Emperor of Ming China hears a case of a couple who tore paper money notes, while fighting over them. Under the law, this is considered to be destroying stamped government documents, which is to be punished by a caning with a bamboo rod of 100 strokes. However, the Emperor decides to pardon them, on the grounds that it was unintentional.

Year 1474 ( MCDLXXIV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. July – Christopher Columbus begins his first trip to the Americas. October 18 – Christopher Columbus arrives at the Bahamas, believing them to be part of the East Indies, and makes landfall at the island now known as San Salvador; he names the island San Salvador, and claims the land for the Kingdom of Castile. November 2 – The first European settlers in the Americas are recorded at Roanoke Colony. Nicolas Flamel and wife Pernelle move to Paris.

Events January–June January – Six months into King Philip 's War , Metacomet ( King Philip ) , leader of the Wampanoag , declares war on the English colonists of Massachusetts and Rhode Island in the name of his deceased brother King Philip. January 7 - John Casor , an indentured servant from Angola , is taken by Rice Powell and his slave Patient Ferdinand to be held captive for life as punishment for attempting to flee. January 22 - Massachusetts becomes a crown colony of Great Britain under a colonial charter issued to Sir Edmund Andros. April 24 - Slavery is outlawed in the British Empire, unless it is "absolutely necessary".

Eric Arthur Heiden ( born June 14 , 1958 ) is an American physician and a former long track speed skater who set world records in five events at the 1980 Winter Olympics. After his athletic career, Heiden served as the head team physician for the United States Ski Team. He is the son of former professional baseball player and manager Dick. Heiden is a 1980 graduate of Harvard College, Magna Cum Laude, where he was captain of the Varsity Hockey team, and was elected a member of the Porcellian Club. [3] He received his M.D.

Palermo ( , ;  , locally also  or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy, the capital of both the autonomous region of Sicily and the Metropolitan City of Palermo, the city's surrounding metropolitan province. The city is noted for its history, culture, architecture and gastronomy, playing an important role throughout much of its existence; it is over 2,700 years old. Palermo is in the northwest of the island of Sicily, by the Gulf of Palermo in the Tyrrhenian Sea.The city was founded in 734 BC by the Phoenicians as  ("flower").

Abolitionism , or the abolitionist movement , was the movement to end slavery . In Western Europe and the Americas , abolitionism was part of a larger social movement to extend the rights of citizens to more groups of people. In Europe , abolitionism was a major movement in Britain, France and in other countries. In the United States , it was the major goal of the movement to get rid of slavery. Abolitionism is not the same as antislavery . Many people who supported abolitionism also opposed slavery , but many others did not necessarily oppose the institution.

August 22 – Charles II of Hungary crowns himself King of Croatia in Sisak. November 10 – The city of Rome is conquered by the Normans led by Robert Guiscard. March 27 – John of Brienne begins his reign as King of Jerusalem.

In September, Doge Vitale II Michiel leads a Venetian fleet (120 ships) against the Byzantines, conquering the cities of Trogir and Dubrovnik. But the plague takes a heavy toll among the fleet's crewmen; half the ships have to be burned to keep them from falling into enemy hands.

Frederick James Prinze ( born Frederick Karl Pruetzel ; June 22 , 1954 – January 29 , 1977 ) was an American rock singer and the front man of the band Zapp. Frederick Karl Pruetzel was born the first of seven children into a German immigrant family, in Chicago, Illinois, to Frederick Pruetzel and his wife, the former Hildegard. He began to sing in church choirs and as a teenager would perform in talent shows at his high school. His parents sent him to a vocational school, where he took drafting classes.

Year 1430 (MCDXXX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 7 – Philip the Good, Duke of Burgundy, marries Isabella of Portugal. January 10 – Philip the Good founds the Order of the Golden Fleece. March 29 – The Ottoman Empire, under Murad II, captures Thessalonica after an eight-year siege.
