January 31 – An earthquake shakes London and the surrounding region, causing the death of an estimated 2,000 people due to collapse of over 8,000 buildings and many fires. February 23 – The second English Civil War begins between supporters of Charles II of England (the King) and supporters of the English Parliament. March 19 – William III and Mary II become joint sovereigns of England.

Year 1390 ( MCCCXC ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display full calendar ) of the Julian calendar . 1405 – Emperor Go-Tsuchimikados ascends to the throne of Japan on the 86th anniversary of the death of Emperor Go-Kameyama . 1415 – The naval Battle of Sluys leads to the capture of many English ships, resulting in the end of the shipbuilding industry in Southampton . 1520 – The Battle of the Herrings is fought between Polish forces and Lithuanian troops. 1613 – King James I of England issues a royal charter establishing the Virginia Company .

Year 1328 ( MCCCXXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In astronomy, a solar eclipse is an event which occurs when the Moon passes between Earth and the Sun, and when Earth, the Moon, and Sun are aligned in a straight line. During a total solar eclipse, the Moon completely obscures the Sun's disk, and can be seen from Earth. The solar corona may be visible, and the Sun's outer atmosphere can appear as a continuous ring around the black disc of the Moon.

Sigismund of Luxembourg (15 February 1368 – 9 December 1437) was a monarch who reigned as king of Hungary and Croatia from 1387, king of Germany from 1411, king of Bohemia from 1419, and Holy Roman Emperor from 1433 until his death in 1437, as well as prince-elector of Brandenburg (1378–1388 and 1411–1415). He was the last male member of the House of Luxembourg.Sigismund was born in Nuremberg, the son of Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV and Elizabeth of Pomerania. He married Queen Mary of Hungary in 1385 and was crowned King of Hungary soon after.

Year 1370 ( MCCCLXX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Hundred Years' War continues as the French continue their advance into English-occupied Calais, causing Edward IV of England and Henry VI of England to withdraw their troops from the city in January, in the process leaving a number of French prisoners behind them. Pope Paul II (Giovanni Battista Cibo) succeeds Pope Eugene IV (Pietro Frangipani). The Council of Florence opens. Emperor Go-Komatsu succeeds Emperor Go-Hanazono as ruler of Japan.

Year 1413 (MCDXIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  March 21 – Henry V becomes King of England following the death of his father Henry IV. July 5 – Battle of Çamurlu: Mehmed I defeats his brother Musa, ending the Ottoman Interregnum. August 28 – The University of St Andrews in Scotland is chartered by papal bull. October 2 – The Kingdom of Poland and Grand Duchy of Lithuania sign the Union of Horodło.Date unknown  Samogitia becomes the last region in Europe to be Christianized.

Wellfleet is a town in Barnstable County , Massachusetts , United States , and is located halfway between the ``elbow'' and the ``shoulder'' of Cape Cod , and is one of the oldest summer communities on Cape Cod . Originally a fishing village , it became known as a summer tourist destination during the Gilded Age. As of the United States 2000 Census , the town had a year-round population of 3,081. The town population nearly doubles in the warm season, as many seasonal residents and vacationers are counted. Wellfleet is home to the Cape Cod National Seashore .

Jesus is comming this sundayYear 1423 ( MCDXXIII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Jesus was the founder of Christianity, which is considered by many to be one of the Abrahamic religions, and by most to be monotheistic. He is the central figure of Christianity, in which he is considered the incarnation of God. Christians believe that Jesus is the second coming of God in the flesh. They believe that through his death, they have been given eternal life; and through his resurrection that they have been given hope and salvation in death.

Year 1366 (MCCCLXVI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  March 13 – Henry II deposes his half-brother, Pedro of Castile, to become King of Castile. October 12 – Frederick III of Sicily forbids decorations on synagogues. October 26 – Comet 55P/Tempel–Tuttle passes  from Earth.Date unknown  Thomas Fraser obtains lands in Aberdeenshire, upon which he starts the building of a towerhouse, that will later be known as Muchalls Castle. Muhammed V builds the Granada Hospital in Granada (in present-day Spain).

Major League Baseball ( MLB ) is a professional baseball organization and the oldest major professional sports league in the United States, and the first North American sports league professional baseball franchise to be directly owned by a woman. Major League Baseball has its roots in the early days of professional baseball, before there was a separate league, in the nineteenth century. In 1901, the first modern World Series between the National League and American League champions was held, although the series was limited to just four games and was held in New York. The modern World Series is still played in New York City.

Lead azide is an inorganic compound . More so than other azides , is explosive . It is used in rocket propulsion , military detonators , mining explosives , and industrial applications . Inorganic compounds are those that do not contain any C-H or C-F bonds, and the bonds they form are only covalent (in contrast to carbon-containing compounds such as the hydrocarbons or the alcohols). In general, when a metal combines with an element that has fewer electrons than it has, the metal loses electrons, forming a positive ion called a metal cation. The cation bonds with the electron-poor atom to form a metal-containing covalent compound.

Year 1290 ( MCCXC ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 13 - Pope Benedict IX is elected pope, but he is forced to resign less than three weeks later. He then retakes the position on October 1. June 5 - Pope Benedict IX becomes the second pope (after Stephen V) in Church history to abdicate. September 30 - Henry III of England renounces his claim to the Kingdom of England. October 3 - Pope Clement V and the majority of the clergy in Rome are taken hostage by the Colonna family.

Robert von Ranke Graves (24 July 1895 – 7 December 1985) was a British poet, historical novelist and critic. His father was Alfred Perceval Graves, a celebrated Irish poet and figure in the Gaelic revival; they were both Celticists and students of Irish mythology. Graves produced more than 140 works in his lifetime. His poems, his translations and innovative analysis of the Greek myths, his memoir of his early life—including his role in World War I—Good-Bye to All That, and his speculative study of poetic inspiration The White Goddess have never been out of print.

Norwich is a town in Windsor County , in the U.S. state of Vermont . The population was 3,612 at the 2000 census. The town was named for Norwich, Norfolk in England ,[ citation needed ] although Norfolk, Virginia is in fact a larger city with a much greater population. Norwich is a town in the Connecticut River valley in southern Vermont . It is located at the crossroads of Route 100, a scenic highway through the heart of Vermont, and Interstate 91. Norwich is located on the border with Connecticut , a few miles to the northwest of Woodstock .

Kazimierz Funk (; February 23, 1884 – November 19, 1967), commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk, was a Polish and American biochemist, generally credited with being among the first to formulate (in 1912) the concept of vitamins, which he called "vital amines" or "vitamines".AchievementsAfter reading an article by the Dutchman Christiaan Eijkman that indicated that persons who ate brown rice were less vulnerable to beri-beri than those who ate only the fully milled product, Funk tried to isolate the substance responsible, and he succeeded. Because that substance contained an amine group, he called it "vitamine".

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling (; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994) was a Swedish actress, novelist and film director.Early lifeZetterling was born in Västerås, Sweden to a working class family. She started her career as an actress at the age of 17 at Dramaten, the Swedish national theatre, appearing in war-era films.CareerZetterling appeared in film and television productions spanning six decades from the 1940s to the 1990s. Her breakthrough came in the 1944 film Torment written by Ingmar Bergman, in which she played a controversial role as a tormented shopgirl.

Louis I, also Louis the Great (; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian (; 5 March 132610 September 1382), was King of Hungary and Croatia from 1342 and King of Poland from 1370. He was the first child of Charles I of Hungary and his wife, Elizabeth of Poland, to survive infancy. A 1338 treaty between his father and Casimir III of Poland, Louis's maternal uncle, confirmed Louis's right to inherit the Kingdom of Poland if his uncle died without a son. In exchange, Louis was obliged to assist his uncle to reoccupy the lands that Poland had lost in previous decades.

A business plan is a formal written document containing the goals of a business, the methods for attaining those goals, and the time-frame for the achievement of the goals. It also describes the nature of the business, background information on the organization, the organization's financial projections, and the strategies it intends to implement to achieve the stated targets. In its entirety, this document serves as a road-map (a plan) that provides direction to the business.Written business plans are often required to obtain a bank loan or other kind of financing.

Stigmata (, plural of  , 'mark, spot, brand'), in Christianity, are the appearance of bodily wounds, scars and pain in locations corresponding to the crucifixion wounds of Jesus Christ, such as the hands, wrists, and feet. Stigmata are primarily associated with Roman Catholicism. Many reported stigmatics are members of Catholic religious orders. St. Francis of Assisi was the first recorded stigmatic. For over fifty years, St. Padre Pio of Pietrelcina of the Order of Friars Minor Capuchin reported stigmata which were studied by several 20th-century physicians.

A semi-automatic rifle is an autoloading rifle that fires one round each pull of the trigger . For comparison , a single shot rifle requires the user to load a cartridge and then place it in the breach before firing. This type of rifle was made popular by John Garand who designed the M1 Garand during world war 2 and used it himself. John Garand won the Colt Gold Cup in 1919 and the U.S. Nationals in 1922, with an AR-10, and also set a world record that stood until the 1970s. M1 Garand Rifle
The rifle was originally named "Automatic Rifle, cal.

Louis the Roman  (7 May 1328 – 17 May 1365) was the eldest son of Holy Roman Emperor, Louis IV the Bavarian, by his second wife, Margaret II, Countess of Hainaut, and a member of the House of Wittelsbach. Louis was Duke of Upper Bavaria as Louis VI (1347–1365) and Margrave of Brandenburg (1351–1365) as Louis II. As of 1356, he also served as Prince-Elector of Brandenburg.BiographyLouis was born in Rome when his parents travelled there for his father's coronation as Holy Roman Emperor, hence his nickname "the Roman".

Provincetown is a New England town located at the extreme tip of Cape Cod in Barnstable County , Massachusetts , United States . The population was 3,442 at the 2010 census. The town includes a number of beaches and is a popular tourist destination during the summer season. The Pilgrims stayed in the area, now known as Race Point , during their exploration of Cape Cod in 1620. The area is also home to the historic Province Lands Charitable Foundation, Inc., a local land conservation organization that has permanently preserved a total of 9,561 acres of town land and waters.

Jon Howard Appleton (January 4, 1939 – January 30, 2022) was an American composer, an educator and a pioneer in electro-acoustic music. His earliest compositions in the medium, e.g. "Chef d'Oeuvre" and "Newark Airport Rock" (1967) attracted attention because they established a new tradition some have called programmatic electronic music. In 1970, he won Guggenheim, Fulbright and American-Scandinavian Foundation fellowships. When he was twenty-eight years old, he joined the faculty of Dartmouth College where he established one of the first electronic music studios in the United States.

Year 1491 ( MCDXCI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. August 28 - Vlad III is declared Voivode of Wallachia. January 30 - The Treaty of Granada, by which the Emirate of Granada recognizes Ferdinand and Isabella of Castile as their sovereigns, thus ending the last remnants of Muslim rule in Spain after eight centuries. February 23 - Martin Luther is summoned before Charles V's Council of Worms and declared an outlaw and heretic. June 17 - Vlad III is declared Voivode of Vallachia, his uncle Mircea the Elder being in prison for 11 months.

Gravity , or gravitation, is a natural phenomenon by which all things with mass or energy, including planets, stars, galaxies and even light, are attracted to (or gravitate toward) one another. On Earth, gravity gives weight to physical objects, and the Moon's gravity causes the tides of the oceans. The gravitational attraction of the original gaseous matter present in the Universe caused it to begin coalescing and forming stars and caused the stars to group together into galaxies, so gravity is responsible for many of the large-scale structures in the Universe.

Edmund of Abingdon ( also known as Edmund Rich , St Edmund of Canterbury , Edmund of Pontigny , French Saint Edme , Italian San Edmondo ) was an English historian, theologian and statesman. After studying in Paris , he became bishop of Bath (1219-1245) , and was then sent to France as an emissary in 1225 by King Henry 3 . In 1234 he was consecrated as an Apostolic Legate for the kingdoms of France and England, where he served as an ambassador to France, Scotland and other countries. After his return to England he became Master of the King's Scholars in Paris in 1240.

A Tesla coil is an electrical resonant transformer circuit designed by inventor Nikola Tesla in 1891 . It is used to generate high-voltage, high-frequency alternating current which can be used to create a plasma in the air or other conducting medium. Tesla coil circuits are also used in some electronic devices, such as Tesla-coil ignition systems , and certain kinds of radio transmitters. Tesla first conceived of and built Tesla coils to study high-voltage resonance phenomena. His first patent on a Tesla coil, United States Patent 512,188, was issued in June 1891 .

The Zwinger is a palatial complex with gardens in Dresden , Germany . Designed by architect Matthäus Daniel Pöppelmann , the Zwinger is best known as the location of three major royal collections: the Porcelain Collection , the Gemälde Galerie (Painted Gallery), and the Grünes Gewölbe (Green Vault) , which together with the Dresdner Frauenkirche ( Frauenkirche ) constituted the most important building project in 18th century Germany . After the reconstruction of the Frauenkirche (1894–1905), work began on converting the eastern wing of the Zwinger into an open-air exhibition gallery .

Year 1317 (MCCCXVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  December  December 10–11 – King Birger of Sweden has his brothers, Dukes Eric and Valdemar, captured and thrown into a dungeon during the Nyköping Banquet, as a revenge for their imprisonment of him in the Håtuna games in 1306. As the dukes soon starve to death in the dungeon, their followers rebel against the king, throwing Sweden into civil war, in which the king is deposed in 1318. Date unknown  The Great Famine of 1315-1317 comes to an end.

Ross Powers ( born February 10 , 1979 ) is an American world champion halfpipe snowboarder from South Londonderry , Vermont , US. He has competed in three Winter Olympic Games , winning two Olympic medals , one gold and one silver. In 2006 Powers won the first medal for the US in Olympic halfpipe history, earning a silver medal behind his friend Shaun White . He won a silver medal again at Vancouver 2010 , and finished with bronze in 2014 in Sochi . Powers is one of the first snowboarders to land a double backside 1260 in the halfpipe, as well as being the first to land the double frontside 1260.

The Cathedral of St. John the Divine (sometimes referred to as St. John's and also nicknamed St. John the Unfinished) is the cathedral of the Episcopal Diocese of New York. It is at 1047 Amsterdam Avenue in the Morningside Heights neighborhood of Manhattan in New York City, between West 110th Street (also known as Cathedral Parkway) and West 113th Street.The cathedral is an unfinished building, with only two-thirds of the proposed building completed, due to several major stylistic changes and work interruptions. The original design, in the Byzantine Revival and Romanesque Revival styles, began construction in 1892.

Perpignan (, , ;  ;  ;  ) is the prefecture of the Pyrénées-Orientales department (known as Northern Catalonia) in southern France, in the heart of the plain of Roussillon, at the foot of the Pyrenees a few kilometres from the Mediterranean Sea and the scrublands of the Corbières massif. It is the centre of the Perpignan Mediterranée Métropole metropolitan area.In 2016 Perpignan had a population of 121,875 (Perpignanais(e) in French, Perpinyanés(a) in Catalan) in the commune proper, and the metropolitan area had a total population of 268,577, making it the last major French city before the Spanish border.

Year 1219 (MCCXIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Fifth Crusade  February – Pelagius orders the Crusader army to prepare an attack against the Egyptians, but is unsuccessful because of the weather and strength of the defenders. Sultan Al-Kamil, in command of the Egyptian forces, is almost overthrown by a conspiracy in his entourage. He considers fleeing to the Ayyubid Emirate of Yemen, ruled by his son Al-Mas'ud Yusuf, but the arrival of his brother Al-Mu'azzam with reinforcements from Syria, ends the conspiracy.

Year 1035 ( MXXXV ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. June 16 - Pope Sergius I succeeds Pope John XIX as the 125th pope. Pope Sergius I, (died May 27, 1012), pope from 1009 to 1012, was born in Venice of noble parentage, and at the age of fifteen was placed by his father at the feet of Peter Damian, at that time the most illustrious member of the Roman Curia. Pope Damasus II was elected pope on July 11, 1048, to succeed the recently deceased Benedict IX.

Events < onlyinclude > January–March January 1 – The Abenaki tribe and the Massachusetts colonists sign a treaty , ending their hostilities and providing for a ten-year peace period. January 7 – Massachusetts governor Simon Bradstreet sends an expedition of 120 men to capture the Abenaki village of Norwottock. January 16 – Captain Samuel Waldo and 35 soldiers are killed in a raid on the Wabanaki village of Norwottock. February 18 – In the Norwottock raid, 64 Wabanaki men, women and children are killed; 28 are captured and enslaved, 20 escape into the woods.

Dissociative identity disorder ( DID ) , previously known as multiple personality disorder ( MPD ) , is a mental condition in which one person’s identity is splintered among multiple separate personalities. The alternative name of multiple personality disorder ( MPD ) has been criticized, as people diagnosed with this condition typically exhibit symptoms of DID, which means that they are only one person, not multiple personalities, and that these are actually different “states” within the person. The term “identity alteration disorder” is sometimes used in clinical contexts to describe the condition that is now known as DID.

Year 1509 ( MDIX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. January 26 - Battle of Cerignola ( Italian : Battaglia di Cerignola ) - Spanish army under the Duke of Pastrengo defeat the French troops under the Duke of Joyeuse at Cerignola. March 11 - Henry VII is crowned King of the Romans at Aachen. April 23 - Pope Julius II dies, to be replaced by Pope Leo X . August 21 - Henry VIII becomes King of England on the death of his father, Henry VII.

Events  January–March  January 5 – The Brandenburger—African Company, of the German state of Brandenburg, signs a greaty with representatives of the Ahanta tribe in what is now Ghana to establish the fort and settlement of Groß Friedrichsburg in honor of Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg. The location is later renamed Princes Town, also called Pokesu. January 6 – The tragic opera Phaëton, written by Jean-Baptiste Lully and Philippe Quinault, is premiered at the Palace of Versailles. January 27 – Gove's Rebellion breaks out in the Province of New Hampshire in North America as a revolt against the Royal Governor, Edward Cranfield.

Year 1526 (MDXXVI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 14 – Treaty of Madrid: Peace is declared between Francis I of France and Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor. Francis agrees to cede Burgundy and abandons all claims to Flanders, Artois, Naples, and Milan. April 21 – Battle of Panipat: Babur becomes Mughal emperor, invades northern India and captures Delhi, beginning the richest dynasty in the world, the Mughal Empire, which lasts until 1857.

Charles Pierce ( July 14 , 1926 – May 31 , 1999 ) was one of the 20th century 's most celebrated photographers. Pierce worked in black-and-white film photography for his entire career, and he was best known for his portraits and for photographing celebrities. His career began in 1948 with a portrait of boxer Sugar Ray Robinson , and he worked with the most popular musicians, actors, models, politicians, and other public figures of his time. He won the Robert Capa Gold Medal for his photographs of the Korean War and his pictures have been featured on magazine covers.

Year 1490 (MCDXC) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 4 – Anne of Brittany announces that all those who ally themselves with the king of France will be considered guilty of the crime of Lèse-majesté. March 13 – Charles II becomes Duke of Savoy at age 1; his mother Blanche of Montferrato is regent. March or April – 1490 Ch'ing-yang event, a presumed meteor shower or air burst over Qingyang in Ming dynasty China, said to have caused casualties.

Events < onlyinclude > January–June January 17 – The Treaty of Königsberg is signed , establishing an alliance between Charles Albert of Saxony , King of Saxony , and the Russian Empire . February 6 – An Austrian army invades the Ticino , the first Italian campaign of the War of the Second Coalition . February 9 – The United Provinces declare war on France , initiating the Netherlands Campaign of the War of the Second Coalition. April 11 – Napoleonic Wars – Battle of Raszyn : The armies of the French First and Fourth Republics defeat Russian forces in the opening battle of the Polish campaign of the Napoleonic wars.

Provincetown  is a New England town located at the extreme tip of Cape Cod in Barnstable County, Massachusetts, in the United States. A small coastal resort town with a year-round population of 3,664 as of the 2020 United States Census, Provincetown has a summer population as high as 60,000. Often called "P-town" or "P'town", the locale is known for its beaches, harbor, artists, tourist industry, and as a popular vacation destination for the LGBT+ community.History At the time of European encounter, the area was long settled by the historic Nauset tribe, who had a settlement known as "Meeshawn".

A battering ram is a siege engine that originated in ancient times and was designed to break open the masonry walls of fortifications or city gates that had been put under siege. It was also used to break down doors and walls in general assaults. It consisted of a strong pole, typically oak, which could be thrust into the wall of a building, and a counterweighted hammer or striking iron to deliver a forceful blow against it, allowing it to split the masonry and break down the defensive structure. A siege ram in the British Museum, London; it is dated to ca.

Year 1484 (MCDLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 26 – William Caxton, the first printer of books in English, prints his translation of Aesop's Fables in London. May 30 – Charles VIII of France (Charles l'Affable) is crowned. June 22 – The first known book printed by a woman, Anna Rügerin, is an edition of Eike of Repgow's compendium of customary law, the Sachsenspiegel, produced in Augsburg. July 6 – Portuguese sea captain Diogo Cão finds the mouth of the Congo River.

In the Swedish calendar it was a leap year starting on Wednesday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  January 1 – Charles XII of Sweden invades Russia, by crossing the frozen Vistula River with 40,000 men. January 12 – Shahu I becomes the fifth Chhatrapati of the Maratha Empire in the Indian subcontinent. February 26 – HMS Falmouth, a 50-gun fourth-rate ship of the line built at Woolwich Dockyard for the Royal Navy, is launched. March 11 – Queen Anne withholds Royal Assent from the Scottish Militia Bill, the last time a British monarch vetoes legislation.

Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe . It was published by Sierra from 1991 to 1997, and was also released for the N-Gage handheld system. Originally developed and released for Apple II systems, the game features Larry Laffer as the main protagonist, an unsuccessful and overweight salesman of software products. Along his path to find his true love, he must navigate through a series of dangerous traps and sexual situations, often ending up with Larry getting arrested for lewd conduct, being beaten up by angry mobs or being forced to undergo unorthodox therapies.

Hawaii Five-O is an American police procedural drama series produced by CBS Productions and created by Leonard Freeman. Set in Hawaii, the show originally aired for 12 seasons from 1968 to 1980, and continues in reruns. At the airing of its last episode, it was the longest-running police drama in American television history and the last fictional primetime show that debuted in the 1960s to leave the air.The show starred Jack Lord as Detective Captain Stephen "Steve" McGarrett, the head of a special state police task force in Hawaii which was based on an actual unit that existed under martial law after  World War II.

Year 1387 ( MCCCLXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar . Sunni Muslims consider it the 120th year of the Hijra , the emigration of Muhammad from Mecca to Medina. It was an average year for Earthquakes : there were 9, in varying magnitudes, of which 6 were of magnitude 7.5 or greater; including one great earthquake of magnitude 8.25 or greater . Dates of the 1380s :
August 3 – King John II of Portugal declares that he is a Christian and abandons his Muslim faith in order to obtain papal approval to marry Beatrice of Portugal .

Events  January–June  January 14 – Portuguese Restoration War – Battle of the Lines of Elvas: The Portuguese beat the Spanish. January 24 – Pierre Corneille's Oedipe premieres in Paris. February 2 – Jan van Riebeeck produces the first South African wine, at the Cape of Good Hope. February 11 – The Assault on Copenhagen by Swedish forces is beaten back, with heavy losses. February 16 – The first known cheque (400 pounds) is written. April 22 – Lord Protector Richard Cromwell dissolves the English Parliament. May 21 – The Kingdom of France, the Commonwealth of England and the Dutch Republic sign the Concert of The Hague.

Year 1452 ( MCDLII ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the Roman calendar, which did not have January and February, this year would be 599 Ab urbe condita . Year 1452 ( MCDLVII ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the Roman calendar, which did not have January or February, this year would have been 599 Ab urbe condita . Year 1452 ( MCDLVII ) was a leap year starting on Saturday of the Julian calendar.

Winter sports or winter activities are competitive sports or non-competitive recreational activities which are played on snow or ice. Most are variations of skiing, ice skating and sledding. Traditionally, such games were only played in cold areas during winter, but artificial snow and artificial ice allow more flexibility. Playing areas and fields consist of either snow or ice. Artificial ice can be used to provide ice rinks for ice skating, ice hockey, ringette, indoor broomball, bandy, rink bandy, rinkball, and spongee in a milder climate.

Events  January–June  January–June – The Swiss Peasant War is fought. January 3 – By the Coonan Cross Oath, the Eastern Church in India cuts itself off from colonial Portuguese tutelage. February 2 – New Amsterdam (later renamed New York City) is incorporated. February 3 – Cardinal Mazarin returns to Paris from exile. March 14 – A Dutch fleet defeats the English in the Battle of Leghorn; the Dutch commander, Johan van Galen, later dies of his wounds. April 20 – Oliver Cromwell expels the Rump Parliament in England.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence ( August 8 , 1901 – August 27 , 1958 ) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist who won the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1939 for his work on the development of the cyclotron . He founded the University of California Radiation Laboratory, better known as the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, and is known as the “Father of the UC Rad Lab”. A native of Catawissa, Missouri , Lawrence graduated from the University of Missouri with a degree in physics in 1924. He received a Master of Arts and a Master of Science in Physics and Chemistry from the University of Chicago .

Year 1059 ( MLIX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. July 16 – The first Crusade is officially launched with the departure of Pope Urban II's delegates to the Council of Clermont in the presence of Emperor Alexios I.
September 21 – Pope Urban II issues the "crusader's blessing" at Clermont-Ferrand to the knights of Christendom assembled in council. October 29 – The first crusaders begin their march from Constantinople into Asia Minor. Crusade against the Byzantines. March 30 – Emperor Henry IV (Holy Roman Emperor) marries Constance of Sicily.

Year 1210 (MCCX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  May – The Second Parliament of Ravennika, convened by Emperor Henry of Flanders, is held in the town of Ravennika in Central Greece, in order to resolve the differences between the princes of Frankish Greece, and the Roman Catholic clergy of their domains. The assembled nobles and prelates conclude a concordat, which recognizes the independence and immunity of all Church property in Frankish Greece from any feudal duties.

Events  January–June  January 1 Colonel George Monck (with his regiment) crosses from Scotland to England at the village of Coldstream, and begins his advance towards London in support of the English Restoration. Samuel Pepys begins his diary. February 3 – George Monck and his regiment arrive in London. February 13 – Charles XI becomes king of Sweden at the age of five, upon the death of his father, Charles X Gustavus. February 27 – John Thurloe is reinstated as England's Secretary of State, having been deprived of his offices late in the previous year. March 16 – The Long Parliament disbands.

Year 1332 (MCCCXXXII) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  February 18 – Amda Seyon I, Emperor of Ethiopia, begins his campaigns in the southern Muslim provinces (possibly in 1329). August 10–11 – Battle of Dupplin Moor: Edward Balliol rebels, and the English defeat the loyalists of David II in Scotland. September – Edward Balliol crowns himself King of Scotland. November 7 – Lucerne joins the Swiss Confederation with Uri, Schwyz, and Unterwalden. December 16 – Battle of Annan: The loyalists of David II defeat Edward Balliol in Scotland.

Year 1468 (MCDLXVIII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December June 30 – Catherine Cornaro is married by proxy to James II of Cyprus, beginning the Venetian conquest of Cyprus. August 26 – Baeda Maryam succeeds his father Zara Yaqob, as Emperor of Ethiopia. October 14 – The Treaty of Péronne is signed by Charles the Bold, Duke of Burgundy, and Louis XI of France. Date unknown  The Lancastrians surrender Harlech Castle to King Edward IV of England after a seven-year siege.

Year 1131 ( MCXXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. September 9 – The city of Kiev is sacked by invading forces under the Mongolian warlord Batu Khan, who destroys the city. October 3 – Battle of the Golden Spurs: Main force of the Ghibellin league, consisting of 80,000 infantry and cavalry, is defeated by 18,000 Frisian and Flemish infantry at the Battle of Courtrai in Flanders. October 19 – The German city of Kulmbach is sacked and almost completely destroyed.

Year 1412 ( MCDXII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. April 15 - The War of the Knights of Saint Matthew and the White Cross begins in Italy. March 12 - Battle of Gurzgan: Ottoman army defeats Byzantine Empire . February 19 - Battle of Kulikovo: Timur Lenk is defeated by a Russian coalition under Dmitry Donskoy. May 3 - Battle of Stirling Bridge: The Scots under William Wallace defeats the English . July 16 - Battle of Bannockburn: King Robert the Bruce defeats the English under King Edward II.

Frederick Barbarossa (1122 – 10 June 1190), also known as Frederick I , was the Holy Roman Emperor from 1155 until his death 35 years later. He was elected King of Germany at Frankfurt on 4 March 1152 and crowned in Aachen on 9 March 1152. He was crowned King of Italy on 24 April 1155 in Pavia and emperor by Pope Adrian IV on 18 June 1155 in Rome. Two years later, the term  ("holy") first appeared in a document in connection with his empire. He was later formally crowned King of Burgundy, at Arles on 30 June 1178.

Casimir IV ( in full Casimir IV Andrew Jagiellon ; ; Lithuanian : ; 30 November 1427 – 7 June ) was Grand Duke of Lithuania (–) and King of Poland (–). His reign saw an increase in the power of Poland as well as in Poland s influence on Lithuania under his rule. In Poland, he was the first ruler of the Jagiellonian dynasty (–1572). In his long reign in Lithuania, Casimir expanded his authority and made it stronger and richer than ever before. In Poland he was the first ruler of the Jagieellonian dynasty.

Year 1548 (MDXLVIII) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 14 – Battle of Uedahara: Firearms are used for the first time on the battlefield in Japan, and Takeda Shingen is defeated by Murakami Yoshikiyo. April 1 – Sigismund II Augustus succeeds his father, Sigismund I the Old, as King of Poland and Grand Duke of Lithuania. May 11 – The great fire in Brielle begins. June Ming Chinese naval forces commanded by Zhu Wan destroy the pirate haven of Shuangyu, frequented by Chinese, Japanese and Portuguese smugglers.

Escherichia coli , also known as E. coli , is a Gram-negative , facultative anaerobic , rod-shaped , coliform bacterium . This bacterium was first discovered by German-American bacteriologist Theobald Smith in 1885. Escherichia coli , along with some other closely related species are part of the phylum Proteobacteria, and the genus Escherichia within the family Escherichiaceae.E. coli can be found in a large number of habitats, such as the gastrointestinal tracts of warmblooded animals and various environments in the human body. It is one of the principal causes of diarrhea which may be transmitted to humans and animals through water and foods.

EventsJanuary–March  January 20 – The Parliament of England (under Tory dominance) limits the size of the country's standing army to 7,000 'native born' men; hence, King William III's Dutch Blue Guards cannot serve in the line. By an Act of February 1, it also requires disbandment of foreign troops in Ireland. January 26 – The Republic of Venice, Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth and Holy Roman Empire sign the Treaty of Karlowitz with the Ottoman Empire, marking an end to the major phase of the Ottoman–Habsburg wars, including the Morean War between Venice and the Ottomans.

Year 1349 (MCCCXLIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December January 22 – An earthquake affects L'Aquila in southern Italy with a maximum Mercalli intensity of X (Extreme), causing severe damage, and leaving 2,000 dead. February 14 – Jewish persecutions during the Black Death: Strasbourg massacre – Because they are believed by the residents to be the cause of the Black Death, roughly 2,000 Jews are burned to death. February 19 – Jewish persecutions during the Black Death: The entire Jewish community in the remote German village of Saulgau is wiped out.

The Muppet Show is a sketch comedy television series created by Jim Henson and featuring the Muppets. The series originated as two pilot episodes produced by Henson for ABC in 1974 and 1975. While neither episode was moved forward as a series and other networks in the United States rejected Henson's proposals, British producer Lew Grade expressed enthusiasm for the project and agreed to co-produce The Muppet Show for the British channel  ATV. Five seasons, totalling 120 episodes, were broadcast on ATV and other ITV franchises in the United Kingdom and in later first-run syndication in the US from 1976 to 1981.

A trisomy is a type of polysomy in which there are three instances of a particular chromosome , instead of the usual two at a given location in the nucleus . [1]
There are three primary types: trisomy 13, 15 and 21. Trisomy 13 and 15 are also called "Patau" or "Cat-eye" syndromes, referring to the characteristic cranial facies of those syndromes. [2] Trisomy 21 (Down's syndrome) is also called "Edward's" syndrome. 4 Down syndrome
5 Trisomy 18
The cause of trisomy is generally chromosome disorder during gamete or zygote formation.

Year 1514 (MDXIV) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 10 – A great fire breaks out, in the Rialto of Venice. March 12 – A huge exotic embassy sent by King Manuel I of Portugal to Pope Leo X arrives in Rome, including Hanno, an Indian elephant. March – Louis XII of France makes peace with Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor. May 2 – The Poor Conrad peasant revolt against Ulrich, Duke of Württemberg begins in Beutelsbach.

In physics , optical depth or optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted radiant power density. At optical depth unity , the light reaches a steady state (in an ideal medium) that is independent of the intensity or direction of the original light . This is the case when all paths have the same chance of being traveled. A medium with such behavior is termed optically thick , as opposed to optically thin which is a medium for which there is negligible absorption. The concept of optical depth is also applied to atmospheric and oceanic conditions.

Heinrich Christian Wilhelm Busch ( 15 April 1832 – 9 January 1908 ) was a German humorist , poet , and author , known as the "Father of Humor" in Germany . BUSCH, Heinrich Christian Wilhelm was born in the city of Berlin on the 15th of April 1832. In his childhood he showed a taste for drawing; but when at school he abandoned his drawing-book, and became a great reader. In 1848 he joined the Berliner Freischar, or Free Rifles, was present at the battle of Grossbeeren, and became a member of the national militia corps, which he entered as a second lieutenant.

The Battle of the Teutoburg Forest, described as the Varian Disaster  by Roman historians, took place at modern Kalkriese in 9 AD, when an alliance of Germanic peoples ambushed Roman legions and their auxiliaries, led by Publius Quinctilius Varus. The alliance was led by Arminius, a Germanic officer of Varus's auxilia. Arminius had acquired Roman citizenship and had received a Roman military education, which enabled him to deceive the Roman commander methodically and anticipate the Roman army's tactical responses.Teutoburg Forest is commonly seen as one of the most important defeats in Roman history, bringing the triumphant period of expansion under Augustus to an abrupt end.

January 5, 1697 – Franco-Dutch War
The Franco-Dutch War, 1672–78, or Dutch War of Independence, was fought between the Dutch Republic and France during the rule of Louis XIV. The war arose from France’s support of the Spanish in their attempt to regain control of their Spanish Netherlands territory. The war began with French invasions of both the United Provinces and of Dutch colonies in Asia.

Year 1145 (MCXLV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Seljuk forces led by Imad al-Din Zengi capture Saruj, the second great Crusader fortress east of the Euphrates. They advance to Birejik and besiege the city, but the garrison puts up a stiff resistance. Meanwhile, Queen-Regent Melisende of Jerusalem joins forces with Joscelin II, count of Edessa and approaches the city. Zengi raises the siege after hearing rumours of trouble in Mosul. He rushes back with his army to take control.

.Year 1134 (MCXXXIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events By place Asia  Count Hugh II (du Puiset), in alliance with the Egyptian city of Ashkelon, revolts against King Fulk V of Jerusalem, attempting to take Jaffa. Hugh submits to Fulk and is exiled for three years. While awaiting for a boat to Italy he is attacked by a Breton knight, but survives the attempted murder. Hugh retires to the Sicilian court of his cousin, King Roger II, who appoints him with the lordship of Gargano, where he dies soon afterwards.

John the Apostle (;  ) or Saint John the Beloved was one of the Twelve Apostles of Jesus according to the New Testament. Generally listed as the youngest apostle, he was the son of Zebedee and Salome. His brother was James, who was another of the Twelve Apostles. The Church Fathers identify him as John the Evangelist, John of Patmos, John the Elder, and the Beloved Disciple, and testify that he outlived the remaining apostles and was the only one to die of natural causes, although modern scholars are divided on the veracity of these claims.

Bdellovibrio is a genus of Gram-negative, obligate aerobic bacterium. One of the more notable characteristics of this genus is that members can prey upon other Gram-negative bacteria and feed on the biopolymers, e.g. proteins and nucleic acids, of their hosts. They have two lifestyles: a host-dependent, highly mobile phase, the "attack phase", in which they form "bdelloplasts" in their host bacteria; and a slow-growing, irregularly shaped, host-independent form.Bdellovibrio bacteriovorusThe most well studied of these is Bdellovibrio bacteriovorus, which is found almost exclusively in host dependent growth in nature.

Year 1151 (MCLI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  September 7 – Geoffrey of Anjou dies, and is succeeded by his son Henry, aged 18. After the Battle of Ghazni, the city is burned by the Prince of Ghur. The first plague and fire insurance policy is issued in Iceland. Bolton Abbey is founded in North Yorkshire, England. Anping Bridge is completed in China's Fujian province. Its total length will not be exceeded until 1846.

Albury–Wodonga is the broad settlement incorporating the twin Australian cities of Albury and Wodonga, which are separated geographically by the Murray River and politically by a state border: Albury on the north of the river is part of New South Wales, while Wodonga on the south bank is in Victoria.History Albury-Wodonga is located on the lands of the Dyinningmiddhang people of the Dhudhuroa language group.In the early 1970s Albury–Wodonga was selected as the primary focus of the Whitlam Federal Labor government's scheme to arrest the uncontrolled growth of Australia's large metropolitan areas (in particular Sydney and Melbourne) by encouraging decentralisation.

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc. Before the release of DeCSS, open source operating systems (such as BSD and Linux) could not play encrypted video DVDs.DeCSS's development was done without a license from the DVD Copy Control Association (CCA), the organization responsible for DVD copy protection—namely, the Content Scramble System (CSS) used by commercial DVD publishers. The release of DeCSS resulted in a Norwegian criminal trial and subsequent acquittal of one of the authors of DeCSS.

Year 1047 (MXLVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  September 25–28 – Rebel general Leo Tornikios (a nephew of Emperor Constantine IX) proclaims himself emperor at Adrianople, and besieges Constantinople. Byzantine troops personally led by Constantine repel him, and re-occupy the walls. Tornikios is forced to withdraw, while his followers start to abandon him. Finally, he is captured at a church in Boulgarophygon (modern Turkey), and is publicly blinded.

April 30 – Emperor Yingzong succeeds his father, Emperor Chongzong on the throne of the Northern Song dynasty of China. May 28 – Battle of Bannockburn: The forces of King Robert I of Scots defeat an invading army of the Kingdom of England under King Edward II of England, to win Scottish independence. May 24 – Battle of Gwakye: A Mongol army under general Yoshisada invades Silla, Korea. King Przemysł II of Poland becomes the first monarch of the House of Piast.

Year 1033 (MXXXIII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  February 2 – Emperor Conrad II (the Elder) holds an assembly at the Abbey of Payerne and is crowned King of Burgundy. He claims dominion over the Kingdom of Burgundy which is incorporated into the Holy Roman Empire. Treaty of Merseburg: Conrad II attends a Hoftag at Merseburg and signs an agreement with King Mieszko II. He divides Poland in three parts with Mieszko designated as supreme ruler, in exchange for Conrad's support.

The foreign relations of Albania are its relations with other governments and peoples . Foreign relations are conducted through the Minister of Foreign Affairs, the Permanent Delegation to International Organizations in Geneva and the Albanian Mission to the United Nations in New York. After the Albanian National Awakening movement succeeded in uniting Albania in the 1912–1913, the country's foreign relations were conducted by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, which was created in October 1913, in accordance with Law no. 12. The Ottoman Empire's defeat in the 19th century was a major political event for Albania.

Tequila is a distilled beverage made from the blue agave plant , primarily in the area surrounding the city of Tequila, Gto., Mexico. Tequila is a region of Mexico and one of fifteen regions used for the designation of Mexico's wines. The agave for Tequila must be of the Agave Tequilana Weber plant species, and the production method is defined by Mexican law. Tequila was the first distilled beverage to be produced in this region and is today a major product of the Mexican economy, with an estimated 100 million bottles exported in 2006 .

Year 1236 (MCCXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – A fleet consisting of ships from the republics of Venice, Genoa and Pisa arrive at Constantinople. It is headed by Geoffrey II of Villehardouin, ruler of Achaea, who brings 100 of his own knights, 300 cross-bowman, and 500 archers. Geoffrey, formally a vassal of Emperor John I of Constantinople, breaks the blockade of the city, sinks 15 Byzantine ships and enters the Golden Horn.

Wenceslaus IV ( also Wenceslas ; ; , nicknamed `` the Idle '' ; 26 February 136116 August 1419 ) was King of Bohemia from 1363 and one of the claimants of the Polish throne in 1382. He was the third son of the Emperor Charles IV and his first wife, Maria of Savoy. He was a member of the House of Luxembourg . He became King of Bohemia on the abdication of his father in 1378. He became King of Poland when his Polish brother-in-law Louis I was imprisoned by his son Jagiello in 1373.

Year 1184 ( MCLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. May 24 - Pope John XI succeeds Innocent III as the 163rd pope. Harald Hardråde defeats the Danish invasion army under the command of King Swein III. Hundred Years' War: Treaty of Paris ends the Forsaken War (877-880). Botulinum toxin ( BoNT ) is a neurotoxic protein produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum and related species . It is the reason behind Botox. Botox is a toxin that stops certain muscles from contracting and causes temporary paralysis of muscles. Botox is the only toxin approved by the FDA to treat muscle spasms, excessive perspiration and cervical dystonia and blepharospasm. There are some other toxins used by cosmetic clinics to treat frown lines, wrinkles, etc. These are not yet approved for that purpose and are used by many practitioners as they are much cheaper compared to Botox which is the gold standard in toxin treatment.

Mariner 2 ( Mariner-Venus 1962 ) , an American space probe to Venus , was the first robotic space probe to attain another planet in the solar system. Mariner 2 was part of the Mariner program , a group of space probes all launched in 1962 to study Venus and other planets of the outer solar system. The spacecraft was developed at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory ( JPL) of the California Institute of Technology under the guidance of Robert C.
Mariner 1 ( Mariner-Solar 1962 ) is an American space probe launched by NASA to study the planet Venus, solar wind and the solar corona .

Year 1235 ( MCCXXXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Great Kanto earthquake, also known as the Great Tokai earthquake, occurred on the 1 September in 1235 in the Kinki region of Honshu , Japan . The earthquake caused a large tsunami and fires, killing an estimated 3.5 million people and destroying cities including Kyoto, Kamakura , Yokohama , and Kanagawa . It was the worst earthquake in Japanese history and resulted in over 70 aftershocks in a single day.

Renate Titzia Groenewold (born 8 October 1976) is a Dutch former long track speed skater and road bicycle racer.Groenewold has won several Dutch Championships. In 1999, 2002 and 2003 she won the Dutch allround championship. At the European Allround Championships she has won various medals. Five times she came in third in the overall ranking. In 2005, she won the silver medal which was her best result at the European Championships. In 2001, she also came in third in the overall ranking on the World Allround Championships, which she won in 2004.Besides participating in the all-round championships Groenewold has participated in the championships for individual distances.

Year 1361 (MCCCLXI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 17 – An-Nasir Hasan, Mamluk Sultan of Egypt, is killed by one of his own mamluks, Yalbugha al-Umari, who, with the senior Mamluk emirs, has al-Mansur Muhammad installed as the new sultan. Year 1201 (MCCI) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  July 31 – John Komnenos the Fat, a Byzantine aristocrat, attempts to usurp the imperial throne; he is proclaimed emperor and crowned by Patriarch John X Kamateros, at Constantinople. Meanwhile, Emperor Alexios III Angelos, who resides in the Palace of Blachernae, dispatches a small force under Alexios Palaiologos, Alexios' son-in-law, who is regarded as his heir-apparent. With support of the Varangian Guard, John is overthrown and decapitated by the end of the day.

New England Digital Corporation ( 1976–1993 ) was founded in Norwich , Vermont , and relocated to White River Junction , Vermont . The company also operated out of Burlington, Vermont . The founders were David A. Levin and Robert L. Hockett, Jr. The company was originally called Digital Equipment Corporation of Vermont to take advantage of the tax benefits of the company locating in New Hampshire. In 1979, the company moved to White River Junction , and it was renamed New England Digital. The company was responsible for the design and manufacturing of the DECtalk speech synthesis system.

The governor of Montana is the head of government of Montana and the commander-in-chief of the state 's military forces. The current Governor is Steve Bullock, a Democrat. The office of the governor is one of the five separately elected executive offices established in the Constitution of Montana . The governor is elected by the electoral college, composed of the members of both houses of the Montana Legislature , to a four-year term. In order to be eligible for office, a person must be a United States citizen, at least thirty years of age, and a qualified elector of the state .

New England Digital Corporation (1976–1993) was founded in Norwich, Vermont, and relocated to White River Junction, Vermont. It was best known for its signature product, the Synclavier Synthesizer System, which evolved into the Synclavier Digital Audio System or "Tapeless Studio." The company sold an FM digital synthesizer/16-bit polyphonic synthesizer and magnetic disk-based non-linear 16-bit digital recording product, referred to as the "Post-Pro." The Synclavier was developed as the "Dartmouth Digital Synthesizer" by Dartmouth College Professors Jon Appleton and Frederick J. Hooven, in association with NED co-founders Sydney A. Alonso and Cameron W. Jones.

Year 998 (CMXCVIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – Otto III retakes Rome and restores power in the papal city. Crescentius II (the Younger) and his followers barricade themselves in Castel Sant'Angelo. Otto's former tutor John Philagathos (Antipope John XVI), who tries to escape into Campania, is pursued by German troops and captured. He is horribly mutilated – his ears, nose and tongue cut off and his eyes are gouged out. Crescentius surrenders at his stronghold and is beheaded.

Year 1579 (MDLXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Monday of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  January 6  – The Union of Arras unites the southern Netherlands under the Duke of Parma, governor in the name of king Philip II of Spain. Cape Cod is a geographic cape extending into the Atlantic Ocean from the southeastern corner of mainland Massachusetts , in the Northeastern United States . [1][2] It is frequently referred to as " Cape Cod" or simply "Cape"; the Cape Cod Canal separates the mainland from the cape. With the exception of a small strip of land at the very northeastern corner, which juts out into the Atlantic as the Province Lands north of the Cape Cod Canal, all of Cape Cod is part of the state's Barnstable County.

J. Robert Oppenheimer (; April 22, 1904 – February 18, 1967) was an American theoretical physicist who was professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley. Oppenheimer was the wartime head of the Los Alamos Laboratory and is among those who are credited with being the "father of the atomic bomb" for their role in the Manhattan Project – the World War II undertaking that developed the first nuclear weapons. Oppenheimer was among those who observed the Trinity test in New Mexico, where the first atomic bomb was successfully detonated on July 16, 1945.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Monday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 26 – War of Spanish Succession: The uprising by Bavarians against the occupation of the  Electorate of Bavaria by Austrian troops ends after 75 days, and ends the plans of Maximilian, the Elector of Bavaria, to bring Bavaria under the rule of the House of Wittelsbach. January 26 – Great Northern War: The Battle of Grodno begins when a coalition of 34,000 Swedish and Polish troops besieges the then-Lithuanian city in the winter time and clashes with 41,000 Russian and Saxon troops.

Natural science is one of the branches of science concerned with the description, understanding and prediction of natural phenomena, based on empirical evidence from observation and experimentation. Mechanisms such as peer review and repeatability of findings are used to try to ensure the validity of scientific advances.Natural science can be divided into two main branches: life science and physical science. Life science is alternatively known as biology, and physical science is subdivided into branches: physics, chemistry, earth science, and astronomy. These branches of natural science may be further divided into more specialized branches (also known as fields).

The Asian Games , also known as Asiad , is a continental multi-sport event held every four years among athletes from all Asian nations . The Games were regulated by Olympic Council of Asia, and has taken place every four years since Its name was abbreviated from its original form as Asian Games, which later became Asian Games of the New Emerging Forces in the 1978 games, and again in Asian Games of Unity in 1986 games. The 1986 games was originally scheduled for 1984, it was pushed back to 1986 due to a political conflict between Afghanistan and India.

The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse (often referred to as the Four Horsemen) are figures in Christian religion, first appearing in the Old Testament's prophetic Book of Zechariah and in the Book of Ezekiel, where they are named as punishments from God, and later in the New Testament's final book, Revelation, an apocalypse written by John of Patmos.Revelation 6 tells of a book or scroll in God's right hand that is sealed with seven seals. The Lamb of God/Lion of Judah opens the first four of the seven seals, which summons four beings that ride out on white, red, black, and pale horses.

Donnybrook is a district of Dublin , Ireland . It is situated on the southside of the city , in a valley between two hills , the Dublin Mountains . It is bounded on the west by the River Dodder , and on the east by Stillorgan. The area is dominated by a large Catholic church , St. Brendan's , the parish church of Donnybrook. The surrounding district was one of the two original townships which comprised Dublin in 1592, the other being the North Inner Suburbs. It became a distinct parish on 31 December 1622, but it remained in the North Inner Suburbs District until 1851.

Year 1556 (MDLVI) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 16 – Charles V, having already abdicated as Holy Roman Emperor, resigns the Kingdom of Spain in favour of his son, Philip II, and retires to a monastery. January 23 –  The Shaanxi earthquake, the deadliest earthquake in history, occurs with its epicenter in Shaanxi province, China; 830,000 people may have been killed. February 5 – Truce of Vaucelles: Fighting temporarily ends between France and Spain.

Year 1456 ( MCDLVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. January – King John II of Sweden is crowned. February – The Treaty of Madrid is signed in which the Crown of Castile cedes the Canary Islands to the Catholic Monarchs. Toktar Ongarbayuly Aubakirov ( (Toqtar Oñğarbaiūly Äubäkırov), , born on 27 July 1946) is a retired Kazakh Air Force officer and a former cosmonaut. He is the first person from Kazakhstan to go to space.Early lifeToktar Aubakirov was born in Karkaraly district, Karaganda region, Kazakh SSR, which is now Kazakhstan. After graduating from the 8th grade of a secondary school he started working as a metal turner at the Temirtau foundry, whilst attending an evening school. In 1965 he joined the Armavir Military Aviation Institute of the Anti-Air Defence Pilots.

The 12th century BC is the period from 1200 to 1101 BC . The Late Bronze Age collapse in the eastern and central Mediterranean is usually dated to the end of this period. The Middle Kingdom of Egypt flourishes and expands its influence into Nubia and to the north of Egypt in the Levant . In Anatolia , Hittite civilization grows to become the dominant power of the area, with an empire that spreads from Syria in the west to Anatolia and the Mediterranean coast. In the Old World, the period saw the emergence and fall of the kingdom of Elam in Iran .

Bamboos are a diverse group of evergreen perennial flowering plants in the subfamily Bambusoideae of the grass family Poaceae . Bamboos are the fastest-growing plants on earth, some growing around 35 cm per day at the start of the growing season, and 60 to 100 cm during the rest of the year . In bamboo, branch growth occurs at the nodes , and new canes arise from underground stems or culms. The new shoots grow rapidly and are hollow, with walls only 0.5 to 0.8 mm thick. Bamboos are unique for their hollow shoots, which some use as culverts and building material.

January 5 – Felix Manz, co-founder of the Swiss Anabaptists, is drowned in the Limmat in Zürich by the Zürich Reformed state church. March 17 – Battle of Khanwa: Babur defeats Rajput ruler Rana Sanga. This and two other major Moghul victories lead to their domination of northern India. Dhaulpur fort is taken by Babur.

Events  January–March  January 11 – 1693 Sicily earthquake: Mount Etna erupts, causing a devastating earthquake that affects parts of Sicily and Malta. Maximilian II (31 July 1527 – 12 October 1576)  was Holy Roman Emperor from 1564 until his death in 1576. A member of the Austrian House of Habsburg, he was crowned King of Bohemia in Prague on 14 May 1562 and elected King of Germany (King of the Romans) on 24 November 1562. On 8 September 1563 he was crowned King of Hungary and Croatia in the Hungarian capital Pressburg (Pozsony in Hungarian; now Bratislava, Slovakia). On 25 July 1564 he succeeded his father Ferdinand I as ruler of the Holy Roman Empire.Maximilian's rule was shaped by the confessionalization process after the 1555 Peace of Augsburg.

Proline ( symbol Pro or P ) is an organic acid classed as a proteinogenic amino acid ( used in the formation of proteins ). It is a secondary amine, with an amino group and a carboxy group. It exists in the D and L forms, with L being by far the most common in biology. L-Proline is used to make collagen, an important protein found in connective tissue. Proline can be found in foods naturally, including in meats ( such as beef or fish ), and in some vegetables. It can also be obtained from supplements.

Year 1051 (MLI) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – William of Normandy consolidates his power in Normandy. He fights over the control of Maine (after the death of Count Hugh IV), and lays siege to the fortresses of Alençon and Domfront (Western France). Year 1230 (MCCXXX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  March 9 – Battle of Klokotnitsa: Byzantine forces under Theodore Komnenos (Doukas) invade Bulgaria, breaking the peace treaty with Tsar Ivan Asen II. Theodore gathers a large army, including western mercenaries. The two armies meet near the village of Klokotnitsa. Ivan applies clever tactics and manages to surround the Byzantines. They are completely defeated, only a small force under Theodore's brother Manuel Doukas manages to escape the battlefield.

La Ruffiana is an older female character of the Commedia dell'Arte with a shady past or who used to be a prostitute. She is used most often in relationship to the vecchi of which group she is a nominal member. Ruffiana is most often romantically involved with Pantalone, though his love may easily be unrequited if it suits the plot. She is generally described as being talkative/gossipy, sneaky, and mischievous, but deep down is actually kind. She has been described as an "outsider" that always mixes things up and causes trouble for the rest of the characters.

Year 1033 ( MXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Jan Bos (born 29 March 1975) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist. In the late 1990s he was world champion in speed skating and he competed in the 1998 and 2002 Winter Olympics.Speed skaterIn 1998 Bos both became the world champion sprint and won the silver medal that year in the 1000 meter sprint during the Winter Olympics in Nagano. He won the silver medal on that same distance in Salt Lake City.He competed at the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens in the team sprint track cycling event, together with his brother Theo Bos, who won the silver at the individual sprint, and Teun Mulder.

The Roman conquest of Britain was a process that consisted of the conquest of territory located on the island of Britain by Rome, culminated in AD 43 and resulting in the Roman annexation of all of Britain by the year AD 47. Initially, the Roman conquest began as a punitive invasion of Wales and Scotland in 29 AD, by the general Gnaeus Domitius Corbulo, in which he destroyed several tribal capitals. In AD 43, the full military conquest of southern Britain began by the army of Aulus Plautius, with the capture of the major British tribal capital Camulodunum and the establishment of a colony in Colchester.

The Mattachine Society , founded in 1950 , was an early national gay rights organization in the United States , and the first in Los Angeles , California . Mattachine (a Spanish word meaning “a group of men”) was founded by American activist Harry Hay with the support of a group of his longtime friends. In 1952, the Mattachine Society expanded into a national organization that included activists throughout California , as well as several chapters in other cities in the West. Harry Hay , an Englishman, had moved to Los Angeles in 1928.

The 7th millennium BC spanned the years 7000 BC to 6001 BC (c. 9 ka to c. 8 ka). It is impossible to precisely date events around this millennium, and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological and anthropological analysis. Towards the end of this millennium, the islands of Great Britain and Ireland were severed from continental Europe by rising seawater.CommunitiesPopulationNeolithic culture and technology were established in the Near East by 7000 BC and there is increasing evidence through the millennium of its spread or introduction to Europe and the Far East.

Year 1355 ( MCCCLV ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year is also known as 655 AH and 39th year of Mu'azzam Tarkhan by the Muslim calendar. This is the first year that 14th August is the first Saturday after 28th July in the same year and not the second Saturday, as this was the first year that the date of 14th August in the Julian calendar fell on the 1st day after the Julian month of September, which is the 10th in the Islamic calendar.

Berchtesgaden is a municipality in the district Berchtesgadener Land , Bavaria , in southeastern Germany , near the border with Austria , at the foot of the Watzmann , the third highest mountain in the Alps . Berchtesgaden was first mentioned as a settlement in a document signed in 795 by the Abbot of Tegernsee . This document confirmed that he received Berchtesgaden from the King of Bavaria in a gift. Since then, Berchtesgaden has been the residence of successive monasteries . In the year 1102, the prince-bishop of Salzburg donated the estate to the Benedictine abbey of Reichenbach , which is in the present day province of Salzburg .

Stephen Arthur Cook , ( born December 14 , 1939 ) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has made contributions to theoretical computer science , especially in the area of the formal verification of algorithms . He has made numerous important contributions in the field of computational complexity, including the proof of the polynomial time hierarchy and the P=NP conjecture . Cook's interest in mathematics was inspired by a high school mathematics teacher, and his early mathematical work was motivated by his love of puzzles. Cook has also made contributions to the foundations and philosophy of computer science and in the area of the algorithmic properties of graph and hypergraph .

`` Coven '' usually refers to a group or gathering of witches . The word `` coven '' ( from Middle English covena , from Anglo-Norman covena , couvene ) is from Middle French couvene , and this word comes from Latin concīvus , meaning `` joined `` . This is where we derive the modern word `` concave '' . The word is related to the Latin word for witchcraft, and has had the same meaning for hundreds of years . The Oxford English Dictionary has a quote from 1543 which literally translates as `` Covenants (or Compacts ) made between God and a multitude of wicked men `` .

Year 1145 ( MCXLV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Mariner-H (Mariner Mars '71), also commonly known as Mariner 8, was (along with Mariner 9) part of the Mariner Mars '71 project. It was intended to go into Mars orbit and return images and data, but a launch vehicle failure prevented Mariner 8 from achieving Earth orbit and the spacecraft reentered into the Atlantic Ocean shortly after launch.MissionMariner 8 was launched on an Atlas-Centaur SLV-3C booster (AC-24). The main Centaur engine was ignited 265 seconds after launch, but the upper stage began to oscillate in pitch and tumbled out of control.

Niihau ( Hawaiian : ) , anglicized as Niihau , is the westernmost main and seventh largest inhabited island in the Hawaiian chain, located in the Kauai County of Hawaiʻi state in the central Pacific Ocean . The island is separated from the Hawaiian islands of Kauai and Oʻahu by the Kauluwela Channel and Kauai Channel, respectively. The island measures 7 miles (11 km) by 10 miles (16 km) in area with a land area of 69.5 sq. mi (180 km²). Niihau has a population of 231 people, with a permanent population of about 130.

Peter Halsten Thorkelson ( February 13 , 1942 – February 21 , 2019 ) , known professionally as Peter Tork , was an American actor, singer, and songwriter. He was a member of the musical and comedy group the Monkees. He was born in Los Angeles, California. His father was an actor and his mother was a teacher and a businesswoman. After graduation from Woodrow Wilson High School in 1959 , Tork attended the University of California, Riverside . There , he played the cello in the school's jazz band and formed his first band , called The Relations .

Uracil ( symbol U or Ura ) is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid RNA that are complementary to the nucleobases adenine ( A ), thymine ( T ) and cytosine ( C ). The other three nucleobases in DNA, adenine, thymine, and guanine are complementary with U and C, but not with U. The name comes from the word urea, whose name is due to urea in uracil. This is the only nucleic acid whose base is an aliphatic hydrocarbon, instead of an aromatic amine.

Year 994 (CMXCIV) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  September 15 – Battle of the Orontes: Fatimid forces, under Turkish general Manjutakin (also the governor of Damascus), besiege Apamea (modern Syria). Emperor Basil II sends a Byzantine expeditionary army, led by Dux Michael Bourtzes, to relieve the city in alliance with the Hamdanid Dynasty. Manjutakin defeats with his forces the Hamdanids, and attacks the Byzantine force in the rear. The Byzantine army panics and flees, losing some 5,000 men in the process.

Year 1176 (MCLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Summer – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) assembles a Byzantine expeditionary force and marches towards Iconium the Seljuk capital. Meanwhile, hordes of Seljuk Turks destroy crops and poison water supplies, to make Manuel's march more difficult, and harass the Byzantine army in order to force it into the Meander valley. Kilij Arslan II, ruler of the Sultanate of Rum, hears of the expedition and sends envoys to ask for peace.

Uracil  (symbol U or Ura) is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid RNA that are represented by the letters A, G, C and U. The others are adenine (A), cytosine (C), and guanine (G). In RNA, uracil binds to adenine via two hydrogen bonds. In DNA, the uracil nucleobase is replaced by thymine. Uracil is a demethylated form of thymine.Uracil is a common and naturally occurring pyrimidine derivative. The name "uracil" was coined in 1885 by the German chemist Robert Behrend, who was attempting to synthesize derivatives of uric acid.

A killer is someone or something that kills , such as a murderer or a serial killer . Killer or killings may also refer to , such as: A person who kills animals, especially a hunter who kills animals for food, sport, or profit. Broadly speaking, there are two classes of murderers: those who kill out of rage and those who kill out of love. One is more likely to be a hired professional assassin, while the other has a long history of criminal behavior. Those who kill for financial gain are more likely to murder multiple times.

A Tesla coil is an electrical resonant transformer circuit designed by inventor Nikola Tesla in 1891. It is used to produce high-voltage, low-current, high frequency alternating-current electricity. Tesla experimented with a number of different configurations consisting of two, or sometimes three, coupled resonant electric circuits.Tesla used these circuits to conduct innovative experiments in electrical lighting, phosphorescence, X-ray generation, high frequency alternating current phenomena, electrotherapy, and the transmission of electrical energy without wires. Tesla coil circuits were used commercially in sparkgap radio transmitters for wireless telegraphy until the 1920s, and in medical equipment such as electrotherapy and violet ray devices.

Wenceslaus IV (also Wenceslas; ; , nicknamed "the Idle"; 26 February 136116 August 1419), also known as Wenceslaus of Luxembourg, was King of Bohemia from 1378 until his death and King of Germany from 1376 until he was deposed in 1400. As  he belonged to the House of Luxembourg, he was also Duke of Luxembourg from 1383 to 1388.BiographyWenceslaus was born in the Imperial city of Nuremberg, the son of Emperor Charles IV by his third wife Anna von Schweidnitz, a scion of the Silesian Piasts, and baptized at St. Sebaldus Church.

Solidarity Electoral Action (, AWS) was a political coalition in Poland. Since 1997, its official name has been Akcja Wyborcza Solidarność Prawicy (AWSP) or Electoral Action Solidarity of the Right. Ruch Społeczny AWS (RS AWS), or Social Movement for Electoral Action Solidarity, was the political arm of the Solidarity trade union and was formerly the leading party within AWS.BackgroundAWS was formed in 1996 as a coalition of over 30 parties, uniting liberal, conservative and Christian-democratic forces. Marian Krzaklewski was its first chairman. In 1997 the coalition was joined by RS AWS, and by the Freedom Union.

Conrad accepts his offer, but the son escapes.

In mathematics, open sets are a generalization of  open intervals in the real line. In a metric space—that is, when a distance function is defined—open sets are the sets that, with every point , contain all points that are sufficiently near to  (that is, all points whose distance to  is less than some value depending on ).More generally, one defines open sets as the members of a given collection of subsets of a given set, a collection that has the property of containing every union of its members, every finite intersection of its members, the empty set, and the whole set itself.

May 10 – Christopher Columbus and his son Ferdinand set sail from Lisbon, Portugal on his final voyage to the New World. September 19 – Battle of Fornovo, between Milan and Venice and their allies. Year 1043 (MXLIII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Constantine IX Monomachos sends a Byzantine expeditionary force to the Balkans against the rebellious George Maniakes, governor of the Catepanate of Italy.
