Poltava (, ;  ) is a city located on the Vorskla River in central Ukraine. It is the capital city of the Poltava Oblast (province) and of the surrounding Poltava Raion (district) of the oblast. Poltava is administratively incorporated as a city of oblast significance and does not belong to the raion. It has a population ofHistoryIt is still unknown when Poltava was founded, although the town was not attested before 1174. However, for reasons unknown, municipal authorities chose to celebrate the city's 1100th anniversary in 1999.

Frederick II of Brandenburg ( 19 November 1413 – 10 February 1471 ) , nicknamed `` the Iron '' (der Eiserne) and `` the Great Elector '' , was a prince of the House of Hohenzollern who ruled as Elector of Brandenburg and Duke of Prussia (Brandenburgian Prussia) from 1440 until his death. He also ruled as Margrave of Brandenburg-Lübben and Prince of Neumark from 1425, with his brothers Albert and Caspar. He was the father of Frederick I, Elector of Brandenburg and the grandfather of Albrecht Achilles, Elector of Brandenburg.

Year 1211 ( MCCXI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. June 8 – Henry of Anjou becomes King of the Romans and is elected King Henry VI of Germany. The Battle of Navas de Tolosa is fought in Spain, resulting in the defeat of the Almoravid rulers by King Alfonso I of Aragon. March 22 – Conrad of Montferrat is crowned the first King of Jerusalem. September 18 – King Sverre of Norway is killed. Raymond IV of Toulouse, Count of Tripoli, takes Jerusalem in the First Crusade.

It is one of eight years (CE) to contain each Roman numeral exactly once (1000(M)+500(D)+100(C)+50(L)+10(X)+(-1(I)+5(V)) = 1664).Events  January–June  January 5 – Battle of Surat: Maratha Chhatrapati Shivaji defeats Mughal captain Inayat Khan, and sacks Surat. May 9 – Robert Hooke discovers Jupiter's Great Red Spot. June – Gazzetta di Mantova is first published in Mantua, Italy. It's the world's oldest private newspaper still published, and the oldest continuously published in print.

In cosmology, the cosmological constant (usually denoted by the Greek capital letter lambda: Λ), alternatively called Einstein's cosmological constant, is the constant coefficient of a term Albert Einstein temporarily added to his field equations of general relativity. He later removed it. Much later it was revived and reinterpreted as the energy density of space, or vacuum energy, that arises in quantum mechanics. It is closely associated with the concept of dark energy.Einstein originally introduced the constant in 1917 to counterbalance the effect of gravity and achieve a static universe, a notion which was the accepted view at the time.

Year 1373 ( MCCCLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. ( 22 January ) John I of Castile marries his daughter Isabella to Ferdinand III of Castile. ( 25 July ) The English parliament passes the Second Statute of Kilkenny, forbidding marriages between English nobles and Irish nobles. ( 7 October ) Alfonso V of Aragon is proclaimed King of Naples after the death of his father, John I of Aragon, who was killed in battle. ( 20 November ) King Alfonso V of Aragon is elected King of Sicily.

Year 1056 (MLVI) was a leap year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August 31 – Empress Theodora (a sister of the former Empress Zoë) dies after a 18-month reign, by a sudden illness at Constantinople. She is succeeded by Michael VI (the Old), who had served as military finance minister under the former Emperor Romanos III. Michael is appointed through the influence of Leo Paraspondylos, Theodora's most trusted adviser. This ends the Macedonian Dynasty.

Events  January–June  January 20 – Russo-Polish War (1654–1667): Poland cedes Kiev, Smolensk, and eastern Ukraine to Russia in the Treaty of Andrusovo, which puts a final end to Poland's status as a major Central European power. February – The first theatre in Scandinavia opens, in Lejonkulan and Bollhuset in Stockholm, Sweden. March – Louis XIV of France abolishes the livre parisis (Paris pound), in favor of the much more widely used livre tournois (Tours pound). He also designates Gabriel Nicolas de la Reynie as the first chief of "police" of Paris.

Year 1556 ( MDLVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar (corresponding to January 15 of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar) . March 23 – Queen Mary of Scots escapes from imprisonment in England, with the help of Bothwell and other friends. She flees southwards from Tutbury Castle to Chatsworth House, and then to Carlisle . March 29 – Battle of Boulogne . French forces, led by Emperor Charles V , are defeated by an English army led by John Dudley, the Duke of Northumberland .

Slapstick is a style of humor involving exaggerated physical activity that exceeds the boundaries of normal physical comedy . Slapstick was popular in silent film comedy and in the early years of film comedy. Slapstick comedy is characterized by exaggerated physical humor, visual jokes, and stylized action. It usually involves comic violence and pratfalls and is popular in pantomime, burlesque, and theater. The term "slapstick" dates to 1812, meaning a kind of heavy stick used to hit someone. In the 1840s, a similar term, "slapstick comedy," or "slapstick", came to mean a stick used for hitting.

Lead azide   is an inorganic compound. More so than other azides,  is explosive. It is used in detonators to initiate secondary explosives. In a commercially usable form, it is a white to buff powder.Preparation and handlingLead azide is prepared by the reaction of sodium azide and lead(II) nitrate in aqueous solution. Lead acetate can also be used.Thickeners such as dextrin or polyvinyl alcohol are often added to the solution to stabilize the precipitated product. In fact, it is normally shipped in a dextrinated solution that lowers its sensitivity.Production historyLead azide in its pure form was first prepared by Theodor Curtius in 1891.

Andorra, officially the Principality of Andorra , also called the Principality of the Valleys of Andorra<ref>Funk and Wagnalls Encyclopedia##, 1993</ref> , is a sovereign landlocked microstate in Southwestern Europe, located in the eastern Pyrenees mountains and bordered by Spain and France.9th to 19th centuriesAndorra claims it is the last independent survivor of the Marca Hispanica, the buffer states created by Charlemagne to keep the Islamic Moors from advancing into Christian France. Tradition holds that Charlemagne granted a charter to the Andorran people in return for their fighting the Moors.

Sigismund (26 October 1427 – 4 March 1496), a member of the House of Habsburg, was Duke of Austria from 1439 (elevated to Archduke in 1477) until his death. As a scion of the Habsburg Leopoldian line, he ruled over Further Austria and the County of Tyrol from 1446 until his resignation in 1490.BiographySigismund (or Siegmund, sometimes also spelled Sigmund) was born at the Tyrolean court in Innsbruck; his parents were the Further Austrian duke Frederick IV of Austria and his second wife , a daughter of the Welf duke Frederick I of Brunswick-Lüneburg.

OCaml ( , formerly Objective Caml) is a general-purpose, multi-paradigm programming language which extends the Caml dialect of ML with object-oriented features. OCaml was created in 1996 by Xavier Leroy, Jérôme Vouillon, Damien Doligez, Didier Rémy, Ascánder Suárez, and others.The OCaml toolchain includes an interactive top-level interpreter, a bytecode compiler, an optimizing native code compiler, a reversible debugger, and a package manager (OPAM). OCaml was initially developed in the context of automated theorem proving, and has an outsize presence in static analysis and formal methods software.

Year 1443 ( MCDXLIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The 1440s was the century that started on 1440 and ended on 1449. His reign marked the end of the Middle Ages. His son and successor was Louis II of Hungary, last king of Hungary. On the 13th of June 1342 at the Battle of Lake Poyais in Haiti, the French were defeated by a huge horde of Haitian rebels under the command of Jean Duval Dessalines, who was later crowned Emperor.

Howard Kingsbury Smith ( May 12 , 1914 – February 15 , 2002 ) was an American journalist , radio and television executive . He was president of the New York Times and CBS television . Smith was born in Philadelphia , Pennsylvania . He was an undergraduate at Princeton University and a postgraduate at Cambridge University in England . After a career in the newspaper business he worked for CBS television . He headed the CBS News Division . Smith also served as Assistant Secretary of State for Public Affairs under John Foster Dulles in the administration of President Dwight Eisenhower . He was a member of the Bilderberg Group from 1969 until 1978 .

William Makepeace Thackeray ( ; 18 July 1811 – 24 December 1863 ) was a British novelist , author and satirist , known for his wit , humour and satirical comments on the social mores , political institutions and artistic practices of the mid-19th century . Thackeray's novel Vanity Fair , published in 1847–1848, is a scathing satire on the British society of the time . It is set during and after the Napoleonic Wars . The title derives from a poem of John Bunyan , in which the main character, the personified Vanity , is warned of the seductive and destructive influence of worldly wealth and desires on the soul .

Year 1510 (MDX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Catherine of Aragon gives birth to her first child, a stillborn daughter. January 23 – An 18-year-old Henry VIII of England jousts anonymously at Richmond, Surrey and draws applause, before revealing his identity. February 27–November 25 – Portuguese conquest of Goa: Afonso de Albuquerque of Portugal conquers Goa. March 1 – Battle of Salt River: Indigenous ǃUriǁʼaekua decisively defeat sailors of the Portuguese Empire in South Africa.

Year 1206 ( MCCVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 25 – First Battle of Lincoln: the Scots led by John Comyn the Younger and Henry of Northumberland are defeated by the English. The Albigensians are crushed in the Battle of Muret, leading to the fall of the County of Foix. The second Mongol invasion of the Russian steppe begins. October 20 – The First Council of Lyon is held, to discuss problems in the Church, led by Pope Urban II, including heresy in France.

1499 (MCDXCIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 8 – Louis XII of France marries Anne of Brittany, in accordance with a law set by his predecessor, Charles VIII. May 19 – 13-year-old Catherine of Aragon, the future first wife of Henry VIII of England, is married by proxy to his brother, 12-year-old Arthur, Prince of Wales. July 22 – Battle of Dornach: The Swiss decisively defeat the army of Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor.

Cooking bananas are banana cultivars in the genus Musa whose fruits are generally used in cooking. They may be eaten ripe or unripe and are generally starchy. Many cooking bananas are referred to as plantains (/ˈplæntɪn/ US: /plænˈteɪn/,UK: /ˈplɑːntɪn/) or green bananas. In botanical usage, the term "plantain" is used only for true plantains, while other starchy cultivars used for cooking are called "cooking bananas". True plantains are cultivars belonging to the AAB Group, while cooking bananas are any cultivars belonging to AAB, AAA, ABB, or BBB groups.

Eleusine coracana , or finger millet , also known as ragi in India , kodo in Nepal , is an ancient African grain that has been grown in Asia since prehistoric times and is still grown today. The plant is native to the tropics of Asia, Africa, and Australia . In the past, it was cultivated by many Native American tribes. It was also cultivated in northern Europe during the Bronze Age. Finger millet is a perennial grass . It is widely cultivated in the tropics. Finger millet is grown as a food crop for its edible grain.

Year 1038 ( MXXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. July 18 – Battle of Marj Dabiq: Ottoman Turks led by Sultan Alp Arslan defeat the Byzantine army of Romanos I Lekapenos. Lothair II, son of Emperor Louis the Pious and Emperor of the Carolingian Empire (approximate date). Arab invasion of Sicily: Arab–Byzantine War, 827–902 – Sicilian Emirate is created by the Aghlabid Emir Ibrahim I (until 856). January 20 – Pope Eugene III succeeds Pope Adrian III as the 151st pope.

A Roman villa was typically a farmhouse or country house built in the Roman Republic and the Roman Empire , for a wealthy Roman to use when visiting a particular country or property. It would have been a place of relaxation for the host Roman , who may visit for several weeks or longer, often during the country's winter when it was too cold or wet in Rome for outdoor activities. The host might also be accompanied by his extended family, who would have used the villa as well. A Roman villa was also a country seat where an emperor could retire to hunt and relax with his entourage.

Year 1539 (MDXXXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January – Toungoo–Hanthawaddy War – Battle of Naungyo, Burma: The Toungoos decisively defeat the Hanthawaddys. January 12 – Treaty of Toledo: Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor (and Charles I of Spain) and Francis I of France agree to make no further alliances with England. The treaty comes after Henry VIII of England's split with Rome and Pope Paul III. January 14 – Spain annexes Cuba.

Prince Igor is an opera in four acts with a prologue , written and composed by Alexander Borodin . The score was completed by Nikolai Rimsky- Korsakov and Mili Alexeevich Balakirev after Borodin's death. Prince Igor premiered at Bolshoi Theatre in Moscow on 6 October 1901 and was conducted by Anatoliy Lyadov , who was succeeded by Alexander Glazunov in 1907. The premiere was followed by over 100 performances, but after the Russian Revolution , the score was withdrawn from circulation. There were two performances in 1938 in Paris and two in New York.

The European bison ( Bison bonasus ) or the European wood bison , also known as the wisent ( or in Polish , wisent ) is the largest surviving wild bovid in Europe , and one of the five subspecies of wisent or European bison. The European Bison can grow up to 2,45 m in height, and has a shoulder width of 180 cm. The horns of males can grow up to 2,40 m in length. An adult male has about 30 kg less body mass than an adult male aurochs . In the winter the European Bison gains weight, so that he is about 250-350 kg.

In mathematics , open sets are a generalization of open intervals in the real line . In a metric space—that is, a set that is given a metric —open sets are, in the most general terms, the complements of closed sets. In the real numbers and related fields, it is possible to talk about "open intervals" as subsets of R of the form [a, b) for real numbers a and b with a <= b. A real number is also open if it is an interval, as in the interval (0,1).

Melvin Kranzberg ( November 22 , 1917 – December 6 , 1995 ) was an American historian , and professor of History of Technology at Illinois Institute of Technology . He was best known for his book The Discipline Of Technology , which is one of the "seminal" books of the field. [1] [2] [3] [4]
He was also one of the founders of Society for the History of Technology . [1] He held the position of Director of the Institute from 1965 – 1973. He was also a former President of the Society for the History of Technology (1975–1976).

Broca's area, or the Broca area (, also , ), is a region in the frontal lobe of the dominant hemisphere, usually the left, of the brain with functions linked to speech production.Language processing has been linked to Broca's area since Pierre Paul Broca reported impairments in two patients. They had lost the ability to speak after injury to the posterior inferior frontal gyrus (pars triangularis) (BA45) of the brain. Since then, the approximate region he identified has become known as Broca's area, and the deficit in language production as Broca's aphasia, also called expressive aphasia.

The Duchy of Anjou (, ; ; ) was a French province straddling the lower river Loire. Its capital was Angers and it was roughly coextensive with the diocese of Angers. Anjou was bordered by Brittany to the west, Maine to the north, Touraine to the east and Poitou to the south. The adjectival form is Angevin, and inhabitants of Anjou are known as Angevins. In 1482, the duchy became part of the Kingdom of France, and from then remained a province of the Kingdom under the name of the Duchy of Anjou.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC. It was a period of great change for several civilizations. In Africa, Carthage is founded by the Phoenicians. In Egypt, a severe flood covers the floor of Luxor temple, and years later, a civil war starts.It is the beginning of the Iron Age in Central Europe, with the spread of the Proto-Celtic Hallstatt culture, and the Proto-Celtic language.Events890s BC  899 BC: The first year of King Yih of Zhou's reign is marked by a solar eclipse.

Year 1511 (MDXI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  March 26 - The 1511 Idrija earthquake occurs, with a maximum Mercalli intensity of X (Extreme). The epicenter is around the town of Idrija in present-day Slovenia, although some place it some 15-20 kilometers to the west, between Gemona and Pulfero in Friulian Slovenia. The earthquake affects a large territory between Carinthia, Friuli, present-day Slovenia and Croatia. April 9 St John's College, Cambridge, England, founded by Lady Margaret Beaufort, receives its charter.The Şahkulu Rebellion breaks out in Anatolia.

Juggling is a physical skill , performed by a juggler , involving the manipulation of objects for recreation , entertainment or sport . There are many kinds of juggling , but most kinds share a set of basic patterns which are usually used in conjunction with throws and catches to produce a point of mutual interaction between juggler and audience. Juggling can also be performed in pairs or groups, but the focus of this article is on individual juggling. What was the first piece of equipment invented for Juggling? Anthropologists believe that early man used bones to keep score of a game similar to modern day volleyball.

The Hubble Space Telescope (often referred to as HST or Hubble) is a space telescope that was launched into low Earth orbit in 1990  and remains in operation. It was not the first space telescope, but it is one of the largest and most versatile, renowned both as a vital research tool and as a public relations boon for astronomy. The Hubble telescope is named after astronomer Edwin Hubble and is one of NASA's Great Observatories, along with the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory (1991–2000), the Chandra X-ray Observatory (1999–present), and the Spitzer Space Telescope (2003–2020).

Business is the activity of making one 's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products ( merchandise ), or by providing services for others. This is in contrast with work, which is generally an activity in which one expends mental or physical energy for the benefit of oneself or others, but does not result in a product to be sold. Professionals who work to support business activities, such as engineering, are now often included in the definition of business. Businesses often seek to earn money by way of retail sales and by offering services to their target market.

Events < onlyinclude > January–March January 16 – Francesco Morosini , the Doge of Venice since 1688 , dies after a six-year illness. He was 73. He was succeeded in office by Giovanni Sagredo . January 16 – The Royal Navy sloop HMS Pandora arrives in the Pacific Ocean after a 6,600 nautical mile journey from England in 18 months. January 20 – Peter II , King of Portugal, abdicates in favour of his 6-year old son John V , the Regent, Dom Pedro, Duke of Braganza becomes regent of Portugal. March 13 – Peter II is crowned King of Portugal .

Dissociative identity disorder (DID), previously known as multiple personality disorder (MPD), is a mental disorder characterized by the maintenance of at least two distinct and relatively enduring personality states. The disorder is accompanied by memory gaps beyond what would be explained by ordinary memory issues. The personality states alternately show in a person's behavior; however, presentations of the disorder vary. Other conditions that often occur in people with DID include post-traumatic stress disorder, personality disorders (especially borderline and avoidant), depression, substance use disorders, conversion disorder, somatic symptom disorder, eating disorders, obsessive–compulsive disorder, and sleep disorders.

Events  January–December  February – The Republic of Venice annexes the seigniory of Ravenna, ending the da Polenta Dynasty. February 12 – King's College, Cambridge, is founded by King Henry VI of England. March 1 – Battle of Samobor: The army of Ulrich II, Count of Celje, defeats the army of Stjepan Banić at Samobor, Croatia in union with Hungary. November 10 – Alfonso V of Aragon lays siege to Naples. November 20 – The Peace of Cremona (1441) ends the war between the Republic of Venice and the Duchy of Milan.

Year 1539 ( MDXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian calendar. April 17 – King Henry VIII of England is excommunicated by Pope Paul III, in response to his marriage to Anne Boleyn, which Henry himself had declared invalid. May 10 – King Henry VIII of England marries Anne of Cleves. May 19 – King Henry VIII of England sends Thomas Cranmer to visit Anne of Cleves in Düsseldorf in order to see if he is satisfied with the match. When he is not, Henry declares that the marriage was consummated.

A mace is a blunt weapon, a type of club or virge that uses a heavy head on the end of a handle to deliver powerful strikes. A mace typically consists of a strong, heavy, wooden or metal shaft, often reinforced with metal, featuring a head made of stone, bone, copper, bronze, iron, or steel.The head of a military mace can be shaped with flanges or knobs to allow greater penetration of plate armour. The length of maces can vary considerably. The maces of foot soldiers were usually quite short (two or three feet, or sixty to ninety centimetres).

Year 1318 ( MCCCXVIII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. May 27 – King Edward II of England grants the first royal licence to crenellate to the Mayor and citizens of King's Lynn, at Norfolk, England. November – Battle of Sapin: Louis de la Tremoille wins a minor victory over a Flemish army led by Gui de Dampmartin, Count of Flanders, and Jacob van Artevelde. Maria de Medici arrives in Florence to take control of the affairs of the Medici Bank.

William Makepeace Thackeray (; 18 July 1811 – 24 December 1863) was a British novelist, author and illustrator. He is known for his satirical works, particularly his 1848 novel Vanity Fair, a panoramic portrait of British society, and the 1844 novel The Luck of Barry Lyndon, which was adapted for a 1975 film by Stanley Kubrick.BiographyThackeray, an only child, was born in Calcutta, British India, where his father, Richmond Thackeray (1 September 1781 – 13 September 1815), was secretary to the Board of Revenue in the East India Company.

Year 1203 (MCCIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It was also the first year to have all digits different from each other since 1098.Events  By place  Fourth Crusade  April 20 – The Crusader army evacuates Zadar, and sets sail to Corfu; Boniface of Montferrat and Doge Enrico Dandolo stay behind to await Prince Alexios Angelos. After a brief pause at Durrës (modern Albania), the fleet reaches Corfu. Meanwhile, news of its approach (through spies) have reached Emperor Alexios III (Angelos) at Constantinople.

McLean Hospital ( formerly known as Somerville Asylum and Charlestown Asylum ) is a psychiatric hospital in Belmont , Massachusetts . The hospital began operating in 1811, originally as a hospital for the mentally ill located on Boston Harbor on Long Island , Massachusetts , and in 1835 moved to an 800-acre campus in Belmont. [1] It was a private facility until it became part of Harvard Medical School in 1913. [2] Since that time the hospital has operated as a teaching facility for Harvard Medical School residents and as part of Harvard Medical School's Department of Psychiatry.

The Battle of the Teutoburg Forest , described as the Varian Disaster by Roman historians , took place at modern Bad Ems between 9 and 12 AD between a Roman army led by Varus and Germanic tribes led by arminius. In early 14 AD the Roman Empire, under the reign of Tiberius , decided to conquer Germany, and sent three Roman legions across the Rhine. In 14, 15 and 16 AD , they were defeated by a coalition led by Arminius , and killed 15, to 20 thousand of them, and captured 9, to 10 thousand others.

GNU Privacy Guard (GnuPG or GPG) is a free-software replacement for Symantec's PGP cryptographic software suite. The software is compliant with RFC 4880, the IETF standards-track specification of OpenPGP. Modern versions of PGP are interoperable with GnuPG and other OpenPGP-compliant systems.GnuPG is part of the GNU Project and received major funding from the German government in 1999.Overview GnuPG is a hybrid-encryption software program because it uses a combination of conventional symmetric-key cryptography for speed, and public-key cryptography for ease of secure key exchange, typically by using the recipient's public key to encrypt a session key which is used only once.

Lullingstone Roman Villa is a villa built during the Roman occupation of Britain , situated in Lullingstone near the village of Eynsford , Maidstone , Kent in England . In the late 1930s, a Mr and Mrs Banks purchased a house with the foundations of an ancient Roman villa , and a Roman altar found in the garden. Further investigations revealed a Roman vaulted room and a tesselated floor, which were later sold to the National Trust for £500, who were at this time trying to buy the property, but could not afford it, and were only able to rent it.

Year 1419 (MCDXIX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – Hundred Years' War: Rouen surrenders to Henry V of England, which brings Normandy under the control of England. June 20 – The Ōei Invasion of Tsushima Island, Japan by Joseon Korea begins. July 30 – The first Defenestration of Prague occurs in Bohemia. August – Siege of Ceuta: The Portuguese successfully defend off the invading Moroccans who attempt to retake the city of Ceuta. September 10 – John the Fearless, Duke of Burgundy is assassinated by adherents of the Dauphin.

Louis I , also Louis the Great ( ; ; ) or Louis the Hungarian ( ; 5 March 132610 September 1382) was king of Hungary and Croatia from 1342 to 1382, from the Árpád dynasty. He was also the first elected king of Bohemia (134776). He was the first monarch of the House of Anjou. He was the fourth son of King Charles II of Hungary by Mary of Naples, his first wife. On 14 February 1342, his father was defeated and slain by a party of nobles, who made Louis' older brother, Stephen, king.

Mercia ( , ; ) was one of the kingdoms of the Anglo-Saxon Heptarchy . The name is a Latinisation of an Old English word for "border" or "frontier". It was an early name for the territory of the inhabitants of Mercia in England; the name of Mercia is still found in a number of placenames. In the early 6th century, Angles and Saxons started to migrate into Britain from the northern European coasts. The Angles eventually dominated the north of the country but the Saxons took over the south, forming three kingdoms: Wessex , Sussex and the Kingdom of Kent .

Year 1435 (MCDXXXV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 11 – Sweden's first Riksdag of the Estates is summoned under rebel leader Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, who is elected rikshövitsman (military commander of the realm), in the absence of a king, on January 13. January 13 – Sicut Dudum, a papal bull forbidding the enslavement of the Guanche natives in Canary Islands by the Spanish, is promulgated by Pope Eugene IV. February 2 – The Kingdom of Naples passes to  René of Anjou.

1581 (MDLXXXI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) in the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Thursday (link will display full calendar) of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–June  March 18 – The Parliament of England's Act against Reconciliation to Rome imposes heavy fines, for practising Roman Catholicism. March 25 – Iberian Union: Philip II of Spain is crowned Philip I of Portugal. April 4 – Following his circumnavigation of the world, Francis Drake is knighted by Elizabeth I of England. July–December  July 14 – English Jesuit Edmund Campion is arrested.

Year 1391 (MCCCXCI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  June 6 – Massacre of 1391: Anti-Jewish pogroms erupt in Seville, Spain. Many thousands of Jews are massacred, and the violence spreads throughout Spain and Portugal, specially to Toledo, Barcelona and Mallorca. This event marks a turning-point in the history of the Spanish Jews, with most of the survivors leaving the Iberian Peninsula or being forced to convert. July 18 – Tokhtamysh–Timur war: Battle of the Kondurcha River – Timur defeats Tokhtamysh of the Golden Horde, in present day southeast Russia.

Year 1526 ( MDXXVI ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. April 9 – The Treaty of Cambrai between Charles V and Francis I of France is ratified. April – The English army, under Henry Grey, Earl of Huntingdon, defeats the Scots under the Earl of Lennox and Regent James Hamilton, 1st Earl of Arran at the First Battle of Pinkie Cleugh; Arran is captured. June 11 – French troops led by the Duke of Joyeuse land in Brittany and march on Saint-Malo to reinstate Anne of Brittany as Duchess.

Broca 's area , or the Broca area ( , also , ) , is a region in the frontal lobe in the brain , located on the medial surface of the frontal bone , under the coronal suture . It is located in the anterior part of the inferior frontal gyrus . It is named after the French neuroscientist Paul Broca , who discovered the area. It has been linked to the ability to communicate in language, specifically in speech , and the ability to interpret language and express oneself verbally . The Broca area is involved in speech perception and language production , particularly the production of speech .

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Friday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–March  January 1 – Battle of St. John's: The French capture St. John's, the capital of the British colony of Newfoundland. January 6 – Western Europe's Great Frost of 1709, the coldest period in 500 years, begins during the night, lasting three months, with its effects felt for the entire year. In France, the Atlantic coast and Seine River freeze, crops fail, and 24,000 Parisians die.

Year 1194 ( MCXCIV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. May 10 - John II, Count of Brittany, is assassinated while returning from a failed crusade. October 9 - Second Battle of Lincoln: King Richard I of England decisively defeats his brother, John, 1st Earl of Mortain and King John of Scotland. November 28 - John, King of England, returns from crusade and takes up residence at Rouen. King John of England is imprisoned by the French.

Year 997 (CMXCVII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Japan  1 February: Empress Teishi give birth to Princess Shushi - she is the first child of the emperor, but because of the power struggle between Michinaga and Korechika, the empress is not allowed to go to the palace 18 May: The imperial court decides to pardon Korechika and Takaie under the illness of Teishi Byzantine Empire  July 16 – Battle of Spercheios: Byzantine forces, under General Nikephoros Ouranos, defeat the Bulgarians at the Spercheios River in Greece.

The Quirinal Hill (; ;  ) is one of the Seven Hills of Rome, at the north-east of the city center. It is the location of the official residence of the Italian head of state, who resides in the Quirinal Palace; by metonymy "the Quirinal" has come to stand for the Italian president. The Quirinal Palace has an extension of 1.2 million square feet.History According to Roman legend, the Quirinal Hill was the site of a small village of the Sabines, and king Titus Tatius would have lived there after the peace between Romans and Sabines.

The Commonwealth Games, often referred to as the Friendly Games, is an international multi-sport event involving athletes from the Commonwealth of Nations. The event was first held in 1930, and, with the exception of 1942 and 1946, has taken place every four years since then. The Commonwealth Games were known as the British Empire Games from 1930 to 1950, the British Empire and Commonwealth Games from 1954 to 1966, and British Commonwealth Games from 1970 to 1974. Athletes with a disability are included as full members of their national teams, making the Commonwealth Games the first fully inclusive international multi-sport event.

Year 1239 (MCCXXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Summer – A German expeditionary force under Emperor Frederick II invades the Romagna and Tuscany, hoping to capture Rome. He appoints his 21-year-old son, Enzo of Sardinia, as imperial vicar general for Northern Italy. Frederick also threatens with war against Venice, who has sent ships to blockade the harbors on Sicily. In order to finance his growing need for arms, he institutes an administrative reorganization of the Holy Roman Empire (among others, the formation of 10 vice regencies in Italy).

Banksia is a genus of around 170 species in the plant family Proteaceae. These Australian wildflowers and popular garden plants are easily recognised by their characteristic flower spikes and fruiting "cones" and heads. Banksias range in size from prostrate woody shrubs to trees up to 30 metres (100 ft) tall. They are found in a wide variety of landscapes: sclerophyll forest, (occasionally) rainforest, shrubland, and some more arid landscapes, though not in Australia's deserts.Heavy producers of nectar, banksias are a vital part of the food chain in the Australian bush.

Year 1137 ( MCXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. On the feast day of John the Evangelist, construction of the Cathedral of Santa Maria del Fiore in Florence is begun. The cathedral will later become one of the world's largest churches. The last king of Kievan Rus, Yaroslav the Wise, is crowned as "Grand Prince of Novgorod, Vladimir, and Pereyaslav". The Mongols destroy the Russian city of Kitezh, a city that was the site of an ancient Bulgarian monastery.

Three bobsleigh events were competed at the 2002 Winter Olympics , at Utah Olympic Park . The competition took place on February 17–18. There were 32 teams in the women's competition and 31 in the men's. Each team consisted of four competitors. The order for each team of four was 1, 3, 2 and 4 respectively. This order stays the same throughout the entire two-run event. This event was first run in the Winter Olympics. In each event, the fastest time from two runs was counted. Each team raced two times with the top four times counting.

Year 1445 ( MCDXLV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar . July 21 – Battle of St. Jakob an der Birs : The Swiss peasant revolt led by Arnold von Winkelried is defeated. March 11 – The Wars of the Roses end with the Yorkist Edward IV becoming King of England. August 7 – Battle of Hedgeley Moor – The Yorkist forces under Edward IV decisively defeat a Lancastrian army under the Earls of Pembroke and Wiltshire, the Duke of Somerset and the Baron Clifford.

Photomontage is the process and the result of making a composite photograph by cutting, gluing, rearranging and overlapping two or more photographs into a new image. Sometimes the resulting composite image is photographed so that the final image may appear as a seamless physical print. A similar method, although one that does not use film, is realized today through image-editing software. This latter technique is referred to by professionals as "compositing", and in casual usage is often called "photoshopping" (from the name of the popular software system).

Year 1375 ( MCCCLXXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. November 19 – Battle of Aljubarrota: Portuguese forces defeat the Castilians in the battle which is considered the end of the Reconquista in the Iberian Peninsula. December 25 – A great fire destroys a third of Moscow. January 25 – John de Mowbray, 4th Baron Mowbray and 8th Baron Segrave, English noble (d. 1399). January 31 – Albert II of Mecklenburg-Schwerin, Duke of Mecklenburg (d. 1412).

Jacques René Chirac ( , , ; 29 November 193226 September 2019 ) was a French politician who served as President of France and as the Chairman of the G7 during his career. Chirac served in the National Assembly of France for 32 years, as a member of the French Section of the Workers World Party (PAF). He was Minister of Finance from 1974 to 1976, and Minister of Agriculture from 1976 to 1977, during the presidency of Valéry Giscard d'Estaing . In 1981, he was appointed Prime Minister by President François Mitterrand , and held that position until 1986.

The Khlysts or Khlysty ( , `` whips '' ) were an underground Spiritual Christian sect , which split from the Russian Orthodox Church in Russia in the late 18th century. The term Khlysty was first used for members of a heretical sect of Slavic Spiritual Christians (see also: Spiritual Christianity ). The sect's leader, Avvakum Petrov , had fled to Siberia and then to Georgia after being exiled from Russia for heresy in 1666. Avvakum and the other Spiritual Christians fled to Siberia to escape from the persecutions of the time and were called Khlysty or Khlysti .

The foreign relations of Albania are its relations with other governments and peoples. Foreign relations are conducted through the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Tirana. The current minister is Olta Xhaçka. The current Ambassador to the United Nations is Besiana Kadare.Albania is a sovereign country in Southern Europe and the Mediterranean that declared its independence on 28 November 1912. Its foreign policy has maintained a policy of complementarism by trying to have friendly relations with all countries. Since the collapse of Communism in 1990, Albania has extended its responsibilities and position in European and international affairs, supporting and establishing friendly relations with other nations around the world.

Year 1434 ( MCDXXXIV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Shroud of Turin, believed by some to have wrapped the body of Jesus Christ after his death, is first mentioned in a document issued at Tours. July 12 - The Ottoman Turks capture Constantinople, ending the Byzantine Empire after 1123 years. August 29 - Huldrych Zwingli becomes the pastor of a Reformed (Calvinist) church in Zürich. September 6 - The Ottoman Turks under Sultan Mehmed Fatih II capture Constantinople and make it the new capital of the Ottoman Empire (1453-1923).

Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics was held at the E Center in West Valley City and Peaks Ice Arena in Provo, Utah. The men's and women's tournaments were won by Canada, who defeated the host United States in both finals.Medal summaryMedal tableMedalistsMen's tournamentQualifyingThe final standings at the end of the 1999 IIHF World Championship were used to determine the path to the Olympic tournament. The top six places were given direct entry to the first round, places seven and eight were given direct entry to the preliminary round, and all other participants were seeded in qualifying tournaments to fill the remaining six spots.

Year 1366 ( MCCCLXVI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. September 12 - King Henry V of England lands in Ireland. September 24 - Battle of Acentejuy: Spanish forces under Pizarro defeat the Inca forces of the Atahualpa dynasty. December 24 – King Henry the Navigator of Portugal is elected King, succeeding his father, Afonso IV, as King of Portugal. The Caliphate in North Africa invades the Middle East, with the invasion of Egypt by Amir Suri al-Muluk ("Prince of Princes") Jaqmaq, a Shiite Kurd.

Events  June 16 – The deposed and imprisoned Mary, Queen of Scots, recognizes Philip II of Spain as her heir. July 6 – The Treaty of Berwick is signed between Queen Elizabeth I of England and King James VI of Scotland. July 21 – English explorer Thomas Cavendish begins the first deliberately planned circumnavigation of the globe. September 20–21 – Execution of the Babington Plotters: The 14 men convicted of a plot (uncovered on July 17) to murder Queen Elizabeth and replace her with Mary, Queen of Scots, are hanged, drawn and quartered (the first seven being disembowelled before death) in St Giles Field, London.

Year 1575 ( MDLXXV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the Julian calendar, this year was the common year of the 14th century . April 14 – The Ottoman Turkish army captures Buda , ending the 152 years of the Kingdom of Hungary . May 3 – The Ottoman Empire conquers Constantinople , the capital of the Eastern Roman Empire , which was conquered in 1453; the Ottomans capture the city after a 53-day siege. The capital is moved to Adrianople for two years until Mehmed II establishes the new Ottoman capital at Istanbul in 1458.

A domain name is an identification string that defines a realm of administrative autonomy, authority or control within the Internet. Domain names are used in various networking contexts and for application-specific naming and addressing purposes. In general, a domain name identifies a network domain, or it represents an Internet Protocol (IP) resource, such as a personal computer used to access the Internet, a server computer hosting a website, or the web site itself or any other service communicated via the Internet. As of 2017, 330.6 million domain names had been registered.Domain names are formed by the rules and procedures of the Domain Name System (DNS).

Digital electronics is a field of electronics involving the study of digital signals and the engineering of devices that use digital techniques. It also deals with the implementation of the aforementioned principles in hardware and software. Computer hardware, computer software, and the study of the interaction between hardware and software, is included within the scope of the field. In the past, digital electronics referred to electronics, the study of how to use electricity to control the operation of a device for a specific application. In today's world, digital electronics refers primarily to digital technology.

Louis the Roman ( 7 May 1328 – 17 May 1365 ) was the eldest son of Holy Roman Emperor Louis IV and the father of Emperor Charles IV . Louis IV was from 1325 to 1347 the Elector Palatine , and from 1349 the German King. In the last decades of the reign of Louis IV there were several attempts to establish the rule of a younger line of kings in Germany, and in 1356 he abdicated in order to save the life of his son. After a year, however, Louis IV resumed his office.

Jochem Simon Uytdehaage ( born 9 July 1976 ) is a Dutch former long track speed skater who won two gold and two silver Olympic medals at the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin and won three gold, one silver and one bronze medal at the 2007 World Allround Speed Skating Championships in Salt Lake City. He also won a gold and a bronze medal at the World Single Distance Championships in 2009. He is considered to be one of the best skaters of all times. Simon was born in Bussum. He started skating at age of four.

Nvidia Corporation is an American multinational technology company incorporated in Delaware and based in Santa Clara , California . It designs and manufactures high-performance graphics processing units (GPU) for the gaming, professional design and manufacturing, and artificial intelligence markets. Most Nvidia GPUs are used for entertainment and productivity. Nvidia GPUs also power deep learning and artificial intelligence (AI) that can sense and analyze data. Nvidia provides high-performance computing (HPC) solutions to research institutions around the world. Nvidia is the world's leader in the design and sale of dedicated AI accelerators to the data center.

In metaphysics, extension signifies both 'stretching out' (Latin: extensio) as well as later 'taking up space', and most recently, spreading one's internal mental cognition into the external world.The history of thinking about extension can be traced back at least to Archytas' spear analogy for the infinity of space. How far can one's hand or spear stretch out until it reaches the edge of reality? “If I arrived at the outermost edge of the heaven, could I extend my hand or staff into what is outside or not?

Microware was a US corporation based in Clive, Iowa that produced the OS-9 real-time operating system.Microware Systems Corporation existed as a separate entity from 1977 until September 2001, when it was bought by RadiSys Corp., and became a division of that company. The rights to Microware OS-9 and related software were purchased by a group of distributors on 1 March 2013. The new owner was Microware LP. Microware initially produced a version of BASIC and a real-time kernel for the Motorola 6800 processor, and was asked by Motorola to develop what turned into BASIC09 for the then-new Motorola 6809 processor.

Solidarity Electoral Action ( , AWS ) was a political coalition in Poland . Since 1997 , its official name is "The Civic Platform – the Coalition of Parties for the Renewal of Poland" ( in Polish: Platforma Obywatelska - Koalicja Partii odnowy Polski). The history of this electoral coalition began in 1996 with the formation of the AWS Solidaristic Electoral Action. In this period, the coalition was associated with liberal-conservative political views. Its leader was Ryszard Bugaj. In the first round of the presidential election in Poland in 1995 was held by the coalition of political parties.

Events January–March January 24 – At least 75 residents of what is now York , Maine , United States , are killed by a massive earthquake. February 5 – Louis XIV of France orders the construction of the Versailles Palace begun. February 8 – John Casor of North America , is the first African slave brought to the English colony of Virginia by Europeans. February 24 – The Ashmolean Museum opens at Oxford , becoming the world's first public museum. March 11 – The Great Fire of Boston , Massachusetts , United States destroys over 349 buildings, including Old State House.

Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus . Symptoms typically begin three to fourteen days after infection, depending on the viral serotype (there are several strains). [2][3][4] The disease can be categorized as one of two patterns, dengue fever and dengue hemorrhagic fever. Dengue fever is a milder illness that causes flu-like symptoms, while dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) is a more serious condition that can result in bleeding or circulatory failure. Dengue shock syndrome, a severe form of DHF, occurs when there is bleeding and fluid volume loss.

Year 1533 (MDXXXIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 25 – King Henry VIII of England formally but secretly marries Anne Boleyn, who becomes his second queen consort. January 26 – Thomas Audley, 1st Baron Audley of Walden, is appointed Lord Chancellor of England. March 30 – Thomas Cranmer becomes Archbishop of Canterbury. April – The Statute in Restraint of Appeals in England declares the king to be the supreme sovereign and forbids judicial appeals to the papacy.

Stephen Arthur Cook,  (born December 14, 1939) is an American-Canadian computer scientist and mathematician who has made major contributions to the fields of complexity theory and proof complexity. He is a university professor at the University of Toronto, Department of Computer Science and Department of Mathematics.BiographyCook received his bachelor's degree in 1961 from the University of Michigan, and his master's degree and Ph.D. from Harvard University, respectively in 1962 and 1966, from the Mathematics Department. He joined the University of California, Berkeley, mathematics department in 1966 as an assistant professor, and stayed there until 1970 when he was denied reappointment.

The Æsir ( Old Norse : ) are the gods of the principal pantheon in Norse religion . They include the most prominent gods and goddesses, such as Æsir and Óðinn, as well as many other gods, goddesses and jótnar (giants). Æsir are the ruling gods who created the nine worlds of Norse cosmology. In the 20th century, following the decipherment of the Younger Futhark runes, and the discovery of numerous rune stones and Viking era graves, scholars in Scandinavia began re-discovering and studying Norse paganism and its gods.

Year 1023 (MXXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  The Judge-Governor of Seville in Al-Andalus (modern Spain) takes advantage of the disintegration of the Caliphate of Córdoba and seizes power as Abbad I, founding the Abbadid dynasty. December – Abbad I declares the Taifa of Seville independent from Córdoban rule. Abd ar-Rahman V is proclaimed Caliph at Córdoba. Asia  April – An epidemic in Kyoto (Japan) is so severe that there are corpses in the streets; disease spreads throughout the country.

John Bunyan ( ; baptised 30 November 162831 August 1688 ) was an English writer and Puritan preacher best remembered as the author of The Pilgrim's Progress from this World into that which lies before us. He was also known for writing The Holy War, The Pilgrim s Progress, The Practice of the Holy Life, The Acceptableness of Christianity with the Reformers of Our Time, and many others. He was also an ordained minister in the Church of England and suffered persecution as an outspoken nonconformist preacher. His works have been translated into more than a hundred languages and have sold millions of copies.

Year 1525 ( MDXXV ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. (April 10) The first book to be printed in the English language is published in London: The Very Learned and Godly Historye of Reynold Reynolds by William Caxton (1410-1492). Kristian II becomes King of Denmark, Norway, Sweden and Schleswig-Holstein. Pope Adrian VI issues the bull Dum Diversas, instructing Christian monarchs to eliminate Muslims in Southwestern Asia and northern Africa and "in any of their lands"
August 13 – Battle of Obertyn: The first battle of the Second Polish-Ottoman War.

The Cross of Gold speech was delivered by William Jennings Bryan, a former United States Representative from Nebraska, at the Democratic National Convention in Chicago on July 9, 1896. In the address, Bryan supported bimetallism or "free silver", which he believed would bring the nation prosperity. He decried the gold standard, concluding the speech, "you shall not crucify mankind upon a cross of gold". Bryan's address helped catapult him to the Democratic Party's presidential nomination; it is considered one of the greatest political speeches in American history.For twenty years, Americans had been bitterly divided over the nation's monetary standard.

The Muppet Show is a sketch comedy television series created by Jim Henson and featuring the Muppets . The series was produced by Jim Henson's Muppets Studio and originally aired on ABC from September 21, 1976-August 2, 1981. The show also ran on CBC in Canada, and from 1996-1981, it was syndicated to various local broadcast stations throughout the United States and Canada. The Muppet Show was one of the first successful television shows for The Muppets after their success in Sesame Street. Each episode would feature performances by several Muppet musicians, who would often perform a song during the show as well as interstitial segments.

In geometry, two figures or objects are congruent if they have the same shape and size, or if one has the same shape and size as the mirror image of the other.More formally, two sets of  points are called congruent if, and only if, one can be transformed into the other by an isometry, i.e., a combination of rigid motions, namely a translation, a rotation, and a reflection. This means that either object can be repositioned and reflected (but not resized) so as to coincide precisely with the other object.

Albert III ( 9 November 141411 March 1486 ) was Elector of Brandenburg from 1471 until his death , the first German monarch of the House of Hohenzollern and the first German prince to use the title of prince of the empire ( Prinz des Reichs ). As a descendant of Albert the Bear, Duke of Saxony and Margrave of Brandenburg, Albert III was also a member of the ruling houses of the Duchy of Saxony and the Margraviate of Brandenburg from the 13th century onwards and the first member of his house to receive a title as Elector in 1415.

Year 1444 (MCDXLIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. It is one of eight years (CE) to contain each Roman numeral once (1000(M)+(-100(C)+500(D))+(-10(X)+50(L))+(-1(I)+5(V)) = 1444.Events  January–December  March 2 – The League of Lezhë, an alliance of Albanian principalities, is established in Lezhë; George Kastrioti Skanderbeg is proclaimed commander of the Albanian resistance.

Botulism is a rare and potentially fatal illness caused by a toxin produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum . The bacteria are found in soil, decaying vegetation and the intestinal tract of animals such as birds and fish. The spores of the bacteria are extremely resilient and can survive for many years. Spores can also enter a home through improperly refrigerated home-canned foods, infants who eat honey with spores, or through improperly cured or prepared meats, or improperly home canned vegetables. Symptoms include blurred or double vision, dry mouth and difficulty swallowing. In severe cases paralysis of the muscles of respiration can occur causing death by suffocation.

Year 1395 (MCCCXCV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1395th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 395th year of the 2nd millennium, the 95th year of the 14th century, and the 6th year of the 1390s decade.Events  January–December  February 12 – The army led by Sigismund of Luxembourg is ambushed by Stephen I of Moldavia, on its way back after conquering Neamț Citadel, and the Hungarians must retreat empty handed.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating, such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy recedes from the observer is continuously increasing with time.The accelerated expansion was discovered during 1998, by two independent projects, the Supernova Cosmology Project and the High-Z Supernova Search Team, which both used distant type Ia supernovae to measure the acceleration. The idea was that as type Ia supernovae have almost the same intrinsic brightness (a standard candle), and since objects that are further away appear dimmer, we can use the observed brightness of these supernovae to measure the distance to them.

Year 1439 ( MCDXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Battle of Blore Heath, between Royalists and Parliamentarians in the First English Civil War, in which both sides suffer heavy losses. Edward VI of England, King from 1547 to 1553 and one of the most accomplished rulers of the English Renaissance, following his half sister, Queen Mary I. Sir Thomas More, lawyer, philosopher, statesman, and author of Utopia. Through a series of wars and alliances, the Polish Lithuanian Commonwealth is extended by 35,000 sq.

Events January–June January 23 – The Triple Alliance of 1668 is formed between England , Sweden and the United Provinces. January 26 – King Charles XI of Sweden is born in Stockholm. February – English Restoration: At the Restoration of the English Monarchy , 62 of the 137 members of parliament who are opposed to the rule of Charles II of England are imprisoned. March 14 – John Wilkes is expelled from the English Parliament for publishing a series of critical essays known as The North Briton. May 1 – John Wilkes is arrested and imprisoned in London.

Year 1377 (MCCCLXXVII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Battle of Đồ Bàn: Trần Duệ Tông, Trần dynasty Emperor of Đại Việt (Vietnam), is killed. January 17 – Pope Gregory XI moves the Papacy back from Avignon to Rome. January 27 – The Bad Parliament begins sitting in England. Influenced by John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster, it undoes the work done by the Good Parliament, the previous year, to reduce corruption in the Royal Council.

Year 1396 (MCCCXCVI) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 19 – Martin I succeeds his brother, John I, as King of Aragon (modern-day north-east Spain). July 20 – Queen Margaret I of Denmark, Norway and Sweden publishes the Treaty of Kalmar, proposing the personal union of the three kingdoms of Denmark, Norway (with Iceland, Greenland, the Faroe Islands, Shetland and Orkney) and Sweden (including Finland and Åland). July 23 – Queen Margaret makes her great-nephew and adopted son Eric of Pomerania joint ruler of Sweden.

In the Swedish calendar it was a leap year starting on Wednesday , one day ahead of the Julian and one day behind the Gregorian. Both Julian and Gregorian are followed in Sweden. Leap years in the Gregorian calendar occur every 4 years, except for centurial years that are divisible by , for which a leap day occurs in the year. The Julian calendar originally had a different leap day rule; the Gregorian calendar has a 10 day difference between it's leap years. This difference means that the Julian calendar adds 3 extra days in every 400 years, but this effect does not apply in Sweden.

Events January–December February – The Republic of Venice annexes the seigniory of Ravenna , ending the da Polenta Dynasty . March – Pope John XII elected. April 6 – Battle of Ostuni : Frederick II is defeated by an alliance between the Byzantines and Norman Kingdom of Sicily; he is forced to cede Taranto, but he manages to regain Bari. The Republic of Venice gains control of the island of Zante , while the Genoese Republic annexes Corsica and Sardinia. December 20 – Henry of Hesse receives the investiture of the archbishops of Mainz in Aschaffenburg from Pope Honorius III.

Year 1317 ( MCCCXVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. October 13 – Battle of the Egremont Moors: An army led by King Henry III is defeated by rebels under Henry of Lancaster. December 13 – Battle of the Golden Spurs: Henry's son Edward II of England defeats the rebels. December 27 – Henry's brother Edmund, Earl of Cambridge, is assassinated. January 5 – Pope Clement V, formerly Archdeacon of Avranches, born in Gascony.
