Mu'ayyad Al-Din Abu Muhammad Al-Shirizli, Islamic scholar ( b.

Freestyle skiing is a  skiing discipline comprising aerials, moguls, cross, half-pipe, slopestyle and big air as part of the Winter Olympics. It can consist of a skier performing aerial flips and spins and can include skiers sliding rails and boxes on their skis. Known as "hot-dogging" in the early 1970s, it is also commonly referred to as freeskiing, jibbing, as well as many other names, around the world.History Ski acrobatics have been practiced since the 1930s/1940s. Aerial skiing was popularized in the 1950s by Olympic gold medalist Stein Eriksen. Early US competitions were held in the mid-1960s.

A pine is any conifer tree or shrub in the genus Pinus  of the family Pinaceae. Pinus is the sole genus in the subfamily Pinoideae. The Plant List compiled by the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew and Missouri Botanical Garden accepts 126 species names of pines as current, together with 35 unresolved species and many more synonyms. The American Conifer Society (ACS) and the Royal Horticultural Society accept 121 species. Pine may also refer to the lumber derived from pine trees; pine is one of the more extensively used types of wood used as lumber.

Year 1377 ( MCCCLXXVII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. ... The year 1377 in science and technology included a number of significant events. ... Events The first printed edition of the Bible is published in Bamberg. ... Events August 1 - The Black Death enters Kaffa (Tana) and begins the spread of the Black Death throughout Crimea, and then throughout Europe. ... Events February 3 - Duke Louis I of Anjou is assassinated by agents of his cousin, King Charles V of France.

Gerard Pieter Hendrik van Velde (born 30 November 1971) is a Dutch retired speed skater who specialised in sprinting. He won an Olympic gold medal in 2002.BiographyVan Velde was considered the best Dutch sprinter during the early 1990s, but did not manage to win a medal in either the 1992 or 1994 Winter Olympics. The 1992 Games were particularly frustrating, as he missed a bronze medal by only one-hundredth of a second.During the late 1990s, clap skates became standard in Olympic competition. Van Velde had such difficulty adjusting to the techniques required with these new skates that he retired from skating and became a car salesman.

Year 1160 (MCLX) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) sends an embassy led by John Kontostephanos to Jerusalem, to ask King Baldwin III to nominate one of the princesses of the Crusader States, as a bride for the widowed emperor. Their two candidates are 15-year-old Maria of Antioch, and Melisende of Tripoli. Baldwin suggests Melisende, and her brother Count Raymond III sets about gathering an enormous dowry. The ambassadors are not satisfied, and delay the marriage for over a year.

Year 1464 ( MCDLXIV ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the Southern United States , this date is known as the Easter "rain day." In the state of Louisiana, it is an observed holiday when schools are closed. In other states where Mardi Gras is celebrated, schools may also close for the day or students may observe a delayed opening. 1528 – Spanish conquistador Francisco de Montejo lands on the Gulf coast of the Yucatan Peninsula. 1534 – The Ottomans defeat the Tatars at the Battle of Ofcas.

As of March 1 ( O.S . February 19 ) , where then Julian calendar acknowledged a leap day and the start of a new year , 1700 years after the incarnation of Jesus Christ according to the proleptic Julian calendar , had the Gregorian calendar been in use, the date of celebration of Easter would have been March 25. This date was selected to celebrate the Annunciation of the Virgin Mary , a date of particular significance to the Orthodox Church. However, Easter Sunday has always been the Sunday after the first full moon after the vernal equinox, and when that moon fell on a Friday, the next day was Sunday.

The history of Anguilla runs from the beginning of human habitation, probably via settlement from South America, through its colonization by the English in the early modern period, to the present day. Following a series of rebellions and a short-lived period as an independent republic during the 1960s, Anguilla has been a separate British overseas territory since 1980.Pre-Columbian AnguillaThe earliest inhabitants of Anguilla were Amerindian people from South America, commonly (if imprecisely) referred to as Arawaks. These people travelled to the island on rafts and in dugout canoes, settling in fishing, hunting and farming groups.

Year 1427 ( MCDXXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. February 25 - King of Portugal John I is assassinated. John's wife, Philippa of Lancaster, is regent for their daughter Beatrice. March 30 (Easter Sunday) - King of Portugal Beatrice is crowned at the age of 19. Beatrice takes refuge at her father-in-law's court, where he reigns in her name. March 31 – Battle of Ráckeve : John Hunyadi wins over the Ottomans, but at a high price.

Reginald Joseph Mitchell CBE , FRAeS , ( 20 May 189511 June 1937 ) was a British aircraft designer who was responsible for many famous aircraft of the Second World War , most notably the legendary Spitfire fighter aircraft . Mitchell , known as R. J . by friends , was educated at Harrow School and then went to Royal Naval Engineering College at Devonport , Plymouth . He had a strong interest in aviation . While serving as a sub lieutenant in the Royal Navy , Mitchell was commissioned to carry out a study of an air-cooled Rolls-Royce Vulture engine in order to find the cause of excessive power output .

The picometre (international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures; SI symbol: pm) or picometer (American spelling) is a unit of length in the metric system, equal to , or one trillionth  of a metre, which is the SI base unit of length.The picometre is one thousandth of a nanometre ( nm), one millionth of a micrometre (also known as a micron), one billionth of a millimetre, and one trillionth of a metre. The symbol μμ was once used for it.

Year 1527 ( MDXXVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 20 - King Henry VIII issues a letter of protection for Thomas More and other Protestant nobles. March 28 - Battle of Bicocca: Spain defeats France. June 1 - Battle of Landriano. July 11 - King Henry VIII marries Anne of Cleves. August 14 - Pope Clement VII is imprisoned by Spain. August 19 - King Henry VIII divorces Anne of Cleves. August 29 - Battle of Marciano: France defeats the Holy League, and captures the island of Corsica.

Mercia (, ; ) was one of the kingdoms of the Anglo-Saxon Heptarchy. The name is a Latinisation of the Old English  or  (West Saxon dialect;  in the Mercian dialect itself), meaning "border people" (see March). Mercia dominated what would later become England for three centuries, subsequently going into a gradual decline while Wessex eventually conquered and united all the kingdoms into the Kingdom of England.The kingdom was centred on the valley of the River Trent and its tributaries, in the region now known as the English Midlands. The court moved around the kingdom, and there was no fixed capital city.

Year 1395 ( MCCCXCV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The 1390s, 14th century, is a decade in the history of the European Renaissance, beginning on January 1 and ending on December 31. It is considered a transitional decade during which the High Middle Ages give way to the Renaissance. It is one of three decades that lies entirely in the 14th century, the others being 1370s and 1390s. 1445 ( MCCCXLV ) was a common year starting on Saturday of the Julian calendar .

Bacillus cereus is a Gram-positive, rod-shaped, facultatively anaerobic, motile, beta-hemolytic, spore-forming bacterium commonly found in soil, food and marine sponges. The specific name, cereus, meaning "waxy" in Latin, refers to the appearance of colonies grown on blood agar. Some strains are harmful to humans and cause foodborne illness, while other strains can be beneficial as probiotics for animals. The bacteria is classically contracted from fried rice dishes that have been sitting at room temperature for hours. B. cereus bacteria are facultative anaerobes, and like other members of the genus Bacillus, can produce protective endospores.

Year 1541 (MDXLI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 12 – Pedro de Valdivia founds Santiago del Nuevo Extremo, which will become the capital of Chile. April 7 – Francis Xavier leaves Lisbon, on a mission to the Portuguese East Indies. April 24 – Battle of Sahart: Gelawdewos is defeated by the forces of Imam Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi. May 8 – Spanish explorer Hernando de Soto reaches the Mississippi River, naming it the Rio de Espiritu Santo ("River of the Holy Spirit").

Alpine skiing, or downhill skiing, is the pastime of sliding down snow-covered slopes on skis with fixed-heel bindings, unlike other types of skiing (cross-country, Telemark, or ski jumping), which use skis with free-heel bindings. Whether for recreation or for sport, it is typically practiced at ski resorts, which provide such services as ski lifts, artificial snow making, snow grooming, restaurants, and ski patrol. "Off-piste" skiers—those skiing outside ski area boundaries—may employ snowmobiles, helicopters or snowcats to deliver them to the top of a slope.

The sousaphone  is a brass instrument in the same family as the more widely known tuba. Created around 1893 by J.W. Pepper at the direction of American bandleader John Philip Sousa (after whom the instrument was then named), it was designed to be easier to play than the concert tuba while standing or marching, as well as to carry the sound of the instrument above the heads of the band. Like the tuba, sound is produced by moving air past the lips, causing them to vibrate or "buzz" into a large cupped mouthpiece.

The earliest arrival of people in the islands now known as The Bahamas was in the first millennium AD. The first inhabitants of the islands were the Lucayans, an Arawakan-speaking Taino people, who arrived between about 500 and 800 AD from other islands of the Caribbean.Recorded history began on 12 October 1492, when Christopher Columbus landed on the island of Guanahani, which he renamed San Salvador Island, on his first voyage to the New World. The earliest permanent European settlement was in 1648 on Eleuthera. During the 18th century slave trade, many Africans were brought to the Bahamas as slaves to work unpaid.

is the Latin name under which the "Lamb of God" is honoured within the Catholic Mass and other Christian liturgies descending from the Latin liturgical tradition. It is the name given to a specific prayer that occurs in these liturgies, and is the name given to the music pieces that accompany the text of this prayer.The use of the title "Lamb of God" in liturgy is based on , in which St. John the Baptist, upon seeing Jesus, proclaims "Behold, the Lamb of God, who takes away the sin of the world!

Freestyle skiing is a skiing discipline comprising aerials , moguls , cross , half-pipe , slopestyle and big air as events, of which half-pipe and slopestyle competitions have been included in the official programme of the Olympic Games starting with 1998 in Nagano, and ski-cross in 2010 in Vancouver. The sport combines elements from alpine skiing and free skiing. Some freestyle skiers may also compete in other skiing disciplines such as downhill , super-G, and giant slalom ; freestyle skiers are not eligible to compete at the World Championships in those disciplines however, as they already have freestyle disciplines of their own.

Ernest Orlando Lawrence (August 8, 1901 – August 27, 1958) was a pioneering American nuclear scientist and winner of the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1939 for his invention of the cyclotron. He is known for his work on uranium-isotope separation for the Manhattan Project, as well as for founding the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory and the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.A graduate of the University of South Dakota and University of Minnesota, Lawrence obtained a PhD in physics at Yale in 1925. In 1928, he was hired as an associate professor of physics at the University of California, Berkeley, becoming the youngest full professor there two years later.

Year 1379 (MCCCLXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  May 29 – John I succeeds his father, Henry II, as King of Castile and King of León. June 30 – New College, Oxford, is founded in England by William of Wykeham, Bishop of Winchester. July 1 – Forces of the Republic of Venice and Ottoman Turks, having invaded Constantinople, restore John V Palaiologos as Byzantine co-emperor. Andronikos IV Palaiologos is allowed to remain as co-emperor, but is confined to the city of Silivri for the remainder of his life.

.Year 1134 ( MCXXXIV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was also the last year in the 1130 s.
The first known Mongol state, the Kerait khanate, was established by Kerait clans. In August 1, Emperor Toba dies, and is replaced by his 5-year-old grandson Konoe. In November 28, Pope Gregory VIII is elected, but he dies in 1137, and is succeeded by his uncle Innocent II. In the same month the Kingdom of Sicily is conquered by Roger II of Sicily.

The Cape Cod Canal is an artificial waterway in the U.S. state of Massachusetts connecting Cape Cod Bay in the north to Buzzards Bay in the south. Originally built in the 1908s and opened on July 29, 1916, the canal is the gateway for the region's commercial and recreational boats between the two bodies of water. The Cape Cod Canal stretches 14.6 miles (23.5 kilometers) from its northern inlet at the town of Scusset, on the Atlantic Ocean, to Sandwich, Massachusetts in the southeast, a town located on the southern shore of Buzzards Bay.

Year 1194 (MCXCIV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  February 4 – King Richard I (the Lionheart) is ransomed for an amount of 150,000 marks (demanded by Emperor Henry VI), raised by his mother Eleanor of Aquitaine – who travels to Austria to gain his release. Henry will never receive the full amount he demanded. In March, Richard returns to England, and remains for only a few weeks before returning to the Continent.

John Bunyan (; baptised 30 November 162831 August 1688) was an English writer and Puritan preacher best remembered as the author of the Christian allegory The Pilgrim's Progress, which also became an influential literary model. In addition to The Pilgrim's Progress, Bunyan wrote nearly sixty titles, many of them expanded sermons.Bunyan came from the village of Elstow, near Bedford. He had some schooling and at the age of sixteen joined the Parliamentary Army during the first stage of the English Civil War. After three years in the  army he returned to Elstow and took up the trade of tinker, which he had learned from his father.

The transport in Azerbaijan involves air traffic , waterways and railroads . All transportation services in Azerbaijan except for oil pipelines are operated by the state. Azerbaijan Airlines ( AZAL ) operates international services. Most of the oil and natural gas is exported by sea through the Azerbaijani Oil and Chemical ports (AIOC) which includes the ports in the capital of Baku, the commercial seaport at Türkmenbaşı, Gəncə, and the small port of Abseron near Baku. Railways are operated by Azerbaijan Railways, a successor of former Russian South Caucasus RR, the Baku Tramway and Maritime transport is operated by the port authority.

In category theory , a branch of mathematics , the abstract notion of a limit captures the essential properties of the limits we encounter in real life. The central notion in category theory is that of an adjoint pair. In a category , such a pair is a pair of morphisms such that the diagram on the right commutes for every object and every morphism . I'll explain what this means now. Let be the category of sets , the category of sets , the category of groups , the category of topological spaces , and the category of manifolds . For every topological space , there is a functor .

ext3, or third extended filesystem, is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel. It used to be the default file system for many popular Linux distributions. Stephen Tweedie first revealed that he was working on extending ext2 in Journaling the Linux ext2fs Filesystem in a 1998 paper, and later in a February 1999 kernel mailing list posting. The filesystem was merged with the mainline Linux kernel in November 2001 from 2.4.15 onward. Its main advantage over ext2 is journaling, which improves reliability and eliminates the need to check the file system after an unclean shutdown.

Adnams is a regional brewery founded in 1872 in Southwold, Suffolk, England, by George and Ernest Adnams. It produces cask ale and pasteurised bottled beers. Annual production is around 85,000 barrels.In 2010, the company established the Copper House distillery for the production of gin, vodka and whisky.HistoryThe earliest recorded brewing on the Adnams site was in 1396 by Johanna de Corby.The Sole Bay Brewery in Southwold was purchased in 1872 by George and Ernest Adnams. The company was incorporated in 1890, and has remained independent since then, producing a range of beers for distribution mainly in East Anglia.

Wellfleet is a town in Barnstable County, Massachusetts, United States, and is located halfway between the "tip" and "elbow" of Cape Cod. The town had a population of 3,566 at the 2020 census, which swells nearly sixfold during the summer. A total of 70% of the town's land area is under protection, and nearly half of it is part of the Cape Cod National Seashore. Wellfleet is famous for its oysters, which are celebrated in the annual October Wellfleet OysterFest.History The area was originally settled by Europeans in the 1650s as Billingsgate (after the famous fish market in East London).

Year 1491 (MCDXCI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 2 – Alain I of Albret signs the Treaty of Moulins with Charles VIII of France. March – The French–Breton War resumes. March 19−20 – Alain I of Albret captures the Château des ducs de Bretagne for the French. April 23 – Granada is besieged by the Catholic Monarchs of Spain, and Santa Fe, Granada is founded. May – The war between the Ottoman Empire and the Egyptian Mamluks ends.

Year 1427 (MCDXXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January – Spring – Radu II of Wallachia resumes the throne for the fourth time, but a seven-year struggle for it ends when he is defeated in battle, and probably killed, by Dan II, who resumes the throne for a fifth term. April – The House of Balsic's rule of Montenegro comes to an end with the death of Balša III. August 4 – Hussite Wars: Battle of Tachov – The Hussites decisively beat the crusader armies, ending the Fourth Anti-Hussite Crusade.

The Motorola MC68010 processor is a 16/32-bit microprocessor from Motorola , released in 1982 as the successor to the Motorola M68000 processor. The architecture of the processor, which was a clean break from Motorola’s previous M68k architecture, introduced several innovations. It included an on-chip microcode ROM and a pipeline which could handle both memory-based and register-based instructions, which allowed it to perform as well as the 80386. However, to achieve this, it had to trade off some features, such as not being superscalar. The final result was the MC68020, which was released in September 1983 and had a performance of about 3 MIPS.

ext3 , or third extended filesystem , is a journaled file system that is commonly used by the Linux kernel and other Unix-like operating systems, as it was developed by Theodore T’so . This system was introduced by the 2.4.0 kernel version released in 2001. With the 2.4 kernel, the ext2 file system was updated with a new journaled data file, allowing for much better crash recovery and protection. The system also added the ext3 data structure in order to store the directory and file metadata, which made the file system more capable of supporting larger volumes.

The 9th century BC started the first day of 900 BC and ended the last day of 801 BC . The 10th century BC started the first day of 800 BC and ended the last day of 701 BC . 812 BC – Roman consul Lucius Volcatius Tullus is killed while leading an army against the Etruscans. 776 BC – The first Olympiad begins in Greece, lasting four years. 771 BC – The Temple of Artemis in Ephesus, which is supposed to have been one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World, is burnt down.

Events  January–March  January 17 – Tuscarora War: Colonel James Moore leads the Carolina militia out of Albemarle County, North Carolina, in a second offensive against the Tuscarora. Heavy snows force the troops to take refuge in Fort Reading, on the Pamlico River. February 1 – Skirmish at Bender, Moldova: Charles XII of Sweden is defeated by the Ottoman Empire. February 4 – Tuscarora War: The Carolina militia under Colonel James Moore leaves Fort Reading, to continue the campaign against the Tuscarora. February 25 – Frederick William I of Prussia begins his reign.

Year 1046 ( MXLVI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Battle of Basra (404) is fought by the Eastern Roman Empire, under the Byzantine general Arsaber. March 21 – The Byzantine Empire begins a successful siege of the city of Antioch, but is repulsed at the gates of the city. A peace treaty is eventually signed. April 7 – Battle of Dorylaeum: The Roman army defeats the Eastern Roman Empire. April 26 – Battle of Antioch (405): The Byzantines defeat an army of the Roman Empire.

Year 1276 ( MCCLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The year 1276 AD is also known as the Year of the Tiger in the Chinese calendar. This is one of several non-repeating 60 year cycle years used in the Han Chinese calendar. The next such year is 2876. This is the year of the male Tiger in the Chinese calendar. Aleksander Nevskiy is elected the ruler of Novgorod, and begins to expand the Russian state to the East, South, and North.

Year 1434 (MCDXXXIV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 14 – The foundation stone of Nantes Cathedral in Nantes, France, is laid. May 30 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Lipany: The Catholics and Ultraquists defeat the Taborites, ending the Hussite Wars. June 19 or 20 – Zara Yaqob becomes Emperor of Ethiopia. Late June – Miner Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson begins a Swedish rebellion against King Eric of Pomerania (named the Engelbrekt rebellion after him), eventually leading to the deposition of the king.

In category theory, a branch of mathematics, the abstract notion of a limit captures the essential properties of universal constructions such as products, pullbacks and inverse limits. The dual notion of a colimit generalizes constructions such as disjoint unions, direct sums, coproducts, pushouts and direct limits.Limits and colimits, like the strongly related notions of universal properties and adjoint functors, exist at a high level of abstraction. In order to understand them, it is helpful to first study the specific examples these concepts are meant to generalize.Definition Limits and colimits in a category  are defined by means of diagrams in .

Year 1347 ( MCCCXLVII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. December 26 – John, Duke of Berry, is murdered in Paris. His body is secretly removed to Troyes and buried in a church there. December 15 – Pope Eugene IV, in his Bull Super Universas, declares the Order of the Knights Templar heretical and excommunicates its members. The papacy later turns over the Templar estates to a military order, the Knights Hospitaller, and to the Teutonic Order. Jean Gerson becomes the thirteenth dean of the Sorbonne.

Maximilian II ( 31 July 1527 – 12 October 1576 ) was Holy Roman Emperor from 1564 until his death. He was born in the Flemish city of Brussels. His father was Holy Roman Emperor Charles V, and he was raised in Spain. He lived in Spain from 1533 to 1548, and spoke only Spanish and Latin. His mother was Princess Isabella of Portugal, and he was raised in his mother’s native Portugal from 1550 to 1558. He learned to speak Portuguese and Latin. He spent much of his childhood traveling between Spain and Portugal.

Year 1515 ( MDXV ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Siege of Rhodes begins in November and lasts into 1516. By 1516 the defenders, under the Grand Master of the Knights Hospitaller, are starved out and forced to surrender. The Knights Hospitaller are exiled from the island, and their possessions, palaces, and churches, including the Grand Master's Palace, are plundered by the Turks and sold. The city, however, remains in the hands of the Christians.

Year 1027 (MXXVII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 26 – Pope John XIX crowns Conrad II ("the Elder") and his wife Gisela of Swabia as Holy Roman Emperor and Empress, respectively, in Old St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. Cnut the Great, King of Denmark and England, attends the coronation, proving his position as sole ruler of the Danish North Sea Empire. May 14 – King Robert II of France ("the Pious") sues for peace with his sons.

Events  January–December  February 21 – The Prussian Confederation is formed. April 9 – Christopher of Bavaria is elected King of Denmark. April – Murad II lays siege to Belgrade. The city is heavily damaged, but the defenders' use of artillery prevents the Turks from capturing the city. September 13 – Breton knight Gilles de Rais is taken into custody, upon an accusation brought against him by the Bishop of Nantes. September – The term of Regent of Sweden Karl Knutsson Bonde ends, as newly elected king of Denmark Christopher of Bavaria is also elected king of Sweden.

Year 1316 ( MCCCXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. June 5 – Henry VI of England issues a proclamation that the Jews may no longer hold land. August 31 – Henry III of England is crowned king of Castile and Leon. October 1 – Battle of Bannockburn: The army of Robert I of Scotland is defeated by a numerically superior English army led by Edward III of England, effectively ending Scottish hopes of recovering lost territories. October 10 – The 60-year war between Pisa and Genoa ends, when Pisa surrenders to the Genoese.

Year 1468 ( MCDLXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In Japan, the Azuchi-Momoyama period begins. Ming campaigns against Mongolian peoples. The Mongols under Bayan and Ligdan Khaan attack and drive Ming general Xiangyun Liu and his troops out of Xingjiang, however Liu is later replaced by Gao Xingzhi. Mongolian campaigns in China: The Ming campaigns against the Mongols. Bayan becomes khan of all Mongolian tribes, the Mongols are divided into several kingdoms. Genghis Khan becomes the chief of a group of Mongols.

Poltava ( , ; ) is a city located on the Vorskla River in central Ukraine . It is the administrative center of the surrounding Poltava Oblast and of the surrounding Poltava Raion . Population: 291,913 (2006 est. ); 272,000. It is located in the historical region of Maeotis , in the valley of the Vorskla River, in the area that used to be inhabited by the Tauri people before their assimilation by Scythians around the 5th century BC. In 1604 and in 1709 the city was destroyed by the forces of the Crimean Khanate.

A sifaka   is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates. The name of their family is an onomatopoeia of their characteristic "shi-fak" alarm call. Like all lemurs, they are found only on the island of Madagascar. All species of sifakas are threatened, ranging from endangered to critically endangered.Anatomy and physiology Sifakas are medium-sized indrids with a head and body length of  and a weight of . Their tail is just as long as their body, which differentiates them from the Indri. Their fur is long and silky, with coloration varying by species from yellowish-white to blackish-brown.

Vapor pressure (or vapour pressure in English-speaking counties other than the US; see spelling differences) or equilibrium vapor pressure is defined as the pressure exerted by a vapor in thermodynamic equilibrium with its condensed phases (solid or liquid) at a given temperature in a closed system. The equilibrium vapor pressure is an indication of a liquid's evaporation rate. It relates to the tendency of particles to escape from the liquid (or a solid). A substance with a high vapor pressure at normal temperatures is often referred to as volatile. The pressure exhibited by vapor present above a liquid surface is known as vapor pressure.

Year 1321 ( MCCCXXI ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 21 – Robert I of Naples is crowned King at Naples Cathedral. March 29 – The Battle of Manapouri takes place between the colonists of the colony of New Zealand in the south island of the island and the inhabitants of the North Island, the Māori tribe led by the Ngāpuhi chief Te Kawau. The battle is won by the Ngāpuhi, in a series of battles and skirmishes. May 24 – The first parliament of Bohemia (the oldest known representative body) is assembled.

In software quality assurance , performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs under a particular workload. Performance testing can apply to any system, whether it is a website or an operating system. It can be used to measure such things as load time or the number of transactions per minute (TPM), whether a system's response time remains consistent or whether the system remains usable and responds to a given number of concurrent users. There are many different types of performance testing: functional, non-functional and load testing to name but a few.

Year 1579 ( MDLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 30 – Battle of Lepanto – Allied Christian navies defeat the Ottoman Empire. Battle of the Gamaras, a Spanish victory over an Ottoman fleet in the Mediterranean. Battle of the Gulf of Lepanto (Battle of La Goleta). William Shakespeare's play Troilus and Cressida is registered for a performance licence. It is probably written at this time. It will not be printed in the First Folio in 1623 until after 1635.

Year 1233 ( MCCXXXIII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1199 or 1299? The year 1299 was a leap year starting on Tuesday of the Julian calendar. ... Year 1399 was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. ... The Julian calendar was developed in Rome under Julius Caesar in 45 BC and was in use throughout the Roman Empire by the first century BC. The calendar was officially named after him in the 2nd century AD by order of Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa.

Year 1059 (MLIX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  November 22 – Emperor Isaac I Komnenos falls ill on a hunt and retires to a monastery after a 2-year reign. He abdicates the Byzantine throne and appoints Constantine X, a Paphlagonian nobleman, as his successor. Fall – The Magyars cross the Danube River, together with several Pecheneg tribes, but are halted by Byzantine forces (approximate date). Europe  Peter Krešimir IV (the Great) is crowned king of Croatia and Dalmatia.

Dub mac Maíl Coluim ( Modern Gaelic : Dubh mac Mhaoil Chaluim , ) , sometimes anglicised as Duff MacMalcolm , was a Scottish clan chief and later king of Scots from 1058 to 1093. He was the third son of Duncan I of Scots and his first wife, Matilda of Huntingdon ( 1030–1118 ). He was probably educated by the monks at Dunkeld , but he also had some links with Iona , the religious centre of his family's power. He succeeded to his father's throne at the age of about thirty, and was crowned as Malcolm III, but there is no contemporary account of this.

Year 1442 (MCDXLII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 18–25 – Battle of Hermannstadt: John Hunyadi defeats an army of the Ottoman Empire 80,000 strong, led by Mesid Bey of Vidin, near Sibiu in Transylvania. June 2 – Alfonso of Aragon proclaims himself King of Naples. September – John Hunyadi defeats another army of the Ottoman Empire (70,000 strong), led by Hadım Şehabeddin, Beylerbey (or governor) of Rumelia, near the Ialomița River. Following this, he places Basarab II as ruler of Wallachia.

Year 1216(MCCXVI) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  Spring – First Barons' War: The English army, led by King John (Lackland), sacks the town of Berwick-on-Tweed (or Berwick), and raids southern Scotland. John pushes up towards Edinburgh over a ten-day period. On his return, he puts down a revolt in East Anglia. On March 24, King John arrives at Hertford, to deal with the challenge of a coming French invasion.

John the Apostle ( ; ) or Saint John the Beloved was one of the Twelve Apostles of Jesus according to the New Testament. He and Andrew were disciples whom Jesus appointed to be his special followers. The gospels provide somewhat varying accounts of Andrew's life and especially his relationship to John the Baptist, Jesus and Jesus' mother. However, all four canonical Gospels agree on the last of these: John's mother Salome is portrayed as the sister of the Virgin Mary, which, given that Mary and Salome are mentioned as being cousins, implies that Salome is also the daughter of Mary's brother.

Year 1310 (MCCCX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  January –  Forces of the Kingdom of Castile retreat from the Siege of Algeciras, after enduring severe losses, and secure a peace treaty. March – Muhammed III, former Sultan of the Emirate of Granada, is blinded and found dead in a pool, after an attempted coup to retake his throne from his brother Nasr. May 11 – In France, 54 members of the Knights Templar are burned at the stake for heresy.Date unknown  Abu al-Fida becomes governor of Hama.

The 1988 United States presidential election was the 51st quadrennial presidential election, held on Tuesday, November 8, 1988. The Republican nominee, incumbent Vice President George H. W. Bush, defeated the Democratic nominee, Governor Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts. This was the first presidential election since 1948, and the most recent to date, in which a party won a third consecutive presidential term. This also remains the most recent election in which a candidate won over 400 electoral votes, and the last time a non-incumbent Republican candidate won the popular vote.Incumbent president Ronald Reagan was ineligible to seek a third term.

The 8th century BCE started the first day of 800 BC and ended the last day of 701 BC . It is considered the beginning of the Classical Period in Ancient Greek history . This period is often divided into the Early Classical period (c. 800 – 700 BC) and the Middle Classical period (c. 700 – 625 BC). However, some date the end of the Early Classical at the death of Homer (770 BC) and the beginning of the Late Classical at the death of Solon (560 BC).

Leisure Suit Larry is an adult-themed video game series created by Al Lowe. It was published by Sierra from 1987 to 2009, then by Codemasters starting in 2009. The first six Leisure Suit Larry titles, along with Magna Cum Laude and Love for Sail Mobile, were distributed by Vivendi Games (now Activision Blizzard), while Box Office Bust and Reloaded were distributed by Codemasters. Currently the games are being published and distributed by Assemble Entertainment.The games follow Larry Laffer, a balding, double entendre-speaking, leisure suit-wearing man in his 40s. The stories generally revolve around his attempting, usually unsuccessfully, to seduce attractive young women.

OCaml ( , formerly Objective Caml ) is a general-purpose , multi-paradigm programming language which extends the Caml dialect of ML, and is based on several other languages including Pascal , Lisp , and Miranda. It was developed by Xavier Leroy at INRIA Rennes . Ocaml is free software and released under the Mozilla license. The latest version, OCaml Pro, is a commercial package produced by the company ILOG and sold by the commercial software vendor, The Math Works. The OCaml Pro code base is based upon the open-source Ocaml 3.0.0 release of the programming language and its standard libraries.

Year 1524 (MDXXIV) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 17 – Florentine explorer Giovanni da Verrazzano, on board La Dauphine in the service of Francis I of France, sets out from Madeira for the New World, to seek out a western sea route to the Pacific Ocean. March – Spanish conquistador Pedro de Alvarado destroys the Kʼicheʼ kingdom of Qʼumarkaj, taking the capital, Quiché. March 1 (approximate date) – da Verrazzano's expedition makes landfall at Cape Fear.

The Stoned Guest is a `` half-act opera '' by Peter Schickele in the satirical persona of P. D. Q. Bach, and is based on The Glass Bead Game, a novel by Hermann Hesse . It premiered at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign , on November 18, 1989. It was revised several times, and had its New York premiere on January 28, 1993, by P.D.Q. Bach Productions, Inc., as part of an evening-length production of three P.D.Q. Bach operas, including The Compleat Wertz (1943) and A Contract with God (1968) with libretti by David St. John.

Year 1020 (MXX) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  Summer – Emperor Henry II conducts his third Italian military campaign. He makes plans to invade the south, but remains non-commital. June 15 – Byzantine troops under Catepan Basil Boioannes (supported by his ally Prince Pandulf IV) capture the fortress of Troia. The French city of Saint-Germain-en-Laye is founded by King Robert II (the Pious). King Canute the Great codifies the laws of England (approximate date).

Hide-and-seek is a popular children 's game in which at least two players ( usually at least three ) conceal themselves from others that they do not want to find them. If the players try to find others, they must count to 100 in sequence, and the finders of players can not repeat their number (for example, the finder can not shout "seven, eight" in a row). Players can call "ready or not, here I come". This means that no one has to find the finder. This is only an informal rule.

Year 1213 (MCCXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  May 15 – King John of England submits to Pope Innocent III, who in turn lifts the interdict of 1208. May 30 – Battle of Damme: The English fleet under William Longespée, 3rd Earl of Salisbury, destroys a French fleet off the Belgian port in the first major victory for the fledgling Royal Navy. September 12 – Battle of Muret: The Toulousain and Aragonese forces of Raymond VI of Toulouse and Peter II of Aragon are defeated by the Albigensian Crusade, under Simon de Montfort.

Year 1449 ( MCDXLIX ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. ^ The Roman Catholic Church was founded in 312 AD and became the Roman Catholic Church. In 330 AD, Emperor Constantine converted to Christianity. Constantine I was the first Christian Emperor of Rome, and he re-established the Roman Capital at Constantinople, modern-day Istanbul. In 1792, the Republic of the United States of the Americas was created, consisting of the territory of the United States of America, East Florida, and West Florida.

Kazimierz Funk ( ; February 23 , 1884 – November 19 , 1967 ) , commonly anglicized as Casimir Funk , was a Polish biochemist who worked in Canada , the United States , Germany and Switzerland . He is known as the " Father of vitamins " for his part in identifying the vitamins and vitamin D , and is credited as an early pioneer in the field of pharmacology . He was born in Białystok (Russian Poland), the son of a wealthy merchant . Funk was educated at the University of Leipzig ( 1902) , and received his Doctor of Pharmaceutical Sciences from the University of Freiburg ( 1906 ).

Year 1516 ( MDXVI ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar . This is a listing of events in the year 1516. Pope Leo X succeeds Pope Adrian VI . June 20 – French forces of King Francis I capture the city of Milan . December 11 – Martin Luther writes to his wife, Katharina von Bora. December 29 – King Francis I of France dies without an heir. His brother Charles becomes King Charles V of France. 10th century BC – The Cyrus Cylinder was made in Iran.

Robert I Estienne (; 15037 September 1559), known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to as Robert Stephens, was a 16th-century printer and classical scholar in Paris. He was the proprietor of the Estienne print shop after the death of his father Henri Estienne, the founder of the Estienne printing firm. Estienne published and republished many classical texts as well as Greek and Latin translations of the Bible. Known as "Printer to the King" in Latin, Hebrew, and Greek, Estienne's most prominent work was the Thesaurus linguae latinae which is considered to be the foundation of modern Latin lexicography.

English Renaissance theatre , also known as Renaissance English theatre and Elizabethan theatre , refers to the theatre of England from 1562 to 1642, during the English Renaissance. It is sometimes known as the Theatre of the Elizabeth Age. The term derives from the replacement of the medieval system of Church censorship over theatrical entertainment by the Crown. Along with the English Renaissance, the period is also associated with the Elizabethan era and Elizabethan culture. This period of English theatre is often considered a golden age in which English literature, theatre, and culture flourished.

Toktar Ongarbayuly Aubakirov ( ( Toqtar Oñğarbaiūly Äubäkırov ) , , born on 27 July 1946 ) is a retired Kyrghyz weightlifter who competed in the 1972 and 1976 Summer Olympics, finishing in 11th place in 1976 in both the light-heavyweight and heavyweight classes. He is an Honored Master of Sports of the USSR and Honored Coach of the Kyrgyz Soviet Socialist Republic. In 1972, he won the Soviet championship in the heavyweight class and took bronze at the Asian Games. In 1974, he took bronze medals at both the Soviet and European championships.

Year 1507 (MDVII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  April 25 – Martin Waldseemüller publishes his Cosmographiae Introductio ("Introduction to Universal Cosmography") and accompanying wall map, the first to show the Americas as a separate continent, naming them in honour of Amerigo Vespucci, his friend and idol. April / May – Martin Luther is ordained a priest of the Catholic Church. July–December  August 20 – Guru Nanak Dev becomes the first guru, and leader, of the Sikh religion.

Jan Bos ( born 29 March 1975 ) is a Dutch speedskater and sprint cyclist . In the late 1990s he was the national sprint champion in both sports. Bos was a member of the Dutch national speedskating team from 1995 to 2002. In this period he won four national sprint titles , as well as a team sprint world title , a European allround title and a team sprint European title . From 2005 he started as a professional cyclist . Bos has won several races on the track . As a cyclist, he was mostly active in the cycling classics .

A shank is a type of knot that is used to shorten a rope or take up slack, such as the sheepshank. The sheepshank knot is not stable. It will fall apart under too much load or too little load.The knot has several features which allow a rope to be shortened: It provides two loops, one at each end of the knot which can be used to pass another rope through The knot remains somewhat secure under tension; the coarser the rope the more secure it is (see Disadvantages, below) The knot falls apart easily when tension is removedConstruction methods A sheepshank knot may be constructed as follows: ...

The Tandy 1000 is the first in a line of IBM PC compatible home computer systems produced by the Tandy Corporation (now RadioShack). It went on sale in August of 1984 for $699.99 (equivalent to $1,483 in 2018 dollars). It featured an Intel 80186 processor with a maximum speed of 3.2MHz, 256 KB RAM, and an expansion slot on the back of the case. Unlike most of the IBM PC compatibles on the market, it had an onboard 64 KB video ROM, which provided a 200-line display and 256-color support.

is the Latin name under which the `` Lamb of God '' is honoured within the Catholic Mass and other rites. The name is a transliteration of λευϒι της ωστεωσ υιου του ζεστων (Levi tēs osteōs hyiou to Zestiōn; Luke 5:23), in the Gospel of Luke ( 5:23–34 ). It refers to the young man who became Jesus' first follower and the first disciple to be named. John the Apostle was considered a leader of the community of believers in Jerusalem by the late first century. He was the only disciple who was at the Last Supper.

The Cape Cod Canal is an artificial waterway in the U.S. state of Massachusetts connecting Cape Cod Bay in the north to Buzzards Bay in the south, and is part of the Atlantic Intracoastal Waterway. The approximately  canal traverses the neck of land joining Cape Cod to the state's mainland. It mostly follows tidal rivers widened to  and deepened to  at mean low water, shaving  off the journey around the Cape for its approximately 14,000 annual users.Most of the canal is located in the town of Bourne, but its northeastern terminus is in Sandwich.

Events January–March January 10 – England and the Dutch Republic sign a mutual defense treaty in order to fight against Spain in the Anglo Dutch Wars. January 19 – Battle of Dunkirk begins. March 8 – Battle of Ostend – Allied forces, commanded by the Duke of Norfolk, capture Ostend, the principal Flemish harbor, from the Spanish. April 1 – The Dutch and England sign an anti-Spanish alliance. May 5 – The Dutch Republic and Spain sign the Truce of Zaragoza. June 11 - The Dutch and the English establish an alliance to defend themselves from the Spanish Armada.

The 1988 United States presidential election was the 51st quadrennial presidential election , held on Tuesday , November 8 , in which Republican candidate , Vice President of the United States , and Governor of Michigan George H. W. Bush defeated Democrat Michael S.
Dukakis after a campaign season that focused on foreign policy and the continuing U.S. economic recovery from the 1980s . Bush was the incumbent vice president as well as a former Director of Central Intelligence . He defeated Democratic U.S. Senator from Massachusetts and former Secretary of the Navy , Ed Muskie , who had been a front-runner in the early days of the campaign .

Year 1354 (MCCCLIV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  Early in the year – Ibn Battuta returns from his travels at the command of Abu Inan Faris, sultan of Morocco, who appoints a scribe to write an account of the adventures. February 12 –  The Treaty of Stralsund settles border disputes between the duchies of Mecklenburg and Pomerania. March 2 –  The Gallipoli earthquake occurs, followed within a month by Turkish capture and settlement (see Fall of Gallipoli).

Year 1273 (MCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  January 22 – Muhammad II becomes Sultan of the Emirate of Granada after the death of his father, Muhammad I, in a riding accident. September 29 – Rudolph I of Germany is elected King of Germany over rival candidate King Otakar II of Bohemia, ending the Interregnum; Otakar refuses to acknowledge Rudolph as the new king, leading to the outbreak of war in 1276. Rudolph is the first of many Habsburgs to hold the throne.

Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech, 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol  (; ; ; 11 May 190423 January 1989) was a Spanish surrealist artist renowned for his technical skill, precise draftsmanship, and the striking and bizarre images in his work.Born in Figueres, Catalonia, Spain, Dalí received his formal education in fine arts in Madrid. Influenced by Impressionism and the Renaissance masters from a young age, he became increasingly attracted to Cubism and avant-garde movements. He moved closer to Surrealism in the late 1920s and joined the Surrealist group in 1929, soon becoming one of its leading exponents.

The Air Ministry was a department of the Government of the United Kingdom with the responsibility of managing the affairs of the Royal Air Force. Prior to the creation of the Royal Air Force, the Air Ministry was a department of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, and before that, from 1919 to 1921, of the British Dominions of Canada, Australia, India, and South Africa. [1] The creation of the independent RAF in April 1918 meant that the air element of the armed services was separated from the Admiralty, and that a separate ministry was created to oversee air affairs.

Botulinum toxin (BoNT) is a neurotoxic protein produced by the bacterium Clostridium botulinum and related species. It prevents the release of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine from axon endings at the neuromuscular junction, thus causing flaccid paralysis. The toxin causes the disease botulism. The toxin is also used commercially for medical and cosmetic purposes.The seven main types of botulinum toxin are named types A to G (A, B, C1, C2, D, E, F and G). New types are occasionally found. Types A and B are capable of causing disease in humans, and are also used commercially and medically.

Year 1149 ( MCXLIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 13 - Battle of the Rhyne: William II of England and his uncle, Robert Curthose, fight each other. Robert is injured and captured. August 24 - Pope Eugene III succeeds Pope Anastasius IV, becoming the 174st pope. October 10 - Pope Eugene III crowns King Henry III of England in Canterbury, thus making England officially Catholic. December 22 - Pope Eugenius III excommunicates Henry of England.

Events June 16 – The deposed and imprisoned Mary , Queen of Scots , recognizes Philip II of Spain as her son's legitimate monarch. Events November 17 – The marriage of Henry's daughter Elizabeth to Frederick V, Elector Palatine takes place at The Hague. The Union of Atrecht , a political arrangement under which the Northern Netherlands was granted autonomy in return for loyalty to Spain, is signed. Events April 24 – Henry II of France and Henry IV of France sign the Edict of Nantes , giving Protestants the right to worship freely in the French-controlled portion of the kingdom.

Jean François Champagny (12 July 1775 – 4 September 1834) was a French statesman and ambassador, born in Paris. In 1806, Napoleon appointed him General Counsel of State, and in the same year made him Minist...
Jean-André-Nicolas Ponte de Boisjoli
Jean-André-Nicolas Ponte de Boisjoli was a French naval officer born in Saint-Domingue.

Mariner 3 ( together with Mariner 4 known as Mariner-Mars 1964 ) was one of two identical deep-space probes designed to explore Mars. It is the fourth successful probe to reach Mars, and the second American spacecraft to orbit Mars. It was the first of two missions in 1964, the other being Mariner 4, which were intended to fly-by the planet Mars, taking pictures and gathering scientific data, as a precursor to a lander mission planned to begin with Mariner 4 and fly-by the planet Venus with the more capable Mariner 6. However, both probes ran out of fuel well before reaching Mars.

The sousaphone is a brass instrument in the same family as the more widely known tuba . Created around 1893 by Adolphe Sax for use in the United States Army Band, the sousaphone is now widely used in marching bands in the United States as well as many countries around the world, such as Brazil , Argentina , and France . It is also used in symphonic music , particularly by British brass bands or in jazz big bands, as well as in music for television, film and video game scores, particularly when a tuba is needed for a low, sustained note.

Events  January–June  January 24 – King Charles II of England dissolves the "Cavalier Parliament", after nearly 18 years. February 3 – Moroccan troops from Fez are killed, along with their commander Moussa ben Ahmed ben Youssef, in a battle against rebels in the Jbel Saghro mountain range, but Moroccan Sultan Ismail Ibn Sharif is able to negotiate a ceasefire allowing his remaining troops safe passage back home. February 5 – The Treaty of Celle is signed between France and Sweden on one side, and the Holy Roman Empire, at the town of Celle in Saxony (now in Germany).

Year 1193 (MCXCIII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  March 4 – Saladin (the Lion) dies of a fever at Damascus. The lands of the Ayyubid Dynasty of Syria and Egypt are split among his relatives. During his reign, he briefly unites the Muslim world, and drives the Crusaders out of Jerusalem to a narrow strip of coast. At the time of his death, Saladin has seventeen sons and one little daughter. Al-Afdal succeeds his father as ruler (emir) of Damascus, and inherits the headship of the Ayyubid family.

Roger Williams (21 December 1603between 27 January and 15 March 1683) was a Puritan minister, theologian, and author who founded Providence Plantations, which became the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations and later the U.S. State of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations, now the State of Rhode Island. He was a staunch advocate for religious freedom, separation of church and state, and fair dealings with Native Americans.Williams was expelled by the Puritan leaders from the Massachusetts Bay Colony and established Providence Plantations in 1636 as a refuge offering what he termed "liberty of conscience."

Algebraic topology is a branch of mathematics that uses tools from abstract algebra to study topological spaces . The basic tool is homology theory . The fundamental theorem of homology, which states that given a topological space X, one can associate a linear vector space H(X) and an exact sequence H(X) → 0 → H1(X) → 0 . The space H1(X) is called the first homology group of X. The term homology is also applied in other contexts in algebra and topology, for example the group homology of an Abelian group , where the terms "cohomology" is used instead.

Year 1532 ( MDXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 14 – Holy Roman Emperor Charles V, the son of Maximilian I and sister of Holy Roman Emperor Ferdinand I, is elected king of the Romans by the Electoral College at Frankfurt. The Ottoman fortress of Srebrenik is destroyed. Turkey and the Hapsburg Empire sign a treaty, granting the Ottomans certain rights of sovereignty in Serbia. The Kingdom of England establishes the Virginia Company, with the goal of establishing colonies on the North American Atlantic coast.

Year 1174 (MCLXXIV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, the 1174th year of the Common Era (CE) and Anno Domini (AD) designations, the 174th year of the 2nd millennium, the 74th year of the 12th century, and the 5th year of the 1170s decade.Events  By place  England  July 13 – Battle of Alnwick: King William I (the Lion) supported by Flemish mercenaries invades England to help fight in the baronial rebellion against King Henry II. William attacks Prudhoe Castle in Northumberland, but is unable to capture it.

arXiv ( pronounced `` archive '' —the X represents the Greek letter chi [ χ ] ) is an open-access electronic archive and a central repository for scientific papers. It was founded and is maintained by Cornell University. It is supported by the Simons Foundation. It is an example of collaborative open-access research. arXiv began as a physics-only archive in 1991 but later came to include other scientific disciplines, including computer science (1993), mathematics (1991), statistics (2001), quantitative finance and economics (2006), quantum physics and condensed matter (2006), quantitative biology (2013), and others.

Figure skating jumps are an element of three competitive figure skating disciplines—men's singles, ladies' singles, and pair skating but not ice dancing. Jumping in figure skating is "relatively recent". They were originally individual compulsory figures, and sometimes special figures; many jumps were named after the skaters who invented them or from the figures from which they were developed. It was not until the early part of the 20th century, well after the establishment of organized skating competitions, when jumps with the potential of being completed with multiple revolutions were invented and when jumps were formally categorized.

Events  January–June  January 10 – The Royal African Company is granted a Royal Charter by Charles II of England. February – English pirates carry out the sack of Campeche in Mexico. March 4 – The Prince Edward Islands in the sub-antarctic Indian Ocean are discovered by Barent Barentszoon Lam, of the Dutch ship Maerseveen, and named Dina (Prince Edward) and Maerseveen (Marion). March 5 – Emperor Go-Sai's reign ends, and Emperor Reigen ascends to the throne of Japan. March 24 – King Charles II of England issues the Charter of Carolina, establishing the Province of Carolina, and dividing it between eight Lords Proprietors.

Panettone (, ;  ) is an Italian type of sweet bread originally from Milan, usually prepared and enjoyed for Christmas and New Year in Western, Southern, and Southeastern Europe as well as in South America, Eritrea, Australia, the United States and Canada.It has a cupola shape, which extends from a cylindrical base and is usually about 12–15 cm high for a panettone weighing 1 kg. Other bases may be used, such as an octagon, or a frustum with a star section shape more common to pandoro. It is made during a long process that involves curing the dough, which is acidic, similar to sourdough.

Arthrobacter ( from the Greek , `` jointed small stick ” ) is a genus of bacteria that is commonly found in soil and water . They are Gram - negative , rod-shaped and motile. The organisms are aerobes , and are able to live in extreme conditions including temperatures as low as 25 Celsius . Arthrobacter species were first discovered in soil and were also found to be associated with plant roots and the Rhizosphere ( a zone immediately surrounding a plant’s root where microorganisms have the greatest concentration ) . Arthrobacter is found around the roots of plants and also as a normal inhabitant of human skin .

Optical rotation , also known as polarization rotation or circular birefringence , is the rotation of the orientation of the plane of vibration of light, that is, of its propagation direction, when a nonpolarized light beam is transmitted through some material. The optical rotatory power ( ϑ, θ ) is defined as the degree of optical rotation. In order to measure the optical rotatory power, a plane polarizer is used as a beam splitter and the light beam emerging from the material is directed towards another polarizer as an analyzer. When the plane polarizers are crossed, the light becomes completely polarized and it can be rotated at any angle.

Cape Cod is a geographic cape extending into the Atlantic Ocean from the southeastern corner of mainland Massachusetts, in the northeastern United States. Its historic, maritime character and ample beaches attract heavy tourism during the summer months. The name Cape Cod, coined in 1602 by Bartholomew Gosnold, is the ninth oldest English place-name in the U.S.As defined by the Cape Cod Commission's enabling legislation, Cape Cod is conterminous with Barnstable County, Massachusetts. It extends from Provincetown in the northeast to Woods Hole in the southwest, and is bordered by Plymouth to the northwest.

Robert Sanderson Mulliken ( June 7 , 1896 – October 31 , 1986 ) was an American physicist and chemist . He received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1966 for his development of the quantum theory of chemical bonds . Born in Cambridge , Massachusetts , he attended the University of Chicago , where his father , William T. Mulliken , was the chairman of the department of physics. After graduating in 1917, he entered the U.S. Navy . In 1920 , he received a doctorate from Princeton University , where he spent the following two years as an instructor in chemistry.

Year 1541 ( MDXLI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 12 September 1541 was a Thursday. It was the first day of September 1541 in the Gregorian calendar and the 255th day of the 1541st year of the Common Era (or 1543rd year of the 1st millennium ), the 26th Thursday of the year, and the first of the month in the Julian calendar. 11 September 1541: Pope Paul III is elected. The Battle of Mühlberg takes place in Saxony.

Year 1328 (MCCCXXVIII) was a leap year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 24 – Philippa of Hainault marries King Edward III of England a year after his coronation. The marriage produces ten children, the eldest of whom is Edward the Black Prince. May 1 – Treaty of Edinburgh–Northampton: England recognises Scotland as an independent nation, after the Wars of Scottish Independence. May 12 – Antipope Nicholas V is consecrated at St. Peter's Basilica in Rome by the bishop of Venice. May 26 – William of Ockham secretly leaves Avignon, under threat from Pope John XXII.

Short-track speed skating is a form of competitive ice speed skating. In competitions, multiple skaters (typically between four and six) skate on an oval ice track with a length of . The rink itself is  long by  wide, which is the same size as an Olympic-sized figure skating rink and an international-sized ice hockey rink. Related sports include long track speed skating and inline speed skating.HistoryShort-track skating developed from speed skating events that were held with mass starts. This form of speed skating was mainly practised in the United States and Canada, as opposed to the international form, where athletes skated in pairs.

The 8th century BCE started the first day of 800 BC and ended the last day of 701 BC. The 8th century BC is a period of great change for several historically significant civilizations. In Egypt, the 23rd and 24th dynasties lead to rule from Nubia in the 25th Dynasty. The Neo-Assyrian Empire reaches the peak of its power,  conquering the Kingdom of Israel as well as nearby countries.Greece colonizes other regions of the Mediterranean Sea and Black Sea. Rome is founded in 753 BC, and the Etruscan civilization expands in Italy.

Year 1295 (MCCXCV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  June 20 – Pope Boniface VIII proposes the Treaty of Anagni, seeking to bring peace between the house of Anjou and Sicily; the effort is in vain. June 26 – Przemysł II is crowned King of Poland in Gniezno Cathedral, the first coronation of a Polish ruler in 219 years. October 23 – The first treaty forming the Auld Alliance, between Scotland and France against England, is signed in Paris.

Mai Elisabeth Zetterling ( ; 24 May 1925 – 17 March 1994 ) was a Swedish actress , novelist and screenwriter who worked in both the United Kingdom and Hollywood . Zetterling worked as an actress from 1943 , making his first film at age 18 in the 1945 German movie Der Engel mit der Posaun directed by Alfred Ebeling. He worked in many European countries before landing in 1949 in Great Britain and Hollywood . She became particularly known for her work in the 1954 movie The Seventh Veil directed by Compton Bennett. She won a Golden Globe award and was nominated for a BAFTA award in that year.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Tuesday, one day ahead of the Julian and ten days behind the Gregorian calendar.Events  January–March  January 12 – Parts of the Netherlands adopt the Gregorian calendar. January 18 – The electorate of Brandenburg-Prussia becomes the Kingdom of Prussia, as Elector Frederick III is proclaimed King Frederick I.  Prussia remains part of the Holy Roman Empire. It consists of Brandenburg, Pomerania and East Prussia. Berlin is the capital. January 28 – The Chinese storm Dartsedo. February 17 (February 6, 1700 O.S.) – The 5th Parliament of King William III is assembled.

The history of Anguilla runs from the beginning of human habitation , probably via settlement from South America , through the 17th century to the creation of an autonomous dependency in the 20th century and continuing through the present day. The British and the French were the first Europeans to settle in Anguilla. The French were the more numerous, with at least 2,000 people. The British were about 1,200 strong, but their numbers were reduced by deaths during a smallpox outbreak and by deportation by the French for supporting the American colonists during the American Revolutionary War . In 1650, Anguilla was formally colonized by English settlers from Saint Kitts .

Robert I Estienne ( ; 15037 September 1559 ) , known as Robertus Stephanus in Latin and sometimes referred to as Robert Stephanus, was a scholar , editor , and printer who worked in Paris , France . He was a key figure in the development of French humanism . He was the father of the Greek scholar and Protestant minister Theodor Zwingli (1581636 ) and the great-grandfather of the French King Louis XIV. In 1503 Robert Estienne was born in Paris , to Antoine Estienne (or Stephanus) (147492) , a printer and the head of the famous printing house known as the Estiennes .
