Events Byzantine emperor Romanos I appoints Nikephoros as new emperor in the West. ... John the Fearless (French : Jean le Maudit; 1275 in Rouen - 14 June 1316 at Montereau), also called John of Burgundy, Duke of Burgundy (le Duc de Bourgogne) was the last of the Capetians to be King of Bohemia. ... This is a list of kings of France from 987 to 1791, and of the first four Kings of the French people from 877 to 987.

The human leg, in the general word sense, is the entire lower limb of the human body, including the foot, thigh and even the hip or gluteal region. However, the definition in human anatomy refers only to the section of the lower limb extending from the knee to the ankle, also known as the crus or, especially in non-technical use, the shank. Legs are used for standing, and all forms of locomotion including recreational such as dancing, and constitute a significant portion of a person's mass.

An engagement ring is a ring indicating that the person wearing it is engaged to be married , especially in Western culture. Such rings are worn primarily by women, indicating their engagement to be married to a particular man. A wedding ring is worn on the hand as an indication of engagement and is traditionally worn by the woman on the ring finger. In most cases the wedding ring is worn on the fourth finger of the left hand. The reason for this is that the other three fingers have a vein that points to the heart, but the fourth finger points to the person’s betrothed (future spouse).

Year 1217 ( MCCXVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. April 13 – Henry of England is crowned King of England. August 6 – Battle of Bouvines: The French army is defeated by the army of the Holy Roman Empire and England ( led by John of England ), leading to the first peace between the Empire and France for 100 years. The Ōtsū Incident ( 大津の変, Ōtsu-no-hen ) occurs in Japan; the capital is relocated to Kyoto for two years, due to a revolt.

Mariner 2 (Mariner-Venus 1962), an American space probe to Venus, was the first robotic space probe to conduct a successful planetary encounter. The first successful spacecraft in the NASA Mariner program, it was a simplified version of the Block I spacecraft of the Ranger program and an exact copy of Mariner 1. The missions of the Mariner 1 and 2 spacecraft are sometimes known as the Mariner R missions. Original plans called for the probes to be launched on the Atlas-Centaur, but serious developmental problems with that vehicle forced a switch to the much smaller Agena B second stage.

Year 1186 (MCLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 27 – Constance of Sicily marries Henry (the future Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor). John the Chanter becomes Bishop of Exeter. The Byzantine Empire recognizes the independence of Bulgaria and Serbia. Joscius becomes Archbishop of Tyre. Jayavarman VII, the king of Cambodia, founds the temple of Ta Prohm. After the death of the child-king Baldwin V, his mother succeeds him as Sibylla of Jerusalem, and appoints her disfavoured husband Guy de Lusignan king consort.

Year 1409 (MCDIX) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – The Welsh surrender Harlech Castle to the English. March 25 – The Council of Pisa opens. On June 5 it deposes Pope Gregory XII and Antipope Benedict XIII, and on June 26 crowns Petros Philargos as Pope Alexander V; he is subsequently regarded as an antipope. July – Martin I of Aragon succeeds his own son, as King of Sicily. August 7 – The Council of Pisa closes. December 2 – The University of Leipzig opens.

Mikhail Afanasyevich Bulgakov ( ; – 10 March 1940 ) was a Russian writer , medical doctor , and playwright . He was a noted satirist, and was an outspoken member of the Orthodox Church, although he was denied ordination in the 1920s due to his alleged atheism . Bulgakov is well known in the English-speaking world for his 1932 novel The Master and Margarita, which is a satire of the Soviet Union , and was adapted for the stage in 1946 . He is also known for his play The Heart of a Dog, a satire of Stalinism that was performed in Russia after the 1957 thaw .

Year 1567 (MDLXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June  January – A Spanish force under the command of Captain Juan Pardo establishes Fort San Juan, in the Native American settlement of Joara. The fort is the first European settlement in present-day North Carolina. January 20 – Battle of Rio de Janeiro: Portuguese forces under the command of Estácio de Sá definitively drive the French out of Rio de Janeiro. January 23 – After 45 years' reign, the Jiajing Emperor dies in the Forbidden City of China.

Spins are an element in figure skating in which the skater rotates , centered on a single point on the ice, and performs movements in different directions . Spins can take place on both one foot or two feet on the blade, depending upon the discipline. There are four spins commonly performed in figure skating: the layback spin, the camel spin, the counter spin, and the sit spin. The spin positions are rotational variations on a basic free skating movement. The spins are named for the position of their arms and legs.

The 7th millennium BC spanned the years 7000 BC to 6001 BC ( c. 9 ka to c. 8 ka). This millennium saw the beginnings of the Holocene and the beginning of modern human civilization, and ended with the advent of farming in China, South Asia, Southeast Asia and the Middle East. 7000 BC – the first known farmers in the Northern Hemisphere begin clearing lands for agriculture. c. 7000 BC (12,000 years ago) – earliest known human habitation of the Andaman Islands, off the coast of Thailand, possibly as early as before 14,000 BCE, according to carbon-dating of the site.

Palermo ( , ; , locally also or ; , from ; older ) is a city in southern Italy. It is the main seaport of western Sicily. The city is also the capital of both the province of Palermo (Province of Palermo) and the Sicilian region ( Sicily ). The city's inhabitants are called "Palermitani" (feminine Palermitan (singular); Palermitana (plural). The first settlement in Palermo was a settlement of Phoenicians ( Phoenicia). The Phoenicians founded the city as "Ziz" around 824/823 BC in the west of the island.

Anne Boleyn ( ; 1501 – 19 May 1536 ) was Queen of England from 1533 to 1536 , as the second wife of King Henry VIII . Anne was queen during a period when Henry VIII broke with Rome and established the Church of England. She gave birth to the only legitimate daughter of Henry VIII, Queen Elizabeth I . Henry’s first wife, Anne’s sister, Queen Catherine , had been married to him for 20 years with no children when Henry fell in love with Anne . He divorced Catherine so that he could marry Anne.

Mariner 10 was an American robotic space probe launched by NASA on 3 November 1973 , to fly by the planets Mercury three times and Venus once. It was the second of NASA's "Mariner program" of missions to the inner solar system. Mariner 10 was equipped with two instruments to obtain photographs and electromagnetic radiation data; a camera that took black and white photographs and a magnetometer to study magnetic fields in the two planets' atmospheres. The spacecraft was built at JPL, which managed the Mariner 10 mission. As of 2019, it remains the only spacecraft to have visited Venus.

Year 1529 ( MDXXIX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. May 21 – Spanish conquest of Guatemala: Hernan Cortés conquers Iximché and Tecún Umán becomes the ruler of the Quiche kingdom. July 27 – Battle of La Bicocca: French forces defeat Imperials. August 19 – Battle of Tumacácori ( Arizona): Spanish conquistadors invade Tubac and defeat the Opata Indians, in a battle known in history as the Battle of Tumacácori. August 31 – Ferdinand Magellan sets sail from Spain on his expedition of the world.

In mathematics, an -sphere or a hypersphere is a topological space that is homeomorphic to a standard -sphere, which is the set of points in -dimensional Euclidean space that are situated at a constant distance  from a fixed point, called the center. It is the generalization of an ordinary sphere in the ordinary three-dimensional space. The "radius" of a sphere is the constant distance of its points to the center. When the sphere has unit radius, it is usual to call it the unit -sphere or simply the -sphere for brevity.

A battering ram is a siege engine that originated in ancient times and was designed to break open the masonry walls of fortifications or splinter their wooden gates. In its simplest form, a battering ram is just a large, heavy log carried by several people and propelled with force against an obstacle; the ram would be sufficient to damage the target if the log were massive enough and/or it were moved quickly enough (that is, if it had enough momentum). Later rams encased the log in an arrow-proof, fire-resistant canopy mounted on wheels. Inside the canopy, the log was swung from suspensory chains or ropes.

Year 1165 ( MCLXV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The 13th year of Pope Urban IV. The Mongols occupy Baghdad and kill all of its population. Construction begins on the Hagia Sophia, Istanbul, Turkey. Mansa Musa of Mali arrives in Cairo to collect funds for the Almohad cause in Spain. Mansa Musa, emperor of Mali, is en route from his kingdom in the west to Mecca, and stops in Cairo. He is so impressed with the Egyptian city that he finances the construction of several buildings there.

A lever ( or ) is a simple machine consisting of a beam or rigid rod pivoted at a fixed hinge, or fulcrum. A lever is a rigid body capable of rotating on a point on itself. On the basis of the locations of fulcrum, load and effort, the lever is divided into three types. Also, leverage is mechanical advantage gained in a system. It is one of the six simple machines identified by Renaissance scientists. A lever amplifies an input force to provide a greater output force, which is said to provide leverage.

The Mattachine Society , founded in 1950, was an early national gay rights organization in the United States, perhaps preceded only by Chicago's Society for Human Rights. Communist and labor activist Harry Hay formed the group with a collection of male friends in Los Angeles to protect and improve the rights of gay men. Branches formed in other cities, and by 1961 the Society had splintered into regional groups.At the beginning of gay rights protest, news on Cuban prison work camps for homosexuals inspired Mattachine Society to organize protests at the United Nations and the White House in 1965.Founding Harry Hay conceived the idea of a gay activist group in 1948.

Year 1347 (MCCCXLVII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar, and a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Proleptic Gregorian calendar.Events  January–December  January 26 – Charles University in Prague is founded by a bull issued by Pope Clement VI at the request of Charles I, King of Bohemia. February 2 – The Byzantine civil war of 1341–1347 between John VI Kantakouzenos and the regency for John V Palaiologos ends with Kantakouzenos entering Constantinople. April – The Knights Hospitaller defeat a Turkish fleet, and sink 100 ships off Imbros.

Year 1489 ( MCDLXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. April 20 - King Charles VIII of France (died 1498) is born. June 27 – Battle of West Bretten: Maximilian I, Count of Baden defeats Charles, Duke of Lorraine at West Bretten, near Baden-Baden. John Cabot lands at Cape Bon in present day Tunisia, making him the first European to do so since the Romans, and explores parts of the Caribbean and North American coast. The Ottoman Empire captures Rhodes.

Slapstick is a style of humor involving exaggerated physical activity that exceeds the boundaries of normal physical comedy. Slapstick may involve both intentional violence and violence by mishap, often resulting from inept use of props such as saws and ladders. The term arises from a device developed for use in the broad, physical comedy style known as commedia dell'arte in 16th-century Italy. The "slap stick" consists of two thin slats of wood, which make a "slap" when striking another actor, with little force needed to make a loud—and comical—sound.

Year 1208 ( MCCVIII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Halley's Comet was visible in the night sky during this year. In August and September it was observed to break into two distinct pieces, one of which broke up again in December. The breakup of Comet Halley in 1240 was the last time the comet will be visible on Earth in its entirety, though its remains were seen on the return of 1335 and 1456. The Great Slavic uprising against the Teutonic Knights in the Prussians (or "Lithuanian War") ends.

Events January–June January 20 – Russo-Polish War ( 1654–1667 ) : Poland cedes Kiev , Smolensk , and eastern Ukraine (including the cities of Kharkov and Belgorod ) to the Russian Tsardom. January 27 – William III of Orange-Nassau and Mary...
Events May–September July 29 – Second Anglo-Dutch War : Battle of Lowestoft . July 31 – King Louis XIV of France grants the Mississippi River to New France , and awards Louisiana to the Marquis of Denonville . August 3 – The city of...
Events May–September September 1 – The Battle of the Downs takes place, in which Dutch warships defeat the English Navy.

Year 1552 ( MDLII ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Gregorian calendar. ... Events January 15 - Sir Thomas Tresham begins building of Tresham Hall, Kettering, Northants May 11 - King Edward VI succeeds his father King Edward VI of England (died 1553). ...

The year 1552 in art involved some significant events. Events January - Painting of The Holy Family with Saint Anne by Correggio completed. ... Events January 15 - The first volume of Dantes Divine Comedy, the Inferno, begins circulating in manuscript.

In probability theory , the central limit theorem ( CLT ) establishes that , in many situations , when independent data are averaged in a suitable way , their typical values will tend to have a normal distribution (with mean and variance equal to the sample mean and sample variance , respectively) regardless of the actual distribution of the individual values . In other words, the sample average will be approximately normally distributed even if the individual data are not normally distributed , and the amount of the departure from normality decreases as more data are averaged .

Events January–March January 17 – Tuscarora War : Colonel James Moore leads the Carolina militia out of Albemarle County , leaving the Tuscarora to retaliate for previous atrocities. January 18 – The British East India Company establishes its factory at Serampore , West Bengal. February 2 – 400 Cherokees under Cherokee war chief Tsali are killed by Tennessee militiamen and U. The Cherokee chief dies by lethal injection on 16 February. February 3 – King George's War – Siege of Fort Loyall : An English expedition led by William Phipps captures the French Fort Loyal. The 38 surviving French troops surrender.

Perpignan ( , , ; ; ; ) is the prefecture of the Pyrénées-Orientales department ( known as Northern Catalonia in Catalan: Catalunya Nord ), in the former Languedoc region in southern France. Its population numbers approximately 80,000 inhabitants (January 2011), and it is by far the biggest city in the département. It is situated on the Canigou river, which forms part of the Catalan Countries' northern border with France. The city was the seat of a countship from around the 840s until the 12th century when it passed to the King of Majorca.

Year 1037 (MXXXVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – A revolt in northern Italy is started by Archbishop Aribert of Milan. King Henry III (eldest son of Emperor Conrad II) travels south of the Alps to quell it. February – At an Imperial Diet in Pavia (assembled by Conrad II), Aribert is accused of fomenting a revolt against the Holy Roman Empire, Conrad orders his arrest. May – Conrad II, with Pavian assistance, lays siege to Milan at the Porta Romana side, but the city holds out.

The Caucasus , or Caucasia , is a region between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea, mainly occupied by Armenia, Azerbaijan, Georgia, and parts of Southern Russia. The Caucasus Mountains, including the Greater Caucasus range, have historically been considered a natural barrier between Eastern Europe and Western Asia.Mount Elbrus, Europe's highest mountain, is in the Western Caucasus. On the southern side, the Lesser Caucasus includes the Javakheti Plateau and the Armenian highlands, part of which is in Turkey.The Caucasus is divided into the North Caucasus and South Caucasus, although the Western Caucasus also exists as a distinct geographic space within the North Caucasus.

Michelangelo Antonioni ( , ; 29 September 1912 – 30 July 2007 ) was an Italian film director , screenwriter and one of the most influential and innovative artists of international cinema in the 20 th century. Born in the Italian province of Ferrara , Antonioni grew up in a wealthy and cultivated family . He began his career as an art critic and in 1928 wrote a book of essays called Poesie , while studying architecture at the University of Florence . In 1933, Antonioni became a journalist at the newspaper Il Messagero and a year later he began working for Cinema .

Salvador Domingo Felipe Jacinto Dalí i Domènech , 1st Marquess of Dalí of Púbol ( ; ; ; 11 May 1904 – 23 January 1989), known professionally as Salvador Dalí, was a prominent Spanish Catalan surrealist painter born in Figueres, Spain. 1904 Born in Figueras, Spain, on 11 May. 1924 Enrolled at the School of Fine Arts, Madrid, where he began to develop his distinctive style. 1925 His painting, The Basket of Bread, exhibited in Madrid, marks the first use in Spain of surrealist painting techniques.

Year 1332 ( MCCCXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 1800 – Great Britain establishes the Province of Van Diemen's Land in Australia . 1802 – The Spanish colony of Santo Domingo declares independence from Haiti , under Jean-Pierre Boyer ; the Dominican Republic is established. Haiti takes the eastern third of the island, now Haiti ; the United States takes the western third, which later becomes the Dominican Republic . 1810 – Argentina declares its independence from Spain and the First Argentine Republic is established.

Year 1432 (MCDXXXII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 1 – Iliaș succeeds his father as Prince of Moldavia. Spring – An Albanian revolt, led by Gjergj Arianit Komneni, breaks out against the Ottoman Empire, and spreads through most of Albania. April – At the end of the Hook and Cod wars, Jacqueline, Countess of Hainaut and Countess of Holland and Zeeland, is forced by Philip the Good, Duke of Burgundy, to abdicate all her estates in his favour, ending Hainaut and Holland as independent counties.

The Tandy 1000 is the first in a line of IBM PC compatible home computer systems produced by the Tandy Corporation for sale in its Radio Shack and Radio Shack Computer Center chains of stores.OverviewIn December 1983, an executive with Tandy Corporation, maker of TRS-80 computers, said about the new IBM PCjr: "I'm sure a lot of people will be coming out with PCjr look-alikes. The market is big". While preparing the Tandy 2000—the company's first MS-DOS computer—for release in November 1983, Tandy began designing the Tandy 1000, code named "August".

Year 1432 ( MCDXXXII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. (April 6) 12 April: Battle of the Salado. (July 1) 20 June: Pope Eugene IV is elected. (November 11): Battle of Aljubarrota. (April 21) 15 April: English troops under the command of Sir John Fastolf arrive at Lisbon, Portugal. (October 24) Battle of Alarcos. (August 11) Ottoman Empire: Battle of Peñón de Algiers.

Year 1530 ( MDXXX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This article is part of an series. The Treaty of Augsburg ends the Wars of the League of Schmalkalden, which was a conflict between the Lutheran princes in the German-speaking states of Central Europe and the Catholic emperor. It provides for religious freedom within the German-speaking territories, and allows the Catholic princes to keep their lands even if they convert to the Lutheran faith. This is the first of many treaties that are to be signed between the Lutheran princes and the Catholic emperors.

Frederick Barbarossa ( 1122 – 10 June 1190 ) , also known as Frederick I , was the Holy Roman Emperor from 1155 to his death in 1190. He also served as King of Germany continuously from 1152 to 1190. He established the Hohenstaufen dynasty , which became one of the most volatile and war-like dynasties to rule the Holy Roman Empire. He was crowned by Pope Adrian IV , the only time before the Middle Ages that the Holy Roman Emperor was crowned by the Pope rather than by the Holy Roman Emperor himself. As such, he is sometimes called Frederick I of the Germans in historical chronologies.

Events January–March January 8 – Carolean Death March begins : A catastrophic retreat by a largely-Finnish Swedish-Carolean army under the Duke Charles, from Swedish Pomerania to Sweden, during the Torstenson War . January 11 – King Charles II is restored to power in England ; Charles XI is made Duke of Savoy by Louis XIV of France. January 12 – Battle of Wesenberg : The Russians under General Aleksei Saltykov occupy Revel (Tallinn) ; Estonia is now a part of the Russian Tsardom. March 28 – An estimated 20,000 to 30,000 Indians are massacred by the Kikuyu and Maasai tribes.

Year 1161 (MCLXI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  February 3 – Battle of Oslo: King Inge I (the Hunchback) is defeated and killed, while fighting the forces of Haakon II (the Broadshouldered). He is succeeded by Haakon with the 5-year-old Magnus V as co-ruler, but not without challenges to his sovereignty. Magnus II (Henriksson), pretender to the Swedish throne, is murdered by Charles VII (or Karl), who becomes king of Sweden (until 1167).

Niihau (Hawaiian: ), anglicized as Niihau , is the westernmost main and seventh largest inhabited island in Hawaii. It is  southwest of Kauaʻi across the Kaulakahi Channel. Its area is . Several intermittent playa lakes provide wetland habitats for the Hawaiian coot, the Hawaiian stilt, and the Hawaiian duck. The island is designated as critical habitat for Brighamia insignis, an endemic and endangered species of Hawaiian lobelioid. The United States Census Bureau defines Niihau and the neighboring island and State Seabird Sanctuary of Lehua as Census Tract 410 of Kauai County, Hawaii.

Year 1216 ( MCCXVI ) was a leap year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar.
