The Roman numeral L is equivalent to one thousand in Roman numeral notation, which is commonly written as 1,000 in Roman numerals or as M. ... A leap year (or bissextile year) is a calendar year containing one or two leap days.

A playwright or dramatist is a person who writes plays.EtymologyThe word `` play '' is from Middle English pleye , dating from about 1200. The Middle English word pleye derives from the Old English plǣga "to play (a game)", which is from the verb plēwan "to play". [1] The word plēwan also gives English plough , as ploughing is literally the playing out of the soil.The word `` dramatist '' comes from the ancient Greek word dráma , which itself comes from the verb graphein (write) and the noun graphē (writing).

Year 1137 (MCXXXVII) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor John II (Komnenos) leads a Byzantine expeditionary force into Cilicia (the Byzantine fleet guards his flank). He defeats the Armenians under Prince Leo I ("Lord of the Mountains"), and captures the cities of Mersin, Tarsus, Adana and Mamistra. Leo retreats to the great fortifications of Anazarbus – where its garrison resists for 37 days. The Byzantine siege engines batter down its walls, and the city is forced to surrender.

Year 1181 (MCLXXXI) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  King Philip II (Augustus) annuls all loans made by Jews to Christians, and takes a percentage for himself. A year later, he confiscates all Jewish property and expels the Jews from Paris. Philip II begins a war against Philip of Alsace, count of Flanders, over the Vermandois. He claims the territory for his wife Isabella of Hainault as her dowry. Philip is unwilling to give it up.

A horoscope ( or other commonly used names for the horoscope in English include natal chart , astrological chart , birth chart) is a diagram or model representing the positions of celestial objects as they were at the time of the observer‘s birth. In modern times, the horoscope may be cast for any particular location and date, but most often for the place of birth of the astrologer, their clients or a historical person. The horizon at that place in the sky is the “Ecliptic” – the path that the Sun appears to follow in its annual journey across the skies.

In probability theory, the central limit theorem (CLT) establishes that, in many situations, when independent random variables are summed up, their properly normalized sum tends toward a normal distribution (informally a bell curve) even if the original variables themselves are not normally distributed. The theorem is a key concept in probability theory because it implies that probabilistic and statistical methods that work for normal distributions can be applicable to many problems involving other types of distributions. This theorem has seen many changes during the formal development of probability theory.

Year 1175 (MCLXXV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  England  King Henry II begins living openly with his mistress Rosamund Clifford, raising suspicions about their relationship and alienating Henry's wife, Queen Eleanor of Aquitaine. Eleanor of Aquitaine is held under house arrest at Old Sarum Castle in Wiltshire. She is kept in comfort there – fine clothes for her are dispatched regularly from London. Treaty of Windsor: High King Ruaidrí Ua Conchobair (or Roderic O'Conner) relinquishes his title and agrees to submit to Henry II as vassal of Connacht in Ireland.

Year 1494 (MCDXCIV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 4 – The Cetinje Octoechos (Цетињски октоих, an Eastern Orthodox octoechos (liturgy), first tone), the first incunabulum written in the Serbian recension of Church Slavonic, and the first book printed in Cyrillic in Southeast Europe, is completed in Cetinje. January 25 – Alfonso II becomes King of Naples. May – Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor, recognises Perkin Warbeck as rightful King of England. May 5 – Christopher Columbus first sights Jamaica.

Georgy Konstantinovich Zhukov (; ; 1 December 1896 – 18 June 1974) was a Soviet general and Marshal of the Soviet Union. He also served as Chief of the General Staff, Minister of Defence, and was a member of the Presidium of the Communist Party (later Politburo). During the Second World War, Zhukov oversaw some of the Red Army's most decisive victories.Born to a poor peasant family from central Russia, Zhukov was conscripted into the Imperial Russian Army and fought in the First World War. He served in the Red Army during the Russian Civil War.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 1 – The Abenaki tribe and the Massachusetts colonists sign a treaty, ending the conflict in New England. January 4 – The Palace of Whitehall in London, England is destroyed by fire. January 23 – George Louis (who in 1714 will become King George I of Great Britain) becomes Elector of Hanover upon the death of his father, Ernest Augustus. Because the widow of Ernest Augustus, George's mother Sophia, was heiress presumptive as the cousin of Anne, Queen of Great Britain, and Anne's closest eligible heir, George will become King of Great Britain.

Year 1529 (MDXXIX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 2 – The Örebro Synod provides the theological foundation of the Swedish Reformation, following the economic foundation of it, after the Reduction of Gustav I of Sweden. March –  Battle of Shimbra Kure: Imam Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi, with 200 men armed with matchlocks, defeats the army of Dawit II, Emperor of Ethiopia. March 25 – Blood libel against the Jewish community of Bosen (formerly in Hungary, today in Slovakia), on the first day of Passover.

Frederick ( Middle High German : Friderich , Standard German : Friedrich ; 21 September 1371 – 20 September 1440) was the third King of the Roman Empire from the House of Habsburg. His reign was marked by the Hussite Wars , the emergence of the Czech rebellion led by Jan Žižka , the fall of Constantinople to the Turks, and the first battle between the forces of Charles VII of France and Henry V of England for the throne of France. At the end of his reign, the Black Plague spread across Europe.

Year 1319 ( MCCCXIX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. July 21 – Philip IV is crowned Holy Roman Emperor. September 23 – Philip IV of France marries Isabella I of Aragon, in a political move designed to bring the Crown of Aragon firmly under French domination. June 30 – The Treaty of Creci is signed between Serbia and Hungary. August 10 – Alfonso III of Aragon, Count of Barcelona, and King of Sicily is crowned King of Valencia.

Year 1502 (MDII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  January 1 – Portuguese explorers, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sail into Guanabara Bay, Brazil, mistaking it for the mouth of a river, which they name Rio de Janeiro. February 12 – Isabella I issues an edict outlawing Islam in the Crown of Castile, forcing virtually all her Muslim subjects to convert to Christianity. May 3 – Portuguese navigator João da Nova discovers the uninhabited island of Saint Helena.

In the performing arts , a scenario ( , ; from Italian : `` that which is pinned to the stage ` ` ; from Greek : σκένη ` scene ` ) may be a depiction of a fiction, a fictionalised rendering of real events or a dramatised actuality in theatrical performance, television, film, radio drama , interactive theatre , or some other presentation of a scripted or improvised work, e. g., where the narrative, drama or action are fixed to a single place (as opposed to being `on tour ` or travelling).

Otto III (June/July 980 – 23 January 1002) was Holy Roman Emperor from 996 until his early death in 1002. A member of the Ottonian dynasty, Otto III was the only son of the Emperor Otto II and his wife Theophanu.Otto III was crowned as King of Germany in 983 at the age of three, shortly after his father's death in Southern Italy while campaigning against the Byzantine Empire and the Emirate of Sicily. Though the nominal ruler of Germany, Otto III's minor status ensured his various regents held power over the Empire.

Gerard Pieter Hendrik van Velde ( born 30 November 1971 ) is a Dutch retired speed skater who specialised in short distances. He won the gold medal for 500 metres at the 1994 Winter Olympics in Lillehammer. He was also the world record holder for that event until 2006. Van Velde started speed skating in 1984 at the age of twelve. His first international race was in December 1988, where he won the gold medal at the World Junior Short Track Championships. After this successful debut he won another gold medal in March 1990 at the European Short Track Championships.

In mathematics , an -sphere or a hypersphere is a topological space that is homeomorphic to a standard -sphere , where the dimension of the sphere is increased. The simplest example, which is a hypersphere in one dimension, has two points joined by a single line, and every point in the -sphere is the midpoint of one and only one line through it (the diameter of the sphere); in dimension two, the simplest example has three points in a plane, joined by four lines through each of them and forming a regular tetrahedron in the plane.

Year 1538 (MDXXXVIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–June February 24 – Treaty of Nagyvárad: Peace is declared between Ferdinand I, future Holy Roman Emperor and the Ottoman Empire. John Zápolya is recognized as King of Hungary (Eastern Hungarian Kingdom), while Ferdinand retains the northern and western parts of the Kingdom, and is recognized as heir to the throne. April 26 – Battle of Las Salinas: Almagro is defeated by Francisco Pizarro, who then seizes Cusco.

Moore 's law is the observation that the number of transistors in a dense integrated circuit ( IC ) doubles approximately every two years. In the 1965, Gordon Moore ( the founder of Intel Corp ) made this prediction, which has since become known as " Moore 's law ", about the future of semiconductor devices and computer hardware performance. The term has also come to describe the observed trend that over the same period of time, the rate of growth in computing ability (and thus in computer technology in general) has closely followed the rate of Moore 's law.

A Roman villa was typically a farmhouse or country house built in the Roman Republic and the Roman Empire, sometimes reaching extravagant proportions.Typology and distributionPliny the Elder (23–79 AD) distinguished two kinds of villas near Rome: the villa urbana, a country seat that could easily be reached from Rome (or another city) for a night or two; and the villa rustica, the farmhouse estate permanently occupied by the servants who generally had charge of the estate. The Roman Empire contained many kinds of villas, not all of them lavishly appointed with mosaic floors and frescoes.

It is one of eight years ( CE ) to contain each Roman numeral exactly once ( 1000 ( M), 10 ( MC ), 1 ( C), 5 ( D), 100 ( CD), 50 ( 2000 ( DCCC ) and 5 ( 1950 ( DCCCLII) ). 1962 is a number divisible by the following numbers: 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 9, 10, 12, 14, and 15. Including the first number, there is no year divisible by all of these numbers (the last year to be this was 1964).

Year 1387 (MCCCLXXXVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsJanuary–December  Elizabeta Kotromanic, mother of Mary, Queen of Hungary and the former regent of Hungary, is murdered in prison by the Croatian rebels (her daughter is liberated on 4 June). January 1 – Charles III ascends to the throne of Navarre, after the death of his father, Charles II. January 5 – John I succeeds his father, Peter IV, as King of Aragon and Valencia, and forms an alliance with France and Castile.

The Fertile Crescent is a crescent-shaped region in the Middle East , spanning modern-day Iraq , Syria , Lebanon , western and northern Jordan, and southern Turkey . Its historical importance is due to the area's role as the cradle of many of the world's religious traditions, including Judaism , Christianity , and Islam . The name derives from the region’s fertile soils and to a lesser degree to the region’s location as a crescent on the Mediterranean coast. The term was used by the 1st-century geographer Strabo to refer to "the country lying round about the sea" in his Geographica.

Tropical Storm Karen was a system that brought record-breaking rainfall and flooding to southeastern Pennsylvania and other Mid-Atlantic states in October 2013. The twelfth tropical cyclone and eleventh named storm of the well below-average 2013 Atlantic hurricane season, Karen originated from a tropical wave that departed from the west coast of Africa on September 16. After passing south of Jamaica and the Cayman Islands, the storm became a tropical cyclone to the northeast of the Yucatán Peninsula. The storm peaked shortly afterward, with 1-minute sustained winds of 65 mph (100 km/h).

Norwich is a town in Windsor County, in the U.S. state of Vermont. The population was 3,612 at the 2020 census. Home to some of the state of Vermont's wealthiest residents, the municipality is a commuter town for nearby Hanover, New Hampshire across the Connecticut River. The town is part of the Dresden School District, the first interstate school district in the United States, signed into law by President John F. Kennedy. The town contains the Norwich Mid-Century Modern Historic District.History The boundaries of Norwich were established on July 4, 1761, when Governor Benning Wentworth of New Hampshire defined the boundaries of townships in Vermont.

The Caucasus , or Caucasia , is a region between the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea , mainly occupied by the Republics of Armenia , Azerbaijan , and Georgia. The Russian federation is also included in this category. The Caucasus lies in the region between the Black and the Caspian Seas and includes Armenia , Azerbaijan , Georgia , the republics of the North Caucasus and Southern Russia . This is a very large and varied region extending over an area of 833,000 square miles (2,100,000 km2), with a population of approximately 26 million people.

Events January–March January 11 – 1693 Sicily earthquake : Mount Etna erupts , causing a devastating earthquake that affects parts of southern Italy and Sicily. July 4 – In a letter to the king, English diarist John Evelyn warns of what he thinks is the imminent outbreak of plague (it doesn't happen until the following spring, but it is one of the first times this is suggested in the English diary tradition ). July 15 – Battle of Landen – French forces under Marshal de Mérode inflict a defeat on the Spanish army, which suffers 5,000 casualties .

Year 1185 (MCLXXXV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August – King William II (the Good) lands in Epirus with a Siculo-Norman expeditionary force of 200 ships and 80,000 men (including 5,000 knights), and marches as far as the Byzantine city of Thessalonica, which he takes and pillages (massacring some 7,000 Greek citizens). September 11–12 – Isaac II (Angelos) leads a revolt in Constantinople and deposes Emperor Andronikos I (Komnenos).

Year 1486 (MCDLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full Julian calendar for the year).Events  January–December  January 18 – King Henry VII of England and Elizabeth of York are married, uniting the House of Lancaster and the House of York, after the Wars of the Roses. February 16 – Archduke Maximilian I of Habsburg is elected King of the Romans at Frankfurt (crowned April 9 at Aachen). February 18 – Lord Chaitanya Mahaprabhu is born in the town of Nadia, West Bengal, India, just after sunset.

A pine is any conifer tree or shrub in the genus Pinus of the family Pinaceae . Pinus is the sole genus in the subfamily Pinoideae; it is native to warm temperate or subtropical climates from the Northern Hemisphere, extending into tropical areas in the southern highlands of both continents and on a number of oceanic archipelagos. Pines, like other conifers, are large growing evergreen trees or shrubs. They are usually tall and have long, limber branches and pine needles. They have an open crown and a straight trunk; some species are shrubby or small bushes. Some pines have rough, scaly bark.

Year 1507 ( MDVII ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This is the year 1507 in the 15th century. March 1 - John I succeeds King Louis XII as King of Naples. April 10 – Battle of Ravenna: French forces defeat the Spanish under Gonzalo de Cordoba and Guido Ascanio. September 15 – Battle of Seminara: Ottoman Turks and French defeat a joint Spanish and Venetian force. October 25 – Ottoman Turks capture Belgrade ( modern Serbia ), then under Hungarian rule.

Year 1343 ( MCCCXLIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. ... 1347 was a common year starting on Saturday of the Julian calendar. ... 1348 was a leap year starting on Saturday of the Julian calendar. ... Events January 20 - Edward III, King of England, defeats the Scottish army and seizes the Stone of Scone, later known as the Coronation Stone and now held in Westminster Abbey. ... 1350 was a leap year starting on Tuesday of the Julian calendar.

Samuel de Champlain (; c. 13 August 1567 – 25 December 1635) was a French colonist, navigator, cartographer, draftsman, soldier, explorer, geographer, ethnologist, diplomat, and chronicler. He made between 21 and 29 trips across the Atlantic Ocean, and founded Quebec, and New France, on 3 July 1608. An important figure in Canadian history, Champlain created the first accurate coastal map during his explorations, and founded various colonial settlements.Born into a family of sailors, Champlain began exploring North America in 1603, under the guidance of his uncle, François Gravé Du Pont.

Tone is the use of pitch in language to distinguish lexical or grammatical meaning – that is , to distinguish between and among words that differ in some sense other than their meaning (as in tonality in music). Tone can be used to convey emotion, attitude, emphasis, intent, and other information about what a person really means when they say or write something. One can also speak of "high tone" versus "low tone". The word tone comes from Greek. The word for "high" in Greek was ὤψ ōps meaning "eyes".

Year 1171 ( MCLXXI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Byzantine-Arab Wars or Byzantine-Muslim wars are a series of destructive wars fought between the Muslim Arabs and Byzantines from 632 AD to the 11th century. Most of the wars took place in the provinces of the eastern part of the Roman empire and were accompanied by devastation and famine. ( Byzantine-Arab Wars ) The Battle of the Orontes was fought between a large Umayyad army and the Byzantines in 872 near the city of Amid, then in the Sassanid controlled region of Syria.

Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the farthest jump after sliding down on their skis from a specially designed curved ramp. Along with jump length, competitor's aerial style and other factors also affect the final score. Ski jumping was first contested in Norway in the late 19th century, and later spread through Europe and North America in the early 20th century. Along with cross-country skiing, it constitutes the traditional group of Nordic skiing disciplines.The ski jumping venue, commonly referred to as a hill, consists of the jumping ramp (in-run), take-off table, and a landing hill.

Events  January – March  January 7 – In India, Sufi rebel leader Shah Inayat Shaheed from Sindh who had led attacks against the Mughal Empire, is beheaded days after being tricked into meeting with the Mughals to discuss peace. January 17 – Jeremias III reclaims his role as the Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople, chief leader within the Eastern Orthodox Church, 16 days after the Metropolitan Cyril IV of Pruoza had engineered an election to become the Patriarch. February 14 – The reign of Victor Amadeus over the principality of Anhalt-Bernburg (now within the state of Saxony-Anhalt in northeastern Germany) ends after 61 years and 7 months.

Year 1298 ( MCCXCVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This page was last modified on 29 August 2016, at 18:58. Content is available under Attribution-ShareAlike 2.5 as long as the original author and source are credited, with no modifications except for formatting. See "Usage" on Wikia for policy and legal information. This is the most common time of the year to have a new year's celebration because it takes place between the autumn and winter solstices. Easter, which is celebrated by Christians annually, is the most important celebration of the year.

Dari ( , , ) , or Dari Persian , is a political term used for the various dialects of Persian spoken in present-day Afghanistan and the general cultural sphere where the language is spoken and the dialects are used. In Afghanistan, the language is called Fārsī, while the term Dari is reserved for literary language and the standard language form used in educational and cultural institutions in Afghanistan. The language has many dialects. In neighboring countries it is known as "Dari". Dari is a registered language in Afghanistan and one of the two official languages.

Year 1219 ( MCCXIX ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Abbasid Caliphate is overthrown by the Mamluk Sultanate of Egypt and Syria, with the Caliph Al-Adid captured. August 6 – King Afonso I of Portugal and Afonso II of Portugal begin their joint reign, following the death of Afonso's brother, Sancho I.
August 25 – A Mongol-Turkish army led by Jebe, a trusted general of Genghis Khan, is defeated in the Battle of the Kalka River.

Johan August Arfwedson (12 January 1792 – 28 October 1841) was a  Swedish chemist who discovered the chemical element lithium in 1817 by isolating it as a salt.Life and work Arfwedson belonged to a wealthy bourgeois family, the son of the wholesale merchant and factory owner Jacob Arfwedson and his spouse, Anna Elisabeth Holtermann. The younger Arfwedson matriculated as a student at the University of Uppsala in 1803 (at the time, matriculating at a young age was common for aristocratic and wealthy students), completed a degree in Law in 1809 and a second degree in mineralogy in 1812.

Year 1357 ( MCCCLVII ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 25 – Pope Eugene IV recognises Charles VII as King of France. March 27 – Battle of Nogent-sur-Seine: The French defeat the English, capturing Henry V.
August 9 – The Ottomans retake Belgrade. September 18 – Battle of Krbava Field: In Croatia , the Croats under John Jelačić defeat the Ottoman Empire. September 27 – The Ottomans defeat the Hungarians and capture Szigetvar ( modern Hungary ). December 28 – The Ottomans capture Edirne .

Political identity came to the territory now occupied by the Principality of Liechtenstein in 814, with the formation of the subcountry of Lower Rhætia. Liechtenstein's borders have remained unchanged since 1434, when the Rhine established the border between the Holy Roman Empire and the Swiss cantons.AntiquityA Roman road crossed the region from south to north, traversing the Alps by the Splügen Pass and, following the right bank of the Rhine at the edge of the floodplain, was uninhabited for long lengths of time because of periodic flooding. Roman villas  have been excavated in Schaanwald and Nendeln.

In art history , literature and cultural studies , Orientalism is the imitation or depiction of aspects in the Eastern world , particularly in the Near and Middle East , Egypt and the Far East , such as India , China , Afghanistan , Iran , Japan , Tibet and Turkey. Orientalism in the art context refers to a tradition of romantic depictions of exotic foreign cultures in the art of Western nations, particularly Europe. It was first used in the early 19th century in the West to describe eastern lands that were a subject of European interest.

Lillian Evelyn Gilbreth ( Moller; May 24, 1878 – January 2, 1972) was an American psychologist, industrial engineer, consultant, and educator who was an early pioneer in applying psychology to time-and-motion studies. She was described in the 1940s as "a genius in the art of living." Gilbreth, one of the first female engineers to earn a Ph.D., is considered to be the first industrial/organizational psychologist. She and her husband, Frank Bunker Gilbreth, were efficiency experts who contributed to the study of industrial engineering, especially in the areas of motion study and human factors.

Year 1250 (MCCL) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsBy placeWorld  The world population is estimated at between 400 and 416 million individuals. World climate transitions from the Medieval Warm Period to the Little Ice Age. Medieval music: The Notre Dame school of polyphony ends.Europe  February 2 – King Eric XI (Eriksson) dies and is succeeded by the 10-year-old Valdemar I, who is the eldest son of Birger jarl. He is elected as ruler of Sweden, and becomes the first Swedish king of the House of Folkung.

Year 990 (CMXC) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Al-Mansur, de facto ruler of Al-Andalus, conquers the Castle of Montemor-o-Velho (modern Portugal), expanding the Umayyad Caliphate of Córdoba. The city of Lund, Sweden is founded, during the reign of the Danish king Sweyn Forkbeard (approximate date). Africa  The Ghana Empire takes the Berber town of Aoudaghost (modern Mauritania) as the West African nation makes further gains. Construction of the Al-Hakim Mosque by orders of the Fatimid vizier Gawar Al-Siqilli begins in Cairo (modern Egypt).

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus (; Latin "oak tree") of the beech family, Fagaceae. There are approximately 500 extant species of oaks. The common name "oak" also appears in the names of species in related genera, notably Lithocarpus (stone oaks), as well as in those of unrelated species such as Grevillea robusta (silky oaks) and the Casuarinaceae (she-oaks). The genus Quercus is native to the Northern Hemisphere, and includes deciduous and evergreen species extending from cool temperate to tropical latitudes in the Americas, Asia, Europe, and North Africa.

Élie Ducommun (19 February 1833, Geneva – 7 December 1906, Bern) was a Swiss peace activist. He was a Nobel laureate, awarded the 1902 Nobel Peace Prize, which he shared with Charles Albert Gobat.Born in Geneva, he worked as a tutor, language teacher, journalist and a translator for the Swiss federal Chancellery (1869–1873).In 1867 he helped to found the Ligue de la paix et de la liberté (League of Peace and Freedom), though he continued working at other positions, including secretary for the Jura-Simplon Steel Company from 1873 to 1891.

The picometre ( international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures ; SI symbol : pm; abbreviation pm or pmt ) is the one-thousandth part of a metre (10−3), which is approximately equal to the width of a proton, and hence is very close to the width of an electron. Other units derived from it are the nanometre, the millimetre, the micrometre and the metre. In the past, before the picometre was recognized as a base unit of the International System of Units, these units were commonly called decametres and the metre was called the hectometre.

Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the farthest jump after sliding down on their skis. The first ski jump was held in Norway in the 14th century, where men would jump from a wooden tower in the hope that they would be able to land on a pile of stones. Women didn’t start taking part until the late 1900s, when the first event was held at a resort in Stubai, Austria. Ski jumping was first included in the Olympics in 1924, but was removed in 1944 because of wartime conditions.

Albury–Wodonga is the broad settlement incorporating the twin Australian cities of Albury and Wodonga , which are separated geographically by the Murray River. The cities are connected by the Hume Highway and the Murray River , which forms the state border between Victoria and New South Wales. In August 2017, Albury-Wodonga had an estimated urban area population of 96,790. Albury Wodonga has the largest population in the Murray Valley, an area which is also known as the Southern Riverina , and is considered part of the Hume Region . The urban area population of Albury and Wodonga together forms Australia's largest inland metropolitan area.

Sigismund ( 26 October 1427 – 4 March 1496 ) , a member of the House of Habsburg , was Holy Roman Emperor and King of Hungary & Croatia , as well as, for a brief period in 1433/4 , King of Italy . Between 1437 and 1493 , he also was the ruler of Bohemia , Luxembourg, Austrian Niederösterreich (Lower Austria ), Styria, Carinthia , Tyrol , and parts of the present-day German states of Saxony , Thuringia , and Swabia . During the last ten years of his reign , he also claimed the Polish crown , but never ruled in Poland .

Events January–June January 13 – Edward Sexby , who had plotted against Oliver Cromwell , dies in the Tower of London. March 22 – Charles II of England is officially declared King of Scotland, in London. May 26 – Oliver Cromwell is formally declared Lord Protector of England, Wales, Scotland and Ireland by the English Parliament. August 5 – Battle of Carbisdale: The English parliamentarian army led by General Monck defeats the Jacobites. August 7 – Charles II lands at Dover. August 8 – Charles II, the king of England, returns to his country after a seven year exile in France.

Dari (, , ), or Dari Persian , is a political term used for the various dialects of the Persian language spoken in Afghanistan. Dari is the term officially recognised and promoted since 1964 by the Afghan government for the Persian language, hence it is known as Afghan Persian or Eastern Persian in many Western sources. As Professor Nile Green remarks "the impulses behind renaming of Afghan Persian as Dari were more nationalistic than linguistic" in order to create an Afghan state narrative. Persian in Afghanistan is generally called Fārsi (فارسی) by Persian-speakers and Pārsi (پارسی) by ethnic Pashtuns.

Year 1051 ( MLI ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Hittite Kingdom collapses, and is absorbed by Armenia and the Kingdom of Van. The Kingdom of Cilicia is established. Armenian King Tirdat IV is crowned. Rashidun Empire: Caliph Abu Yazid, son and designated successor of Muqtadir, dies after a short reign. Caliph Muqtadir's son Mahdi dies shortly afterwards, leaving no designated heir. The governor of Egypt Ziyadat Allah succeeds Muqtadir and is crowned Caliph. The Second Council of Constantinople convenes under the papacy of Leo the Great.

Divorce ( also known as dissolution of marriage ) is the process of terminating a marriage or marital union . The term “divorce” comes from the word ” divorcee ” which is derived from the Old French word divorz , and is from the Latin word […]
Wills, Trusts & Estate Law – A Brief Introduction
Wills, Trusts & Estate Law is a legal area that involves a wide variety of practice areas. A Will, for instance, can be used to appoint a guardian for a minor child. Or, a Trust may be established to provide for medical or educational purposes.

Year 1449 (MCDXLIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 6 – Constantine XI Palaiologos is crowned Byzantine Emperor at Mistra; he will be the last in a line of rulers that can be traced to the founding of Rome. February – Alexăndrel seizes the throne of Moldavia, with the support of the boyars. March 24 – Hundred Years' War: English capture Fougères in Brittany. April 7 – The last Antipope, Felix V, abdicates. April 19 – Pope Nicholas V is elected by the Council of Basel.

In computational complexity theory, PSPACE is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine using a polynomial amount of space.Formal definition If we denote by SPACE(t(n)), the set of all problems that can be solved by Turing machines using O(t(n)) space for some function t of the input size n, then we can define PSPACE formally asPSPACE is a strict superset of the set of context-sensitive languages.It turns out that allowing the Turing machine to be nondeterministic does not add any extra power.

Events January–June January–June – The Swiss Peasant War is fought . January 3 – By the Coonan Cross Oath , Irish Catholic noblemen and clergy in.. December 20 – In India, English East India Company troops under Colonel Robert Clive defeat the last Maratha Hindu ruler of Bengal and the surrounding provinces.. January 6 – A fire breaks out in the French naval port of Rochefort, destroying a majority of the ships in the French East India Company fleet, and nearly a third of the French navy. February 12 – Peter III of Portugal is crowned King of Portugal in Santarém after the assassination of John IV of Portugal.

OS-9 is a family of real-time , process-based , multitasking , multi-user operating systems , developed in the 1980s , for the Apple II, Apple IIGS and Macintosh series computers. ... The BIOS is the fundamental software which allows the hardware of a computerized system to be used and interacts with the system firmware. The BIOS, which stands for Basic Input/Output System is stored in a specific memory of a computer (in the form of a small program, usually on a flash memory or ROM chip) and is initially loaded at boot time by a microcontroller, called a bootstrap loader .

Frederick James Prinze (born Frederick Karl Pruetzel; June 22, 1954 – January 29, 1977) was an American stand-up comedian and actor. Prinze was the star of the NBC-TV sitcom Chico and the Man from 1974 until his suicide in 1977, when he shot himself in the head at the young age of 22. Prinze was the father of actor Freddie Prinze Jr.Early lifePrinze was born Frederick Karl Pruetzel (German spelling: Prützel) at Saint Clare's Hospital in Manhattan, New York City the son of Edward Karl Pruetzel and Maria de Gracia Pruetzel (née Graniela y Ramirez).

Year 1292 ( MCCXCII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. June 22 – Pope Boniface VIII is elected. Ming–Yuan Warring States Period: Xuande Emperor, Emperor of the Ming Dynasty, takes power over China. Genghis Khan dies from an unspecified illness in Karakorum, Mongolia. His empire breaks up into a number of Khanates. Kubilai Khan succeeds his great-grandfather, Guyuk Khan, and begins his reign as the new Great Khan of the Mongol Empire. Petrus de Rivo becomes the 39th Bishop of Bologna, in the Kingdom of Italy.

Year 1046 (MXLVI) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Autumn – King Henry III (the Black) travels to Italy to secure the imposition of Guido da Velate, archbishop of Milan, and other similarly loyal candidates in other sees (like Ravenna, Verona and Modena). Vatha Pagan Revolt: King Peter Orseolo (the Venetian) is overthrown after a 2-year reign. Bishops Gerard of Csanád and Bystrík (or Bestricus) are stoned to death in Budapest (Hungary).

In mathematics , two sets are said to be disjoint sets if they have no element in common . Equivalently, two sets are disjoint when they have no intersection . A set with no elements is also disjoint. A set A is an element of its own complement; it is an element of the set of sets that are disjoint to A. The complement of A, denoted , is defined as . Disjointness implies the following properties:
If A = B, then A is disjoint to A. For any sets A, B and C, the sets A \ B and A \ C are disjoint.

Vanity Fair is an English novel by William Makepeace Thackeray, which follows the lives of Becky Sharp and Amelia Sedley amid their friends and families during and after the Napoleonic Wars. It was first published as a 19-volume monthly serial from 1847 to 1848, carrying the subtitle Pen and Pencil Sketches of English Society, which reflects both its satirisation of early 19th-century British society and the many illustrations drawn by Thackeray to accompany the text. It was published as a single volume in 1848 with the subtitle A Novel without a Hero, reflecting Thackeray's interest in deconstructing his era's conventions regarding literary heroism.

Year 1337 ( MCCCXXXVII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. 16 September - The Council of Constance opens. July - Pope Gregory XII resigns as Pope, due to his age and failing health. 25 January - The Council of Constance elects Pope Martin V.
20 June–2 July - The Council of Constance declares the Knights Templar to be heretical. 15 October - The Council of Constance issues the decree Donum super partes and ends the papal schism. The Ottoman Empire declares war on Christian Hungary, opening the Ottoman-Hungarian wars.

GNU Privacy Guard ( GnuPG or GPG ) is a free-software replacement for Symantec 's PGP cryptographic software suite . GPG is available on a number of platforms including most Unix systems , including GNU / Linux, BSD, Mac OS X, and Solaris . It is distributed as part of the Debian operating system , as well as in other Debian based distributions . GPG is also used by default in Fedora . GPG is a full implementation of OpenPGP as defined in RFC-2440 , with the major exception that it does not comply with the MIME type of MIME . GPG supports asymmetric key cryptography and public key cryptography .

Year 1472 ( MCDLXXII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. A series of calamitous natural events occurred in Europe during the winter and spring, including heavy rains, floods, and storms, killing many people. This article describes the events of July 1565 throughout the world. In February 1865, the United States and France signed an alliance and the French government secretly supplied Union troops with ships, arms, and munitions. The Treaty of Paris (1783), in which Great Britain acknowledged the independence of the former colonies, was signed on September 3.

Andrew Stuart "Andy" Fastow (born December 22, 1961) is a convicted felon and former financier who was the chief financial officer of Enron Corporation, an energy trading company based in Houston, Texas, until he was fired shortly before the company declared bankruptcy. Fastow was one of the key figures behind the complex web of off-balance-sheet special purpose entities (limited partnerships which Enron controlled) used to conceal Enron's massive losses in their quarterly balance sheets. By unlawfully maintaining personal stakes in these ostensibly independent ghost-entities, he was able to defraud Enron out of tens of millions of dollars.

Year 1302 (MCCCII) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  April 10 – The first meeting of the Estates General of the Kingdom of France is convened by Philip IV of France, at the Notre-Dame in Paris.May 18 – Bruges Matins: The French garrison in Bruges is massacred at night, by members of the local Flemish militia. June 12 – Rakvere, Estonia, receives Lübeck city rights. July 11 – Battle of the Golden Spurs (also called the Battle of Courtrai): the County of Flanders gains a major victory over the Kingdom of France.

Year 1489 (MCDLXXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 14 – The Queen of Cyprus, Catherine Cornaro, sells her kingdom to the Republic of Venice. March 26 – The Treaty of Medina del Campo between England and Spain includes provision for a marriage between Arthur, the son of King Henry VII of England, and Princess Catherine of Aragon.June 29 – King James IV grants Andrew, Lord Gray, the lands and Barony of Lundie in Scotland. July 17 – Delhi Sultanate: Sikandar Lodi succeeds Bahlul Khan Lodi as sultan.

A domain name is an identification string that defines a realm of administrative autonomy , authority or control within the Internet . It is used in various networking parameters , such as host names , URLs , and mail box names . Its name is derived from the word domain , which is related to the concept of a realm of a king . The term is also used more generally to mean a subordinate branch of a larger division of authority or power. It can also refer to a set of interconnected networks under the administration of an organization , a company or a community.

Year 1149 (MCXLIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) recovers Corfu with the help of the Venetians, who defeat the Sicilian fleet. During the three-month siege, Byzantine admiral Stephen Kontostephanos  is killed by a stone thrown by a catapult. Manuel prepares an offensive against the Normans, King Roger II sends a fleet (some 40 ships) under George of Antioch to pilliage the suburbs of Constantinople.

Year 1509 (MDIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–June  February 3 – Battle of Diu: The Portuguese defeat a coalition of Indians, Muslims and Italians. April 21 – Henry VIII becomes King of England (for 38 years) on the death of his father, Henry VII. April 27 – Pope Julius II places Venice under interdict and excommunication, for refusing to cede part of Romagna to papal control. May 14 – Battle of Agnadello: French forces defeat the Venetians.

The hobby of collecting includes seeking, locating, acquiring, organizing, cataloging, displaying, storing, and maintaining items that are of interest to an individual collector. Collections differ in a wide variety of respects, most obviously in the nature and scope of the objects contained, but also in purpose, presentation, and so forth. The range of possible subjects for a collection is practically unlimited, and collectors have realised a vast number of these possibilities in practice, although some are much more popular than others.In collections of manufactured items, the objects may be antique or simply collectable.

The Roman conquest of Britain was a process that consisted of the conquest of territory located on the island of Britain by occupying Roman forces. It began in AD 43 under Emperor Claudius, and was largely completed by 87 when the Stanegate was established.The Roman army was generally recruited in Italia, Hispania, and Gaul. To control the English Channel they used the newly formed fleet.The Romans under their general Aulus Plautius first forced their way inland in several battles against British tribes, including the Battle of the Medway, the Battle of the Thames, and in later years Caratacus's last battle against Caratacus and the Roman conquest of Anglesey.

Panettone ( , ; ) is an Italian type of sweet bread originally from Milan , usually prepared and enjoyed in the Christmas season , but can also be enjoyed all year round. It is often flavored with dried fruit and served as a sweet dessert. The word comes from the Italian verb panare, which means to bread or knead dough . Panetton is the Tuscan variant, and pannettone is the Emilian variant. The modern panettone is an adaptation of the "briocheschino" (little bread bun), a simple type of sweet bread made in Milan for hundreds of years.

Epicureanism is a system of philosophy founded around 307 BC based upon the teachings of the ancient Greek philosopher Epicurus (341-270 BC). Epicurus was the most influential representative of the school of philosophy called the New Academy, which was founded by his father. The main tenets of his philosophy were the belief that all things are made up from atoms (microscopic particles that can’t be divided further) and that gods are indifferent to human affairs. Epicurus also argued against Plato’s theory of forms, claiming that nothing exists beyond the perceived world.

Business is the activity of making one's living or making money by producing or buying and selling products (such as goods and services). Simply put, it is "any activity or enterprise entered into for profit. "Having a business name does not separate the business entity from the owner, which means that the owner of the business is responsible and liable for debts incurred by the business. If the business acquires debts, the creditors can go after the owner's personal possessions. A business structure does not allow for corporate tax rates.

Year 1337 (MCCCXXXVII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  March 16 – Edward, the Black Prince establishes the Duchy of Cornwall, becoming the first English Duke. May 24 – Philip VI of France confiscates Gascony from English control. August – English forces relieve Stirling Castle, ending Edward III of England's last campaign in Scotland. October – Hundred Years' War: Edward III of England formally rejects Philip VI's claim to the French throne, initiating hostilities between France and England.

Dyson's eternal intelligence concept (the Dyson Scenario), proposed by Freeman Dyson in 1979, proposes a means by which an immortal society of intelligent beings in an open universe may escape the prospect of the heat death of the universe by extending subjective time to infinity even though expending only a finite amount of energy.Bremermann's limit can be invoked to deduce that the amount of time to perform a computation on 1 bit is inversely proportional to the change in energy in the system. As a result, the amount of computations that can be performed grows over time.

Events January–March January 5 – The Brandenburger—African Company , of the German state of Brandenburg , signs a greaty with the United Kingdom , giving the British the exclusive rights to the importation of African products and slaves into the port of Cape Town. January 17 – In Massachusetts , the town meeting system is established, by which residents of each town gather in a central location to discuss local issues. The first state to do so. January 20 – The University of Edinburgh is founded in Scotland as a chartered corporation, under the name “The Incorporation of the Royal College of Surgeon in Edinburgh.

Dengue fever is a mosquito-borne tropical disease caused by the dengue virus. Symptoms typically begin three to fourteen days after infection. These may include a high fever, headache, vomiting, muscle and joint pains, and a characteristic skin rash. Recovery generally takes two to seven days. In a small proportion of cases, the disease develops into a more severe dengue hemorrhagic fever, resulting in bleeding, low levels of blood platelets and blood plasma leakage, or into dengue shock syndrome, where dangerously low blood pressure occurs.Dengue is spread by several species of female mosquitoes of the Aedes genus, principally Aedes aegypti.

Year 1203 ( MCCIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 21 – Crusaders storm the fortress of Maarat al-Numan , capturing it. April – Crusaders besiege Antioch for the third time since the Battle of Antioch (1098). June 28 – First Crusade – Battle of Civita Castellana: Duke Godfrey of Lorraine's crusader army, besieging Civita Castellana , is attacked by a coalition of Lombard and Roman armies. Godfrey retreats from the battlefield, and is later captured by the Roman army and sentenced to life imprisonment.

The Laboratory for Atmospheric and Space Physics (LASP) is a research organization at the University of Colorado Boulder. LASP is a research institute with over one hundred research scientists ranging in fields from solar influences, to Earth's and other planetary atmospherics processes, space weather, space plasma and dusty plasma physics. LASP has advanced technical capabilities specializing in designing, building, and operating spacecraft and spacecraft instruments.HistoryFounded after World War II, the first scientific instruments built at LASP were launched into space using captured German V-2 rockets. To this day LASP continues a suborbital rocket program through periodic calibration instrument flights from White Sands Missile Range.

DeCSS is one of the first free computer programs capable of decrypting content on a commercially produced DVD video disc. Its existence, as well as the existence of the underlying technology that made it possible—the DeCSS software toolkit—were made known in 1999 after Jon Lech Johansen successfully used the toolkit to de-encode a commercial DVD movie, The Matrix Reloaded. Johansen’s original intentions had been merely to see if the content was encrypted or encoded using an open standard, and to determine if the encryption was strong. However, DeCSS subsequently became the center of much debate about the morality of circumventing such technological protection.

Year 1169 (MCLXIX) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Late Summer – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) sends an embassy to Egypt to demand tribute, and threatens the country with war when they refuse to pay it. The Byzantine fleet under Admiral Andronikos Kontostephanos sets out from the Hellespont; 60 war galleys are sent to Palestine. with money for "the knights of Jerusalem". Andronikos with the rest of the fleet sails to Cyprus, at which he defeats a patrolling squadron of 6 Fatimid ships.

Year 1439 (MCDXXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  May 4 – Battle of Grotnik: Władysław III's royal army defeats the Hussite movement in Poland. June 29 – Date of Venerable Macarius' Miracle of the Moose, according to Russian hagiographers. July 6 – Pope Eugene IV issues the Bull of Union with the Greeks, proclaiming the end of the East–West Schism, which was repudiated by most eastern bishops shortly thereafter. September 8 – Cardinal Giovanni Vitelleschi captures Foligno, ending Trinci's signoria.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Monday , one day ahead of the Julian and one day behind the Gregorian calendar until 1700, then one day later than Gregorian calendar until . The Swedish Empire encompassed the whole of Scandinavia, most of the Baltic sea shores and overseas territories during the 17th century. Swedish trading companies built the first modern long-distance colonies in the 17th century, which paved the way for the nation's later expansion during the Age of Great Power. The Swedish era of Great Power status began with the Thirty Years War, when Sweden joined the anti-Habsburg alliance.

Charles Pierce (July 14, 1926 – May 31, 1999) was one of the 20th century's foremost female impersonators, particularly noted for his impersonation of Bette Davis.Life and careerBorn in Watertown, New York, he began his show business career playing the organ and acting in radio dramas at station WWNY. He branched out into a comedy routine, attired in tuxedo, yet managing to evoke eerily convincing imitations of popular movie actresses. Eschewing the term drag queen, which he hated, he billed himself as a male actress.Initially playing in small gay clubs, his fame spread.

Year 1035 (MXXXV) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  July – The 8-year-old William I becomes duke of Normandy, after his father Robert I (the Magnificent) dies, on a pilgrimage at Nicaea (modern Turkey). Robert's death leads to a period of instability in Normandy, as William is too young to take his father's place. The Norman nobles in the region take the opportunity to settle old feuds, and to increase their private wealth.

Year 1422 (MCDXXII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 10 – Hussite Wars – Battle of Deutschbrod: The Hussites defeat 2,000 Royalist Crusaders. March 21–May 2 – Hundred Years' War – Siege of Meaux: Meaux surrenders to the English. June 10–September – The Ottoman sultan Murad II besieges Constantinople; the siege is broken off as a result of the rebellion of Küçük Mustafa. August 22 – Use of the Spanish era dating system in the Kingdom of Portugal ceases.

An oak is a tree or shrub in the genus Quercus ( ; Latin `` oak tree '' ) of the beech family, Fagaceae. Oak trees can live to be 500 years old or more. They can grow up to 40 metres (130 ft) tall. They have broad leaves 10 - 25 centimetres (4 - 10 in) across, with a smooth edge. The flowers are on a catkin, hanging from a leaf bud. They live in the Northern hemisphere, from Europe and Asia, to North America and the northernmost tip of South America.

The earliest arrival of people in the islands now known as The Bahamas was in the first millennium AD . A Lucayan archaeological site dating from 300 BC to 1500 AD was located on Bimini. The Lucayan, or Arawak, tribe inhabited The Bahamas when Christopher Columbus landed there in 1492. Columbus sighted the island of San Salvador while searching for a route to Cathay, the legendary Chinese empire. The islands were uninhabited when he landed there in 1492, and the original Lucayan inhabitants called them the "Islands of the Bajari." Spanish settlers arrived on the islands in the 1500s.

Pearl Harbour is a small harbour at the head of the Waiau River, in the town of Manapouri on the South Island of New Zealand.The harbour and town are located at the south-east corner of Lake Manapouri. The name was given to the harbour soon after the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, Hawaii in 1941.Pearl Harbour is used mainly by ferry and water taxi operators transporting Meridian Energy staff  across Lake Manapouri to the Manapouri Hydroelectric Power Station, on the West Arm of the lake. Ferries also carry tourists travelling to the power station and onwards to Doubtful Sound, located on the coast 10 km beyond the West Arm.

Charles XV also Carl ( Carl Ludvig Eugen ) ; Swedish : Karl XV and Norwegian : Karl IV ( Karl Øystein ) ; was King of Sweden and Norway from 18 July 1859 until his death. The son of king Oscar I, he was the second king of a union that united Sweden and Norway until the dissolution on 7 June 1905. His name was Carl after his grandfather, the first king Carl XIV of Sweden. He was born as Carl Oscar in Stockholm palace, the third son of the future king Oscar.

Year 1372 ( MCCCLXXII ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The 14th century has been described as an age of discovery. Lazzi (; from the Italian lazzo, a joke or witticism) are stock comedic routines that are associated with Commedia dell'arte. Performers, especially those playing the masked Arlecchino, had many examples of this in their repertoire, and would use improvisatory skills to weave them into the plot of dozens of different commedia scenarios. These largely physical sequences could be improvised or preplanned within the performance and were often used to enliven the audience when a scene was dragging, to cover a dropped line or cue, or to delight an expectant audience with the troupe's specialized lazzi.Lazzi could be completed by a single player (e.g.

Events January–December February 21 – The Prussian Confederation is formed . April 9 – Christopher of Bavaria is elected King of the Romans by the Imperial Diet, as the successor to Charles V. ...
Events January–December February 24 – Henry IV of France is crowned King of Navarre at Pamplona, Spain . February 25 – Henry IV of France, king of Navarre becomes King of France. March 1 – Henry IV ...
Events January–December March 20 – Coronation of Henry IV of France as king of Navarre in Pamplona, Spain . March 23 – Henry, Prince of Wales, and Elizabeth of York are married in Winchester Cathedral.

A sifaka is a lemur of the genus Propithecus from the family Indriidae within the order Primates . The name is derived from sivaká, the name for the lemurs in the local Malagasy language . They are endemic to Madagascar and the nearest islands. The most closely related group is the indri with which they share the same island. Other primate genera with similar morphology are lemurs and sportive lemurs , but unlike those genera, they do not include the sifaka within the family. Although they look like lemurs they do not belong to the family of lemurs but rather to the indris.

The Khlysts or Khlysty (,  "whips") were an underground Spiritual Christian sect, which split from the Russian Orthodox Church and existed from the 1600s until the late 20th century.NameThe members of the sect referred to themselves by various names, including "God's People" (liudi bozh'i), "followers of Christ's faith" (Khristovovery), or simply "Christs" (Khristy). The appellation "Khlysty" is a derogatory term applied by critics of the sect. The origin of the term is disputed.

Tropical Storm Karen was a system that brought record-breaking rainfall and flooding to southeastern Pennsylvania and other Mid-Atlantic states in the U.S.
Scientists have been monitoring Karen's effects on the Earth system. Their studies are providing important insight into how hurricanes, and tropical storms in general, impact our atmosphere, weather patterns, ocean currents and other areas of the environment. These studies are also providing scientists with information about how these weather phenomena, and their effects on climate, may change in the future. The study was funded by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.

Year 1511 ( MDXI ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Kingdom of Hungary, led by King Louis II of Hungary , makes a second attempt to regain control of the Kingdom of Croatia . Following the death of Manuel II Paleologus, Andronikos is elected as new Patriarch of Constantinople . Treaty of Granada: Muhammad XII of Granada surrenders his kingdom to Ferdinand and Isabella of Spain . Mansa Musa , the ruler of Mali , makes his famous pilgrimage to Mecca and causes the gold currency of the time to plummet.

Arthur Andersen LLP was an American holding company based in Chicago . Formerly one of the `` Big Five '' accounting firms, it was well known for its annual survey of corporate executive compensation. The company prepared tax returns, audited financial statements, performed due diligence on mergers and acquisitions, and provided a host of other accounting services. The company changed its name to Accenture in 2001 after its conviction on criminal charges stemming from the collapse of energy company Enron. Arthur Andersen was born in Copenhagen, Denmark and emigrated with his family to America in 1885.

Year 1316 (MCCCXVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 28–March 18 – Llywelyn Bren revolts against English rule in Wales. February 22 – Battle of Picotin: Catalan forces of Ferdinand of Majorca defeat those of Matilda of Hainaut on the Peloponnese. July 5 – Battle of Manolada: Forces of the Duchy of Burgundy defeat the Kingdom of Majorca, kill its king, Ferdinand, and conquer the Principality of Achaea. August – Battle of Gransee: A North German-Danish alliance, led by Henry II of Mecklenburg, decisively defeats the forces of Waldemar of Brandenburg.

Year 1310 ( MCCCX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. April 21 – King Philip IV of France invades England at the start of the first War of Scottish Independence. August 22 – Pope Innocent III excommunicates King Philip IV of France. August 29 – Battle of Falkirk. Edward I of England is victorious over William Wallace and Andrew Moray, but the English suffer 200-300 dead. September 13 – Battle of Morgarten. December 1 – Battle of Lumphanan: Robert the Bruce fights the English.

In the Swedish calendar it was a common year starting on Tuesday , one day ahead of the Julian and ten days ahead of the Gregorian calendar. This was also the last common year that started on Tuesday in Sweden. The year is dominated by the first year of warfare in the American Civil War; the war would last 4 years, but would only be formally resolved with the signing of the Treaty of Paris in , 50 years after the start of hostilities. The year also marked the beginning of the New Imperialism.

Year 1502 ( MDII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. July - King Henry VII marries his former fiancée, Elizabeth of York, thus uniting the houses of Lancaster and York in what will become known as the "Tudor" dynasty. The marriage is celebrated in London in a spectacular pageant in the presence of several European rulers. September 24 - The Treaty of Granada ends the last remnants of the Emirate of Granada in the Iberian Peninsula by recognizing the Catholic Monarchs' de facto power over the area, and giving them a monopoly on trade.

In physics, optical depth or optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted radiant power through a material.Thus, the larger the optical depth, the smaller the amount of transmitted radiant power through the material. Spectral optical depth or spectral optical thickness is the natural logarithm of the ratio of incident to transmitted spectral radiant power through a material. Optical depth is dimensionless, and in particular is not a length, though it is a  monotonically increasing function of optical path length, and approaches zero as the path length approaches zero.

In software quality assurance, performance testing is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload. It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.Performance testing, a subset of performance engineering, is a computer science practice which strives to build performance standards into the implementation, design and architecture of a system.Testing typesLoad testing Load testing is the simplest form of performance testing. A load test is usually conducted to understand the behavior of the system under a specific expected load.

Mariner-H ( Mariner Mars '71 ) , also commonly known as Mariner 8 , was ( along with Mariner 9 ) one of two NASA Mariner 960-class space probes launched to Mars . Mariners 4, 5 and 8 were built by aerospace contractors in the United States, and Mariner 9 and Mariner 8 were the first spacecraft to be designed to land on the Martian surface, with Mariner 8 the first spacecraft to achieve that feat. [1]
Mariner-H ( Mariner Mars 1971) was a Mars orbiter space probe which carried six experiments to Mars.

May 10 - Henry III becomes king of the Germans
August 26 - King Bolesław I of Poland is defeated and captured by his brother Zbygniew. Bolesław is taken to Kievan Rus, where he is eventually killed. Huang Zhong is killed in the battle of Gaoping (Kaifeng).

Year 1358 ( MCCCLVIII ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. July 19 - Battle of Bautzen: Albert III Achilles is defeated by his brother John of Saxony. July 26 - King Louis I of Hungary dies. September 15 - John II succeeds his uncle Louis I as king of Hungary . November 26 - King Casimir III of Poland signs the peace treaty of Toruń with Grand Duke Vitovt . Batu Khan captures the Golden Horde after defeating Tokhtamysh. Henry VI of Germany captures Milan.

The Cross of Gold speech was delivered by William Jennings Bryan , a former United States Representative from Nebraska , at the 1896 Democratic National Convention . He delivered his speech in Chicago , Illinois , on July 9, 1896, in which he criticized the McKinley tariff , which had raised the tariff rates and was the subject of considerable debate and protest at the time. The speech also established Bryan's image as a crusader against corporate power and in support of free silver . The Cross of Gold speech is the most notable speech of the Populist movement .

Year 1422 ( MCDXXII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. The Invention of the Printing Press took place in this year. Wars in which the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth played the decisive role. After the death of Queen Elizabeth I and the succession of James VI to the English throne, the Scottish Confederation was reorganized as a personal union between England and Scotland. Miguel López de Legazpi claims Cebu from Sultan Lapu-Lapu II and declares it for Spain (founding of the first European settlement in the Philippines).

Bessarabia (; ; ; , Bessarabiya; ; , Bessarabiya; , Besarabiya) is a historical region in Eastern Europe, bounded by the Dniester river on the east and the Prut river on the west. About two thirds of Bessarabia lies within modern-day Moldova, with the Ukrainian Budjak region covering the southern coastal region and part of the Ukrainian Chernivtsi Oblast covering a small area in the north.In the aftermath of the Russo-Turkish War (1806–1812), and the ensuing Peace of Bucharest, the eastern parts of the Principality of Moldavia, an Ottoman vassal, along with some areas formerly under direct Ottoman rule, were ceded to Imperial Russia.

EventsJanuary–March January 20 – The Parliament of England ( under Tory dominance ) limits the size of the country 's armies in the so-called Triennial Act , a measure designed to prevent standing armies from becoming a threat to the ruling monarch. January 20 – Pope Paul IV issues the Papal bull Regimini militantis ecclesiae ( On the Militant Church ), a condemnation of the Church of England and a declaration that England's monarch must convert to Roman Catholicism. January 20 – The English Parliament passes the Act of Apprentices , a measure designed to curb the spread of Huguenot immigration.

Events  January–June  January 3 – The Long Parliament adopts the Directory for Public Worship in England, Wales, Ireland and Scotland, replacing the Book of Common Prayer (1559). Holy Days (other than Sundays) are not to be observed. January 10 – Archbishop of Canterbury William Laud is executed for treason on Tower Hill, London. January 14 – English Civil War: Fairfax is appointed Commander-in-Chief. January 29 – English Civil War: Armistice talks open at Uxbridge. February 2 – Battle of Inverlochy: The Covenanters are defeated by Montrose.

The standard circulating coinage of the United Kingdom, British Crown Dependencies and British Overseas Territories is denominated in pounds sterling (symbol "£"), and ranges in value from one penny to two pounds. Since decimalisation, on 15 February 1971, the pound has been divided into 100 (new) pence. Before decimalisation, twelve pence made a shilling, and twenty shillings made a pound. British coins are minted by the Royal Mint in Llantrisant, Wales. The Royal Mint also commissions the coins' designs.In addition to the circulating coinage, the UK also mints commemorative decimal coins (crowns) in the denomination of five pounds.

Year 1355 (MCCCLV) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 6 – Charles IV of Bohemia is crowned with the Iron Crown of Lombardy as King of Italy in Milan. January 7 – King Alphonso IV of Portugal sends three men who kill Inês de Castro, beloved of his son Peter, who revolts and incites a civil war. February 10 – St Scholastica Day riot in Oxford, England, breaks out, leaving 63 scholars and perhaps 30 locals dead in two days.

Events <onlyinclude>January–March  January 5 – King Charles II of England gives the title Duke of St Albans to Charles Beauclerk, his illegitimate son by Nell Gwyn. January 15 (January 5 O.S.) - To demonstrate that the River Thames, frozen solid during the Great Frost that started in December, is safe to walk upon, "a Coach and six horses drove over the Thames for a wager" and within three days "whole streets of Booths are built on the Thames and thousands of people are continually walking thereon." Sir Richard Newdigate, 2nd Baronet, records the events in his diary.

Greyhound racing is an organized , competitive sport in which greyhounds are raced around a track . There are two forms of racing. The first is Sprint Racing in which two dogs start together and the one reaching the finish line first is the winner . The second form is Long Distance racing where one dog is set off at intervals to run one race at a time . Greyhound Racing has been a popular sport throughout the US since 1900’s and was first seen in the UK as early as 1926 . Greyhound racing is often called “The Sport of Queens” and there are many reasons why.

Observations show that the expansion of the universe is accelerating , such that the velocity at which a distant galaxy is receding from an observer, c, approaches a value greater than c as the distance to the galaxy becomes larger. The observed acceleration was first noted by the Russian-American astronomer Vesto Slipher in the 1910s. Since then measurements have been made from a wide variety of objects including distant stars, supernovae and clusters of galaxies. The accelerating expansion was discovered in 1998 with the use of the redshift of the light from these distant galaxies.

Juggling is a physical skill, performed by a juggler, involving the manipulation of objects for recreation, entertainment, art or sport. The most recognizable form of juggling is toss juggling. Juggling can be the manipulation of one object or many objects at the same time, most often using one or two hands but also possible with feet. Jugglers often refer to the objects they juggle as props. The most common props are balls, clubs, or rings. Some jugglers use more dramatic objects such as knives, fire torches or chainsaws.

Year 1136 ( MCXXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. March 12 - Edward the Confessor is crowned king of England, in Westminster Abbey; his reign is to endow Westminster Abbey, Winchester Cathedral and other churches throughout England with treasures. March 14 - The English city of London is devastated by a fire. It is later determined that the flames were caused by lightning. June 6 - In England, the first known reference to St George's Day (the patron saint of England) occurs in a record of a feast.

A shank is a type of knot that is used to shorten a rope or take up slack , such as on a boat line or a rope used in mooring . It may consist of a short section of rope, often a loop or figure eight (square knot) with the free end of the rope secured in a manner that prevents its slippage. "shank" or "shanks" may refer to a knot, or a method for attaching a knot. It may also refer to a short metal bar with a rounded or fluted end that is used to sharpen knives.

Hide-and-seek is a popular children's game in which at least two players (usually at least three) conceal themselves in a set environment, to be found by one or more seekers. The game is played by one chosen player (designated as being "it") counting to a predetermined number with eyes closed while the other players hide. After reaching this number, the player who is "it" calls "Ready or not, here I come!" or "Coming, ready or not!" and then attempts to locate all concealed players.The game can end in one of several ways.

Year 1239 ( MCCXXXIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Mansur ibn Ishaq becomes ruler of the Almoravid Dynasty. Friday, June 17 – The Almoravid commander, Ibn Tashfin, enters Marrakesh and becomes its ruler. March 29 – Conrad I is elected anti-king of the Lombard Kingdom. May 29 – Conrad I is defeated and imprisoned by Frederick I of Germany at Pavia. July 15 – Battle of the Ría de Pontevedra: Afonso VII of Galicia and Alfonso I of Portugal defeat the Muslim invaders.

Year 1140 ( MCXL ) was a leap year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Magnus I becomes King of Sweden. The first crusaders invade Byzantium, taking the capital, Constantinople, without meeting serious opposition. After a year of plunder and pillage in Byzantium, the crusaders sack and burn the city, killing many of its inhabitants, including all the men of military age, on June 23. The Byzantine Emperor Alexius III is captured and blinded; he is later released and restored to power by Alexius IV.

1166 (MCLXVI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) asks Venice to help pay the costs of defending Sicily, whose Norman rulers have had good relations with Venice. Doge Vitale II Michiel refuses to pay the requested subsidy. Manuel begins to cultivate relationships with the main commercial rivals of Venice: Genoa and Pisa. He grants them their own trade quarters in Constantinople, very near to the Venetian settlements. Europe  May 7 – King William I (the Wicked) of Sicily dies at Palermo after a 12-year reign.

Events  January–March  January 7 – the Republic of Genoa forbids the unauthorized printing of newspapers and all handwriten newssheets. The ban is lifted after three months. January 12 – Scottish minister James Renwick, one of the Covenanters resisting the Scottish government's suppression of alternate religious views, publishes the Declaration of Lanark. January 21 – The Ottoman Empire army is mobilized in preparation for a war against Austria that culminates with the 1683 Battle of Vienna. January 24 – The first public theater in Brussels, the Opéra du Quai au Foin, is opened.

Events  January–June  January 18 – François, Duke of Anjou, attacks Antwerp. February 4 – Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg, newly converted to Calvinism, formally marries Agnes von Mansfeld-Eisleben, a former canoness of Gerresheim, while retaining his position as Archbishop-Elector of Cologne. March 10 – The Queen Elizabeth's Men troupe of actors is ordered to be founded in England. May – Battle of Shizugatake in Japan: Shibata Katsuie is defeated by Toyotomi Hideyoshi, who goes on to commence construction of Osaka Castle. May 22 – Ernest of Bavaria is elected as Roman Catholic Archbishop of Cologne, in opposition to Gebhard Truchsess von Waldburg.

Year 1429 (MCDXXIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  February 12 – Battle of Rouvray (or "of the Herrings"): English forces under Sir John Fastolf defend a supply convoy, which is carrying rations (food) to the army of William de la Pole, 4th Earl of Suffolk at Orléans, from attack by the Comte de Clermont and John Stewart. April 29 – Siege of Orléans: Joan of Arc enters Orléans with a relief expedition. May 7 – The Tourelles, the last English siege fortification at Orléans, falls.

A conjugate acid, within the Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, is a  chemical compound formed when an acid donates a proton (H+) to a base—in other words, it is a base with a hydrogen ion added to it, as in the reverse reaction it loses a hydrogen ion. On the other hand, a conjugate base is what is left over after an acid has donated a proton during a chemical reaction. Hence, a conjugate base is a species formed by the removal of a proton from an acid, as in the reverse reaction it is able to gain a hydrogen ion.

The Motorola MC68010 processor is a 16/32-bit microprocessor from Motorola, released in 1982 as the successor to the Motorola 68000. It fixes several small flaws in the 68000, and adds a few features.The 68010 is pin-compatible with the 68000, but is not 100% software compatible. Some of the differences were: The MOVE from SR instruction is now privileged (it may only be executed in supervisor mode). This means that the 68010 meets Popek and Goldberg virtualization requirements. Because the 68000 offers an unprivileged MOVE from SR, it does not meet them.
